{{Boris Johnson sidebar}}
'''Alexander Boris de Pfeffel Johnson''' (born 19 June 1964) is a British politician and writer who served as [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] and [[Leader of the Conservative Party (UK)|Leader of the Conservative Party]] from 2019 to 2022. He was previously [[Foreign Secretary]] from 2016 to 2018 and [[Mayor of London]] from 2008 to 2016. He was [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Henley (UK Parliament constituency)|Henley]] from 2001 to 2008 and for [[Uxbridge and South Ruislip]] from 2015 to 2023.

In his youth Johnson attended [[Eton College]] and [[Balliol College, Oxford]], and he was elected [[president of the Oxford Union]] in 1986. In 1989 he began writing for ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', and from 1999 to 2005 he was the editor of ''[[The Spectator]]''. He became a member of the [[Shadow Cabinet of Michael Howard]] in 2001 before being dismissed over a claim that he had lied about an extramarital affair. After Howard resigned Johnson became a member of [[David Cameron]]'s [[Shadow Cabinet of David Cameron|Shadow Cabinet]]. He was [[2008 London mayoral election|elected mayor of London in 2008]] and [[Resignation from the House of Commons of the United Kingdom|resigned from the House of Commons]] to focus his attention on the mayoralty. He was [[2012 London mayoral election|re-elected mayor in 2012]], but did not run for re-election [[2016 London mayoral election|in 2016]]. At the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]] he was elected MP for Uxbridge and South Ruislip. Johnson was a prominent figure in the [[Vote Leave|Brexit campaign]] in the [[2016 EU membership referendum]]. After the referendum Prime Minister [[Theresa May]] appointed him foreign secretary. He resigned from the position in 2018 in protest at both the [[Chequers Agreement]] and May's approach to Brexit.

Johnson succeeded May as prime minister. He [[Brexit negotiations in 2019|re-opened Brexit negotiations]] with the EU and in early September [[2019 British prorogation controversy|he prorogued Parliament]]; the [[Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|Supreme Court]] later ruled the prorogation to have been unlawful. After agreeing to a revised [[Brexit withdrawal agreement]] but [[Parliamentary votes on Brexit|failing to win parliamentary support]], Johnson called [[2019 United Kingdom general election|a snap general election]] to be held in December 2019, in which he won a [[landslide victory]]. During [[Johnson's premiership]], the government [[British government response to the COVID-19 pandemic|responded to the COVID-19 pandemic]] by introducing various [[Coronavirus Act 2020|emergency powers]] to mitigate its impact and approved [[COVID-19 vaccination in the United Kingdom|a nationwide vaccination programme]]. He also [[United Kingdom and the Russian invasion of Ukraine|responded to the Russian invasion of Ukraine]] by imposing [[International sanctions during the Russian invasion of Ukraine|sanctions on Russia]] and authorising [[List of military aid to Ukraine during the Russo-Ukrainian War|foreign aid and weapons shipments]] to Ukraine.<ref>{{Cite news |date=29 June 2022 |title=UK Gives £1 Billion to Ukraine to Help Fund Offensive Operations |work=Bloomberg.com |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-06-29/uk-gives-1-billion-to-ukraine-to-help-fund-offensive-operations |access-date=7 July 2022 }}</ref> In the [[Partygate]] scandal it was found that numerous parties had been held at [[10 Downing Street]] during [[COVID-19 lockdown in the United Kingdom|national COVID-19 lockdowns]], and COVID-19 social distancing laws were breached by 83 individuals, including Johnson, who in April 2022 was issued with a [[fixed penalty notice]]. The publishing of the [[Sue Gray report]] in May 2022 and a widespread sense of dissatisfaction led in June 2022 to a [[2022 vote of confidence in the Conservative Party leadership of Boris Johnson|vote of confidence in his leadership]] amongst Conservative MPs, which he won. In July 2022, revelations over [[Chris Pincher scandal|his appointment of Chris Pincher]] as [[Deputy Chief Whip|deputy chief whip]] of the party while knowing of allegations of sexual misconduct against him led to a [[July 2022 United Kingdom government crisis|mass resignation of members of his government]] and to Johnson announcing his resignation as prime minister. He was succeeded as prime minister by [[Liz Truss]], his foreign secretary. He remained in the House of Commons as a [[backbencher]] until June 2023, when he received the draft of the [[Commons Privileges Committee investigation into Boris Johnson|Commons Privileges Committee investigation into his conduct]] that unanimously found that he had lied to the Commons on numerous occasions. Johnson resigned his position as MP the same day.

[[Public image of Boris Johnson|Johnson is a controversial figure]] in British politics. His supporters have praised him for being humorous, witty and entertaining, with an appeal reaching beyond traditional Conservative Party voters, viewing him as an electoral asset to the party. Conversely, his critics have accused him of lying, [[elitism]], [[cronyism]] and [[bigotry]]. During his premiership his supporters praised him for "[[Get Brexit Done|getting Brexit done]]", overseeing the UK's COVID-19 vaccination programme, which was amongst the fastest in the world, and being one of the first world leaders to offer [[List of humanitarian aid to Ukraine during the Russo-Ukrainian War|humanitarian support to Ukraine]] following the Russian invasion of the country. His tenure also encompassed several controversies and scandals, and is viewed as the most scandalous premiership of modern times by historians and biographers alike.

{{TOC limit}}

==Early life and education==
===Childhood===
Alexander Boris de Pfeffel Johnson was born on 19 June 1964 in the [[Upper East Side]] of [[Manhattan]], New York City,<ref>{{cite news |last=Lawless |first=Jill |date=23 July 2019 |title=Boris Johnson's Chaotic Path to Power Finally Pays Off |work=[[Associated Press]] |url=https://apnews.com/b48561749c65479fbadbcdc35808343a |access-date=31 July 2019 |archive-date=31 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190731085804/https://apnews.com/b48561749c65479fbadbcdc35808343a |url-status=live}}</ref>{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1p=10|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=1}} to [[Stanley Johnson (writer)|Stanley Johnson]], then studying economics at [[Columbia University]],{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1p=11|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=2}} and [[Charlotte Johnson Wahl|Charlotte Fawcett]],<ref name="telegraph.co.uk">{{cite news |last=Llewellyn Smith |first=Julia |date=18 May 2008 |title=Boris Johnson, by his mother Charlotte Johnson Wahl |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/borisjohnson/1976150/Boris-Johnson-by-his-mother-Charlotte-Johnson-Wahl.html |url-status=dead |work=[[The Sunday Telegraph]] |location=London |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110123154217/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/borisjohnson/1976150/Boris-Johnson-by-his-mother-Charlotte-Johnson-Wahl.html |archive-date=23 January 2011 |access-date=16 April 2020 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> an artist, whose father [[James Fawcett (barrister)|Sir James Fawcett]], was a prominent [[barrister]] and president of the [[European Commission of Human Rights]] from 1972 to 1981.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/borisjohnson/1924866/London-mayor-elections-2008-Family-of-influence-behind-Boris-Johnson.html | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Family of influence behind Boris Johnson | date=3 May 2008 | access-date=6 May 2010 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110123154101/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/borisjohnson/1924866/London-mayor-elections-2008-Family-of-influence-behind-Boris-Johnson.html | archive-date=23 January 2011 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Johnson is one of only two British prime ministers to have been an [[Birthright citizenship in the United States|American citizen]] {{crossreference|(see [[Honorary citizenship of the United States]])}}.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Frost |first=Amanda |title=Everyone born in the United States is a U.S. citizen. Here's why. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/made-by-history/2023/03/28/birthright-citizenship-supreme-court/ |newspaper=The Washington Post |access-date=3 November 2023 |archive-date=2 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230602053231/https://www.washingtonpost.com/made-by-history/2023/03/28/birthright-citizenship-supreme-court/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Citizen of the United States, 1963 |url=https://www.nationalchurchillmuseum.org/citizen-of-the-united-states.html |website=National Churchill Museum |access-date=3 November 2023 |archive-date=3 November 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231103003715/https://www.nationalchurchillmuseum.org/citizen-of-the-united-states.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Johnson's parents returned to the UK in September 1964 so Charlotte could study at the [[University of Oxford]].{{sfnm|1a1=Edwards|1a2=Isaby|1y=2008|1p=44|2a1=Purnell|2y=2011|2pp=12–13|3a1=Gimson|3y=2012|3p=11}} She lived with her son in [[Summertown, Oxford]], and in September 1965 she gave birth to a daughter, [[Rachel Johnson|Rachel]].{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=13}} In July 1965, the family moved to [[Crouch End]] in [[north London]],{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=14}} and in February 1966 they relocated to Washington, DC, where Stanley worked with the [[World Bank]].{{sfnm|1a1=Edwards|1a2=Isaby|1y=2008|1p=44|2a1=Purnell|2y=2011|2p=16|3a1=Gimson|3y=2012|3p=14}} Stanley then took a job with a policy panel on [[population control]], and moved the family to [[Norwalk, Connecticut]], in June.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=16}} A third child, Leo, was born in September 1967.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1p=15|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=14}}

[[File:Ashdown House - geograph.org.uk - 1691918.jpg|thumb|left|[[Ashdown House, East Sussex|Ashdown House]] preparatory school, East Sussex, attended by Johnson from 1975 to 1977]]

The family returned to the UK in 1969, and lived at West Nethercote Farm, Somerset, Stanley's family home in [[Exmoor]].{{sfnm|1a1=Edwards|1a2=Isaby|1y=2008|1p=44|2a1=Purnell|2y=2011|2p=17|3a1=Gimson|3y=2012|3p=17, 20–22}} His father was regularly absent, leaving Johnson to be raised largely by his mother, assisted by [[au pair]]s.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1p=18|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=25}} As a child, Johnson was quiet, studious,{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=14}} and deaf, resulting in several operations to insert [[Tympanostomy tube|grommets]] into his ears.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1p=13|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=11}} He and his siblings were encouraged to engage in intellectual activities from a young age.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1p=26|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=18}} Johnson's earliest recorded ambition was to be "world king".{{sfnm|1a1=Edwards|1a2=Isaby|1y=2008|1p=45|2a1=Purnell|2y=2011|2p=28|3a1=Gimson|3y=2012|3pp=17–18}} Having no other friends, the siblings became very close.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=28–29}}

In late 1969, the family moved to [[Maida Vale]] in west London, while Stanley began post-graduate research at the [[London School of Economics]].{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=29}} In 1970 Charlotte and the children briefly returned to Nethercote, where Johnson attended Winsford Village School, before returning to London to settle in [[Primrose Hill]],{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=30}} where they were educated at Primrose Hill Primary School.{{sfnm|1a1=Edwards|1a2=Isaby|1y=2008|1p=44|2a1=Purnell|2y=2011|2p=30|3a1=Gimson|3y=2012|3p=26}} A fourth child, [[Jo Johnson|Joseph]], was born in late 1971.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=31}}

After Stanley secured employment at the [[European Commission]] in April 1973, he moved his family to [[Uccle]], Brussels, where Johnson attended the [[European School, Brussels&nbsp;I]] and learnt to speak French.{{sfnm|1a1=Edwards|1a2=Isaby|1y=2008|1p=44|2a1=Purnell|2y=2011|2pp=31–32|3a1=Gimson|3y=2012|3p=26}}<ref>{{cite news |last=Johnson |first=Stanley |author-link=Stanley Johnson (writer) |title=Stanley Johnson: Why I remain a fan of Brussels |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/europe/belgium/brussels/articles/stanley-johnson-why-i-remain-a-fan-of-brussels/ |url-status=live |url-access=limited |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |location=London |date=18 June 2016 |access-date=5 May 2021 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20160701222600/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/europe/belgium/brussels/articles/stanley-johnson-why-i-remain-a-fan-of-brussels/ |archive-date=1 July 2016}}</ref> Charlotte had a [[nervous breakdown]] and was hospitalised with depression, after which Johnson and his siblings were sent back to the UK in 1975 to attend [[Ashdown House, East Sussex|Ashdown House]], a preparatory boarding school in East Sussex.{{sfnm|1a1=Edwards|1a2=Isaby|1y=2008|1p=44|2a1=Purnell|2y=2011|2pp=33–35|3a1=Gimson|3y=2012|3pp=27–29}} There, he developed interests in [[Rugby football|rugby]], [[Ancient Greek]], and [[Latin]].{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1p=42|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2pp=30–31}} In December 1978 his parents' relationship broke down; they divorced in 1980,{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=36, 42}} and Charlotte moved to [[Notting Hill]], London, where her children joined her for much of their time.{{sfnm|1a1=Edwards|1a2=Isaby|1y=2008|1pp=44–45|2a1=Purnell|2y=2011|2pp=38–39|3a1=Gimson|3y=2012|3p=35}}

===Eton and Oxford: 1977–1987===
{{quote box|width=25em|align=right|quote=As a kid I was extremely spotty, extremely nerdy and horribly {{Wikt-lang|en|swotty}}. My idea of a really good time was to travel across London on the tube to visit the [[British Museum]].|author= —&thinsp;Boris Johnson{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=49}} }}

[[File:Oxford - Balliol College - geograph.org.uk - 1329613.jpg|thumb|right|Johnson studied Classics at [[Balliol College, Oxford]].]]

Johnson gained a [[King's Scholar]]ship to study at [[Eton College]], a boarding school near [[Windsor, Berkshire]].{{sfnm|1a1=Edwards|1a2=Isaby|1y=2008|1p=44|2a1=Purnell|2y=2011|2p=42}} Arriving in the autumn term of 1977,{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=45}} he began going by his middle name Boris,<ref>{{cite web|title=The 10 ages of Boris Johnson: a guide to his road to power|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/21/boris-johnson-route-to-number-10|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Sonia|first=Purnell|date=21 July 2019|access-date=30 July 2022|archive-date=11 July 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220711204147/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/21/boris-johnson-route-to-number-10|url-status=live}}</ref> and developed "the eccentric English persona" for which he became famous.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=47–48}} He denounced Catholicism and joined the [[Church of England]].{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=48}} School reports complained about his idleness, complacency, and lateness,{{sfnm|1a1=Edwards|1a2=Isaby|1y=2008|1p=44|2a1=Purnell|2y=2011|2pp=50–51|3a1=Gimson|3y=2012|3pp=41–44}} but he was popular at Eton.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=47–48}}

Johnson's friends were largely from the wealthy upper classes; his best friends were [[Darius Guppy]] and [[Charles Spencer, 9th Earl Spencer|Charles Spencer]]. Both would go on to accompany him at the [[University of Oxford]] and remained his friends into adulthood.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=53}} Johnson excelled in [[English studies|English]] and the [[Classics]], winning prizes in both,{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=49–50}} and became secretary of the school [[debating society]]{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=55}} and editor of the school newspaper.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=49, 53}} In late 1981 he became a member of [[Eton Society|''Pop'']],{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=54–55|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2pp=51–52}} a small, self-selecting elite group of school prefects. After leaving Eton, Johnson went on a [[gap year]] to Australia, where he taught English and Latin at [[Timbertop]], an [[Outward Bound]]-inspired campus of [[Geelong Grammar]], an independent boarding school.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=58–59}}<ref>{{Cite news |last=Bunbury |first=Stephanie |date=17 August 2013 |title=Boris Johnson and the right to write |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/books/boris-johnson-and-the-right-to-write-20130815-2ryy9.html |access-date=12 January 2018 |archive-date=13 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180113041055/http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/books/boris-johnson-and-the-right-to-write-20130815-2ryy9.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Johnston |first=Chris |date=15 July 2016 |title=When Boris was just another Timbertop Rent-A-Pom |work=[[The Border Mail]] |url=http://www.bordermail.com.au/story/4033888/when-boris-was-just-another-timbertop-rent-a-pom/?cs=4067 |access-date=12 January 2018 |archive-date=13 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180113035552/http://www.bordermail.com.au/story/4033888/when-boris-was-just-another-timbertop-rent-a-pom/?cs=4067 |url-status=live }}</ref>

Johnson won a scholarship to read ''[[Literae humaniores]]'' at [[Balliol College, Oxford]], a four-year course in Classics, ancient languages, literature, history, and philosophy.{{sfnm|1a1=Edwards|1a2=Isaby|1y=2008|1p=45|2a1=Purnell|2y=2011|2p=57|3a1=Gimson|3y=2012|3p=83}} [[Matriculating]] in late 1983,{{sfn|Gimson|2012|p=56}} he was one of a generation of Oxford undergraduates who dominated British politics and media in the early 21st century, including Cameron, [[William Hague]], [[Michael Gove]], [[Jeremy Hunt]] and [[Nick Boles]].{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=62}} While at Oxford, Johnson joined the college's [[rugby union]] team as a [[tighthead prop]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Johnson |first=Boris |title=Friends, Voters, Countrymen: Jottings on the Stump |publisher=[[HarperCollins]] |year=2001 |isbn=0007119135 |location=London |pages=151}}</ref> To his later regret, he joined the [[Bullingdon Club]], an exclusive drinking society notorious for vandalism.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=63–65|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2pp=63–66}}<ref>{{Cite news |date=28 May 2013 |title=David Dimbleby Slams 'Disgraceful' Boris Johnson For Ruining Bullingdon Club |work=[[HuffPost]] |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2013/05/28/david-dimbleby-bullingdon-club-boris-johnson_n_3345077.html |access-date=29 May 2014 |url-status=live |archive-date=11 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181211065921/https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2013/05/28/david-dimbleby-bullingdon-club-boris-johnson_n_3345077.html }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Kingsley |first=Patrick |date=10 August 2011 |title=UK riots: how do Boris Johnson's Bullingdon antics compare? |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2011/aug/10/uk-riots-boris-johnson |access-date=29 May 2014 |url-status=live |archive-date=6 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206061641/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2011/aug/10/uk-riots-boris-johnson }}</ref> Many years later, [[1987 Bullingdon Club photograph|a group photograph]] including himself and Cameron in Bullingdon Club formal dress led to much negative press coverage. While at Oxford, he began a relationship with [[Allegra Mostyn-Owen]], cover girl for ''[[Tatler]]'' magazine and daughter of [[Christie's Education]] chairman [[William Mostyn-Owen]]. They became engaged.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=72, 74–78|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2pp=76–83}}

Johnson was popular and well known at Oxford.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1p=70|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=60}} Alongside Guppy, he edited the university's satirical magazine ''Tributary''.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1p=68|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=74}} In 1984, Johnson was elected secretary of the [[Oxford Union]],{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=70–71}} and campaigned unsuccessfully for the position of [[List of Presidents of the Oxford Union|Union President]].{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=71–73}} In 1986, Johnson ran successfully for President,{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=80–81}} but his term was not distinguished or memorable,{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=84}} and questions were raised regarding his competence and seriousness.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=87}} At graduation, Johnson was awarded an [[Upper second-class honours|upper second-class]] degree,{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=89–90|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=84}}<ref>{{Cite news |last=Barber |first=Lyn |date=5 October 2003 |title=Charmed, I'm Sure |work=The Guardian |location=London |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2003/oct/05/pressandpublishing.politicsphilosophyandsociety |access-date=8 April 2020 |archive-date=6 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206061733/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2003/oct/05/pressandpublishing.politicsphilosophyandsociety |url-status=live }}</ref> and was deeply unhappy he did not receive a first.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=92}}

==Early career==
===''The Times'' and ''The Daily Telegraph'': 1987–1994===

In September 1987, Johnson and Mostyn-Owen married.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=92–94|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2pp=85–86}} They settled in [[West Kensington]], London.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=94}} In late 1987, through family connections, he began work as a graduate trainee at ''[[The Times]]''.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=95–99|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2pp=88–90}} Scandal erupted when Johnson wrote an article for the newspaper on the archaeological discovery of [[Edward II]]'s palace, having invented a quote which he falsely attributed to the historian [[Colin Lucas]], his godfather. After the paper's editor, [[Charles Wilson (journalist)|Charles Wilson]], learnt of the matter, he dismissed Johnson.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=100–102|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2pp=90–96}}

Johnson secured employment on the lead-writing desk of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', having met its editor, [[Max Hastings]], while at university.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=102–103|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=97}} His articles appealed to the newspaper's Conservative-voting "[[Middle England]]" readership,{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=108}} and he was known for his distinctive literary style, replete with old-fashioned phrasing and for regularly referring to the readership as "my friends".{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=106–107}} In early 1989, Johnson was appointed to the newspaper's Brussels bureau to report on the European Commission,{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=109}} remaining in the post until 1994.<ref name="Fletcher">{{cite news |last=Fletcher |first=Martin |date=4 November 2017 |title=The joke's over – how Boris Johnson is damaging Britain's global stature |work=[[New Statesman]] |url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2017/11/joke-s-over-how-boris-johnson-damaging-britain-s-global-stature |access-date=7 November 2017 |archive-date=6 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206063009/https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2017/11/joke-s-over-how-boris-johnson-damaging-britain-s-global-stature |url-status=live}}</ref> A strong critic of the integrationist Commission president [[Jacques Delors]], he established himself as one of the city's few [[Eurosceptic]] journalists.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=115–116}} He wrote articles about [[euromyths]]: that Brussels had recruited sniffer dogs to ensure that all manure smelt the same,{{sfn|Bower|2021|pp=68, 627}} they were about to dictate the acceptable curve of British bananas,{{efn|[[Commission Regulation (EC) No. 2257/94]] introduced the requirement for bananas to be "free from malformation or abnormal curvature"; different standards applied to different classes of banana.<ref>{{cite news |last=Henley |first=Jon |title=Is the EU really dictating the shape of your bananas? |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/11/boris-johnson-launches-the-vote-leave-battlebus-in-cornwall |date=11 May 2016 |access-date=28 November 2021 |archive-date=18 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220518134152/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/11/boris-johnson-launches-the-vote-leave-battlebus-in-cornwall |url-status=live}}</ref>}} limit the power of their vacuum cleaners<ref>{{cite news |last=Henley |first=Jon |title=Is the EU really dictating the shape of your bananas? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/11/boris-johnson-launches-the-vote-leave-battlebus-in-cornwall |url-status=live |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=11 May 2016 |access-date=8 November 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220518134152/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/11/boris-johnson-launches-the-vote-leave-battlebus-in-cornwall |archive-date=18 May 2022}}</ref>{{efn|The EU introduced limits on the power of vacuum cleaners in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |last=Smithers |first=Rebecca |date=21 August 2014 |title=EU ban on powerful vacuum cleaners prompts anger and legal challenge |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/aug/21/anger-as-eu-bans-most-powerful-vacuum-cleaners |access-date=28 November 2021 |archive-date=28 November 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211128200311/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/aug/21/anger-as-eu-bans-most-powerful-vacuum-cleaners |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Dallison |first=Paul |date=23 February 2016 |title=Boris Johnson's 11 best Europe moments |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/the-eu-is-a-lobster-boris-johnson-best-moments-europe-reporting/ |access-date=28 November 2021 |website=Politico Europe |archive-date=28 November 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211128200309/https://www.politico.eu/article/the-eu-is-a-lobster-boris-johnson-best-moments-europe-reporting/ |url-status=live}}</ref>}} and order women to return their old sex toys.{{sfn|Bower|2021|pp=68, 627}} He wrote that euro notes made people impotent and that a plan to blow up the [[Berlaymont building]] was in place because asbestos cladding made the building too dangerous to inhabit.{{sfn|Bower|2021|pp=68, 627}} Many of his fellow journalists were critical of his articles, saying they often contained lies designed to discredit the commission.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=121, 126|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2pp=98–99, 100–101}} The Europhile Conservative politician [[Chris Patten]] later said that Johnson was "one of the greatest exponents of fake journalism".<ref name="Fletcher" /> Johnson opposed banning handguns after the [[Dunblane school massacre]], writing in his column "Nanny is confiscating their toys. It is like one of those vast [[Compulsory sterilization#India|Indian programmes of compulsory vasectomy]]."<ref>{{cite web|date=25 March 2021|title=Boris Johnson handgun quote is real|url=https://fullfact.org/online/boris-johnson-dunblane-guns/|access-date=10 October 2021|website=Full Fact|archive-date=8 June 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220608071851/https://fullfact.org/online/boris-johnson-dunblane-guns/|url-status=live}}</ref>

According to one of his biographers, [[Sonia Purnell]], – who was Johnson's Brussels deputy<ref name="Fletcher" /> – he helped make Euroscepticism "an attractive and emotionally resonant cause for the Right", whereas it had been associated previously with the Left.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=115}} Johnson's articles exacerbated tensions between the Conservative Party's Eurosceptic and Europhile factions. As a result, he earned the mistrust of many party members.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=124}} His writings were also a key influence on the emergence of the eurosceptic [[UK Independence Party]] (UKIP) in the early 1990s.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=115}} [[Conrad Black]], then proprietor of ''The Daily Telegraph'', said Johnson "was such an effective correspondent for us in Brussels that he greatly influenced British opinion on this country's relations with Europe".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Black |first=Conrad |date=29 June 2019 |title=Max Hastings vs Boris Johnson: I know who I'd trust more |url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/article/battle-of-hastings |access-date=9 April 2020 |website=[[The Spectator]] |archive-date=31 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220331165808/https://www.spectator.co.uk/article/battle-of-hastings |url-status=live }}</ref>

In February 1990 Johnson's wife Allegra broke up with him; after several attempts at reconciliation, their marriage ended in April 1993.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=129–130, 134|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2pp=107–111, 113–114}}<ref name=guardian200218/> He began a relationship with childhood friend [[Marina Wheeler]], who had moved to Brussels in 1990.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=130–133|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2pp=111–114}} They were married in May 1993.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1p=134|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2pp=114–115}} Soon after, Marina gave birth to a daughter.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1p=135|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=115}} Johnson and his new wife settled in [[Islington]], north London,{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=142}} an area known for its association with the left-liberal [[intelligentsia]]. Under the influence of this ''milieu'' and of his wife, Johnson moved in a more liberal direction on issues such as [[climate change]], [[LGBT rights]] and race relations.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=144, 148}} While in Islington, the couple had three more children, all given the surname Johnson-Wheeler.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1p=143|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=125}} They were sent to the local Canonbury Primary School and then to private secondary schools.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=146–147}} Devoting much time to his children, Johnson wrote a book of verse, ''The Perils of the Pushy Parents: A Cautionary Tale'', which was published to largely poor reviews.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=153}}

===Political columnist: 1994–1999===
Back in London, Hastings turned down Johnson's request to become a [[war reporter]],{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=139–140}} instead promoting him to assistant editor and chief political columnist.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1p=161|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=124}} Johnson's column received praise for being ideologically eclectic and distinctively written, and earned him Commentator of the Year Award at the ''[[What the Papers Say]]'' awards.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1p=168|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=125}} Some critics condemned his writing style as bigotry; in columns he used the words "[[piccaninnies]]" and "[[watermelon smiles]]" when referring to Africans, championed European colonialism in Uganda{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=169}}<ref>{{cite news |last=Johnson |first=Boris |date=10 January 2002 |title=If Blair's so good at running the Congo, let him stay there |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/0/blairs-good-running-congo-let-stay/ |url-status=live |work=The Daily Telegraph |archive-url=https://archive.today/20201108122710/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/0/blairs-good-running-congo-let-stay/ |archive-date=8 November 2020 |access-date=5 May 2021 |url-access=limited}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Johnson |first=Boris |date=1 September 2005 |title=Getting our knickers in a twist over China |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/personal-view/3619424/Getting-our-knickers-in-a-twist-over-China.html |url-status=live |work=The Daily Telegraph |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200305160557/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/personal-view/3619424/Getting-our-knickers-in-a-twist-over-China.html |archive-date=5 March 2020 |access-date=5 May 2021 |url-access=limited}}</ref> and referred to gay men as "tank-topped bumboys".{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=171}}

In 1993, Johnson outlined his desire to run as a Conservative in the [[1994 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|1994 European Parliament elections]]. [[Andrew Mitchell]] convinced Major not to veto Johnson's candidacy, but Johnson could not find a constituency.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=162–165}} He turned his attention to obtaining a seat in the House of Commons instead. After being rejected as Conservative candidate for [[Holborn and St. Pancras]], he was selected the Conservative candidate for [[Clwyd South (UK Parliament constituency)|Clwyd South]] in north Wales, then a [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] [[safe seat]]. Spending six weeks campaigning, he attained 9,091 votes (23 per cent) in the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]], losing to Labour candidate [[Martyn Jones]].{{sfnm|1a1=Edwards|1a2=Isaby|1y=2008|1p=46|2a1=Purnell|2y=2011|2pp=185–186|3a1=Gimson|3y=2012|3p=125}}

Scandal erupted in June 1995 when a recording of a 1990 telephone conversation between Johnson and his friend [[Darius Guppy]] was made public.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=173–176|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2pp=117–123}} In it, Guppy said that his criminal activities involving insurance fraud were being investigated by ''[[News of the World]]'' journalist Stuart Collier, and he asked Johnson to provide him with Collier's private address, seeking to have the latter beaten. Johnson agreed, although he expressed concern that he would be associated with the attack.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=173–176|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2pp=117–123}} When the phone conversation was published, Johnson stated that ultimately he had not obliged Guppy's request. Hastings reprimanded Johnson but did not dismiss him.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=173–176|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2pp=117–123}}

Johnson was given a regular column in ''[[The Spectator]]'', sister publication to ''The Daily Telegraph'', which attracted mixed reviews and was often thought rushed.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=168}} In 1999, he was also given a column reviewing new cars in the American men's monthly magazine ''[[GQ]]''.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1p=171|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2pp=177–178}} The large number of parking fines that Johnson acquired while testing cars frustrated staff.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=171}} At ''The Daily Telegraph'' and ''The Spectator'', he was consistently late delivering copy, forcing staff to stay late to accommodate him; some related that if they published without his work, he would shout at them with expletives.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=179–181|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=177}}

Johnson's April 1998 appearance on the BBC's satirical current affairs show ''[[Have I Got News for You]]'' brought him national fame.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/29/arts/television/have-i-got-news-for-you-boris-johnson-brexit.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191029104004/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/29/arts/television/have-i-got-news-for-you-boris-johnson-brexit.html |archive-date=29 October 2019 |url-access=limited |url-status=live |title=A Show That Laughs at Boris Johnson, and May Have Aided His Rise|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=29 October 2019 |access-date=10 June 2021|last1=Marshall |first1=Alex }}</ref> He was invited back on to later episodes, including as a guest presenter; for his 2003 appearance, Johnson was nominated for the [[British Academy Television Award for Best Entertainment Performance|BAFTA Television Award for Best Entertainment Performance]].{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=176–178|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2pp=127–129}}<ref>{{Cite web |date=18 April 2020 |title=Television in 2004 – BAFTA Awards |url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2004/television |access-date=3 May 2020 |website=[[BAFTA]] |archive-date=14 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170814063714/http://awards.bafta.org/award/2004/television |url-status=live }}</ref> After these appearances, he came to be recognised on the street, and was invited to appear on other shows, such as ''[[Top Gear (2002 TV series)|Top Gear]]'', ''[[Parkinson (TV series)|Parkinson]]'', ''[[Breakfast with Frost]]'', and ''[[Question Time (TV programme)|Question Time]]''.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1p=178|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=130}}

===''The Spectator'' and MP for Henley: 1999–2008===
In July 1999, Conrad Black offered Johnson the editorship of ''The Spectator'' on the condition he abandon his parliamentary aspirations; Johnson agreed.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1p=188|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=131}} While retaining ''The Spectator''{{'}}s traditional right-wing bent, Johnson welcomed contributions from leftist writers and cartoonists.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=198–199}} Under Johnson's editorship, the magazine's circulation grew by 10% to 62,000 and it became profitable.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=191}} His editorship also drew criticism; some opined that under him ''The Spectator'' avoided serious issues,{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=204}} while colleagues became annoyed that he was regularly absent from the office, meetings, and events.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=192, 194}} He gained a reputation as a poor political pundit because of incorrect political predictions.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=204}} His father-in-law [[Charles Wheeler (journalist)|Charles Wheeler]] and others strongly criticised him for allowing ''Spectator'' columnist [[Taki Theodoracopulos]] to publish racist and antisemitic language.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=193}}<ref>{{Cite news |date=2 April 2008 |title=Boris says sorry over 'blacks have lower IQs' article in the Spectator |work=[[Evening Standard]] |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/boris-says-sorry-over-blacks-have-lower-iqs-article-in-the-spectator-6630340.html |access-date=30 August 2018 |archive-date=31 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831010906/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/boris-says-sorry-over-blacks-have-lower-iqs-article-in-the-spectator-6630340.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

Journalist Charlotte Edwardes wrote in ''The Times'' in 2019 that Johnson had squeezed her thigh at a private lunch at the ''Spectator'' in 1999 and that another woman had told her he had done the same to her. A spokesman denied the allegation.<ref>{{Cite news |date=29 September 2019 |title=No 10 denies Boris Johnson 'thigh squeeze' claim |work=[[BBC News]] |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-49873301 |access-date=29 September 2019 |archive-date=29 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190929190514/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-49873301 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Edwardes|first=Charlotte|date=29 September 2019|title=Charlotte Edwardes on Boris Johnson's wandering hands|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/charlotte-edwardes-on-boris-johnson-s-wandering-hands-hnxnqwbb8|url-access=subscription|access-date=7 August 2021|website=[[The Times]]|archive-date=7 August 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210807164700/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/charlotte-edwardes-on-boris-johnson-s-wandering-hands-hnxnqwbb8|url-status=live}}</ref>

In 2004, Johnson published an editorial in ''The Spectator'' after the murder of [[Ken Bigley]] suggesting that Liverpudlians were wallowing in their victim status and "hooked on grief" over the [[Hillsborough disaster]], which Johnson partly blamed on "drunken fans".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Pidd |first=Helen |date=11 August 2019 |title=PM should apologise for Hillsborough remarks, says Liverpool mayor |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/aug/11/boris-johnson-should-apologise-for-spectator-hillsborough-remarks-says-liverpool-mayor |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=17 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220717173734/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/aug/11/boris-johnson-should-apologise-for-spectator-hillsborough-remarks-says-liverpool-mayor |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Boris sorry for Scouse stereotype |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/3756418.stm |access-date=27 June 2020 |work=BBC News |date=19 October 2004 |archive-date=22 May 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060522110858/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/3756418.stm |url-status=live }}</ref> In an appendix added to a later edition of his 2005 book ''[[The Dream of Rome]]'', [[Tell MAMA]] and the [[Muslim Council of Britain]] criticised Johnson for arguing [[Islam]] has caused the [[Muslim world]] to be "literally centuries behind" the West.<ref name="theguardian">{{Cite news |last=Perraudin |first=Frances |date=15 July 2019 |title=Boris Johnson claimed Islam put Muslim world 'centuries behind' |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/15/boris-johnson-islam-muslim-world-centuries-behind-2007-essay |access-date=27 July 2019 |archive-date=27 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727063050/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/15/boris-johnson-islam-muslim-world-centuries-behind-2007-essay |url-status=live }}</ref>

====Becoming an MP====
{{quote box|width=25em|align=right|quote=The selection of Boris Johnson&nbsp;... confirms the Tory Party's increasing weakness for celebrity personalities over the dreary exigencies of politics. Johnson, for all his gifts, is unlikely to grace any future Tory cabinet. Indeed, he is not known for his excessive interest in serious policy matters, and it is hard to see him grubbing away at administrative detail as an obscure, hardworking junior minister for social security. To maintain his funny man reputation he will no doubt find himself refining his [[Bertie Wooster]] interpretation to the point where the impersonation becomes the man.|author= –Max Hastings, ''London Evening Standard''|source={{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=219}}}}

Following [[Michael Heseltine]]'s retirement, Johnson decided to stand as Conservative candidate for [[Henley (UK Parliament constituency)|Henley]], a Conservative safe seat in [[Oxfordshire]].{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=209–210|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=141}} The local Conservative branch selected him although it was split over Johnson's candidacy. Some thought him amusing and charming while others disliked his flippant attitude and perceived lack of knowledge of the local area.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=211–212}} Assisted by his television fame, Johnson won the seat in the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 general election]].{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=220–221}} Alongside his Islington home, Johnson bought a farmhouse outside [[Thame]] in his new constituency.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=240}} He regularly attended Henley social events and occasionally wrote for the ''[[Henley Standard]]''.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=238}} His constituency surgeries proved popular, and he joined local campaigns to stop the closure of [[Royal Berkshire NHS Foundation Trust|Townlands Hospital]] and the local [[Thames Valley Air Ambulance|air ambulance]].{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=239}}

In Parliament, Johnson was appointed to a [[standing committee]] assessing the [[Proceeds of Crime Act 2002|Proceeds of Crime Bill]], but missed many of its meetings.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=225}} Despite his credentials as a public speaker, his speeches in the House of Commons were widely deemed lacklustre.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=232–233}} He attended around half of Commons votes,{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=230}} usually supporting the Conservative [[party line (politics)|party line]].{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=231}} In [[free votes]], he demonstrated a more socially liberal attitude, supporting the [[Gender Recognition Act 2004]] and the repeal of [[Section 28]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/2664163.stm|title=Section 28 compromise avoids a crisis|date=16 January 2003|work=BBC News|access-date=30 July 2022|archive-date=27 May 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060527114531/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/2664163.stm|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Conservative Revolts">{{cite web|url=http://www.revolts.co.uk/Conservative%20splits.pdf |title=Mapping Conservative Divisions Under Michael Howard |access-date=3 February 2010 |last1=Cowley |first1=Philip |last2=Stuart |first2=Mark |date=19 November 2004 |publisher=Revolts.co.uk |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606033124/http://www.revolts.co.uk/Conservative%20splits.pdf |archive-date=6 June 2011 |url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2001 Johnson had spoken out against plans to repeal Section 28, saying it was "Labour's appalling agenda, encouraging the teaching of homosexuality in schools".<ref>{{cite news |last=Johnson |first=Boris |title=Another voice |url=http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/15th-april-2000/8/another-voice |access-date=6 June 2021 |work=[[The Spectator]] |date=15 April 2000 |page=8 |archive-date=19 May 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210519015210/http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/15th-april-2000/8/another-voice |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Cooper |first=Alex |title=Boris Johnson gets mixed reviews from U.K.'s LGBTQ community |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/feature/nbc-out/boris-johnson-gets-mixed-reviews-u-k-s-lgbtq-community-n1035241 |access-date=6 June 2021 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=26 July 2019 |archive-date=6 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210606212010/https://www.nbcnews.com/feature/nbc-out/boris-johnson-gets-mixed-reviews-u-k-s-lgbtq-community-n1035241 |url-status=live}}</ref> After initially stating he would not, he [[British Parliamentary approval for the invasion of Iraq|supported]] the government's plans to join the United States in the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]],{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=240}} and in April 2003 visited occupied Baghdad.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=149}} In August 2004, he backed unsuccessful [[Parliamentary motion to impeach Tony Blair|impeachment procedures]] against Prime Minister [[Tony Blair]] for "[[high crimes and misdemeanours]]" regarding the war,<ref>{{cite news |date=2 September 2004 |title=Programmes = BBC Parliament – Impeachment in practice |publisher=BBC |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/bbc_parliament/3622380.stm |access-date=18 December 2016 |archive-date=16 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201116220243/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/bbc_parliament/3622380.stm |url-status=live}}</ref> and in December 2006 described the invasion as "a colossal mistake and misadventure".{{sfn|Gimson|2012|p=265}}

Although labelling Johnson "ineffably duplicitous" for breaking his promise not to become an MP, Black decided not to dismiss him because he "helped promote the magazine and raise its circulation".{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=189, 190}} Johnson remained editor of ''The Spectator'', while also writing columns for ''The Daily Telegraph'' and ''GQ'', and making television appearances.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=226}} His 2001 book, ''[[Friends, Voters, Countrymen: Jottings on the Stump]]'', recounted that year's election campaign,{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1p=230|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2pp=145–146}} while 2003's ''Lend Me Your Ears'' collected previously published columns and articles.{{sfn|Gimson|2012|pp=176–177}} In 2004, [[HarperCollins]] published his first novel: ''[[Seventy-Two Virgins: A Comedy of Errors]]'' revolved around the life of a Conservative MP and contained autobiographical elements.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=249–251|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2pp=189–192}} Responding to criticism that he was juggling too many jobs, he cited [[Winston Churchill]] and [[Benjamin Disraeli]] as exemplars who combined political and literary careers.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1p=227|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=143}} To manage stress, he took up jogging and cycling,{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=228}} and became so well known for the latter that [[Andrew Gimson]] suggested he was "perhaps the most famous cyclist in Britain".{{sfn|Gimson|2012|p=182}}

Following [[William Hague]]'s resignation as Conservative leader, the party elected [[Iain Duncan Smith]].{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=223–224|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=150}} Johnson had a strained relationship with Duncan Smith, and ''The Spectator'' became critical of his party leadership.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1p=234|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=150}} Duncan Smith was succeeded by [[Michael Howard]] in November 2003; Howard deemed Johnson to be the most popular Conservative politician with the electorate and appointed him vice-chairman of the party, responsible for overseeing its electoral campaign.{{sfnm|1a1=Edwards|1a2=Isaby|1y=2008|1pp=46–47|2a1=Purnell|2y=2011|2pp=242–243|3a1=Gimson|3y=2012|3p=178}} In his Shadow Cabinet reshuffle of May 2004, Howard appointed Johnson as shadow arts minister.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1p=243|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=179}} In October, Howard ordered Johnson to apologise publicly in [[Liverpool]] for publishing a ''Spectator'' article – anonymously written by [[Simon Heffer]] – which said the crowds at the [[Hillsborough disaster]] had contributed to the incident and that Liverpudlians had a predilection for reliance on the [[Welfare state in the United Kingdom|welfare state]].{{sfnm|1a1=Edwards|1a2=Isaby|1y=2008|1p=47|2a1=Purnell|2y=2011|2pp=251–252|3a1=Gimson|3y=2012|3pp=193–207}}<ref>{{Cite news |date=19 October 2004 |title=Boris sorry for Scouse stereotype |work=BBC News |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/3756418.stm |access-date=9 April 2020 |archive-date=9 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200409193955/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/3756418.stm |url-status=live }}</ref>

In November 2004, the tabloids revealed that since 2000 Johnson had been having an affair with ''Spectator'' columnist [[Petronella Wyatt]], resulting in two abortions.{{sfnm|1a1=Edwards|1a2=Isaby|1y=2008|1p=47|2a1=Purnell|2y=2011|2pp=257–263|3a1=Gimson|3y=2012|3pp=162–173, 209–218}} Johnson denied the allegations but they were subsequently proven to be true, and Howard dismissed him as vice-chairman and shadow arts minister when he refused to resign.{{sfnm|1a1=Edwards|1a2=Isaby|1y=2008|1p=47|2a1=Purnell|2y=2011|2pp=265–267|3a1=Gimson|3y=2012|3pp=222–223}}<ref>{{Cite news |last=McSmith |first=Andy |date=14 November 2004 |title=On your bike, Boris: Howard sacks Johnson over private life |work=[[The Independent]] |location=London |url=http://news.independent.co.uk/uk/politics/story.jsp?story=582750 |access-date=12 September 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041213175715/http://news.independent.co.uk/uk/politics/story.jsp?story=582750 |archive-date=13 December 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Stubley |first1=Peter |title=Boris Johnson: The most infamous lies and untruths by the Conservative leadership candidate |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-lies-conservative-leader-candidate-list-times-banana-brexit-bus-a8929076.html |access-date=29 March 2024 |work=The Independent |date=25 May 2019 |archive-date=20 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211220041838/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-lies-conservative-leader-candidate-list-times-banana-brexit-bus-a8929076.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

====Second term====
[[File:University Park MMB 21 Portland Building - Boris Johnson.jpg|thumb|right|As shadow minister for higher education, Johnson visited various universities (as here at the [[University of Nottingham]] in 2006)]]
[[File:Boris Johnson cropped.JPG|thumb|Johnson in 2007]]
At the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]], Johnson was re-elected MP for Henley.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1p=277|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=232}} Labour won the election and Howard stood down as Conservative leader; Johnson backed [[David Cameron]] as his successor.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=283–284|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2pp=235–236}} After Cameron was elected, he appointed Johnson as the shadow higher education minister.{{sfnm|1a1=Edwards|1a2=Isaby|1y=2008|1p=47|2a1=Purnell|2y=2011|2p=289|3a1=Gimson|3y=2012|3p=243}} Interested in streamlining university funding,{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=302}} Johnson supported Labour's [[Tuition fees in the United Kingdom|proposed top-up fees]].{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=291}} He campaigned in 2006 to become the [[Rector of the University of Edinburgh]], but his support for top-up fees damaged his campaign, and he came third.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=291–292|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=248}}<ref name="HES24Feb06">{{Cite news |last=Fazackerley |first=Anna |date=24 February 2006 |title=Blond has more fun but fails to thwart anti top-up fee vote |work=[[Times Higher Education Supplement]] |location=London |url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storyCode=201555&sectioncode=26 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120514070050/http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storyCode=201555&sectioncode=26 |archive-date=14 May 2012}}</ref>

In April 2006, the ''[[News of the World]]'' alleged that Johnson was having an affair with journalist Anna Fazackerley; the pair did not comment, and shortly afterwards Johnson began employing Fazackerley.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=296–300|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2pp=255–257}}<ref name="Barber-2008">{{Cite news |last=Barber |first=Lynn |date=19 October 2008 |title=No more Mr Nice Guy |work=The Guardian |location=London |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2008/oct/19/boris-london |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=6 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206061751/https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2008/oct/19/boris-london |url-status=live }}</ref> In September 2006, Papua New Guinea's [[High Commission]] protested after he compared the Conservatives' frequently changing leadership to [[Human cannibalism|cannibalism in the country]].{{sfn|Gimson|2012|p=266}}

In 2005, ''The Spectator''{{'}}s new chief executive, [[Andrew Neil]], dismissed Johnson as editor.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=289–290|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2pp=244–245}} To make up for this loss of income, Johnson negotiated with ''The Daily Telegraph'' to raise his salary from £200,000 to £250,000, averaging £5,000 per column.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=294–295}}<ref>{{Cite news |last=Brook, Stephen |date=15 May 2008 |title=Boris to return to Telegraph column |work=The Guardian |location=London |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/may/15/dailytelegraph.pressandpublishing |access-date=7 July 2010 |archive-date=6 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206061804/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/may/15/dailytelegraph.pressandpublishing |url-status=live }}</ref> He presented a [[popular history]] television show, ''[[The Dream of Rome]]'', which was broadcast in January 2006; a book followed in February.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=292–293|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2pp=250–253}} A sequel, ''After Rome'', focused on early Islamic history.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=294}} In 2007 he earned £540,000, making him the third-highest-earning MP that year.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=295}}

==Mayor of London (2008–2016)==
{{Main|Mayoralty of Boris Johnson}}

===Mayoral election: 2007–2008===
{{main|2008 London mayoral election}}
{{See also|2007 London Conservative Party mayoral selection}}
[[File:Boris Johnson -holding a red model bus -2007.jpg|thumb|right|Johnson pledged to replace the city's [[Articulated buses in London|articulated buses]] with [[New Routemaster]] buses if elected mayor]]

In September, Johnson was selected as the Conservative candidate for [[Mayor of London]] after a public London-wide [[Partisan primary|primary]].{{sfnm|1a1=Edwards|1a2=Isaby|1y=2008|1p=53|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=279}}<ref>{{Cite news |date=27 September 2007 |title=Johnson is Tory mayor candidate |work=BBC News |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7014739.stm |access-date=2 January 2010 |archive-date=13 April 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080413185715/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7014739.stm |url-status=live }}</ref> Johnson's campaign focused on reducing youth crime, making public transport safer, and replacing the [[Articulated buses in London|articulated buses]] with an updated version of the [[AEC Routemaster]].{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=327}} Targeting the Conservative-leaning suburbs of [[outer London]], it capitalised on perceptions that the Labour Mayoralty had neglected them in favour of [[inner London]].{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1p=327|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=285}} His campaign emphasised his popularity, even among those who opposed his policies,{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=326–327}} with opponents complaining a common attitude among voters was: "I'm voting for Boris because he is a laugh."{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=327}} The campaign of Labour incumbent [[Ken Livingstone]] portrayed Johnson as an out-of-touch [[toff]] and bigot.{{sfnm|1a1=Hosken|1y=2008|1pp=426–427|2a1=Edwards|2a2=Isaby|2y=2008|2pp=67–69, 133|3a1=Purnell|3y=2011|3pp=90, 315}}

In the election, Johnson received 43% and Livingstone 37% of first-preference votes; when second-preference votes were added, Johnson was victorious with 53% to Livingstone's 47%.{{sfnm|1a1=Edwards|1a2=Isaby|1y=2008|1pp=200–201|2a1=Purnell|2y=2011|2p=348}}<ref name="bbcmayorwin">{{Cite news |date=3 May 2008 |title=Johnson wins London mayoral race |work=BBC News |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7380947.stm |access-date=3 May 2008 |archive-date=9 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809215058/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7380947.stm |url-status=live }}</ref> Johnson subsequently announced his intention to stand down as MP for Henley.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=351}}<ref>{{Cite news |last=Watt |first=Nicholas |date=3 May 2008 |title=Johnson snatches Tories' biggest prize |work=The Guardian |location=London |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/may/03/london08.boris1 |access-date=1 April 2010 |archive-date=6 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206061843/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/may/03/london08.boris1 |url-status=live }}</ref>

===First term: 2008–2012===
After Johnson became mayor, those in City Hall deemed too closely allied to Livingstone's administration had their employment terminated.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=366}} Johnson appointed [[Tim Parker (businessman)|Tim Parker]] as his deputy mayor, but after Parker began taking increasing control at City Hall, Johnson dismissed him.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=368–271}} Many in the Conservative Party initially distanced themselves from Johnson's administration, fearing it would be damaging for the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]].{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=368}}

[[File:Boris Johnson on the podium.jpg|thumb|right|Johnson gave a victory speech in [[City Hall, Southwark|City Hall]] after being elected as the [[Mayor of London]] ]]

During the campaign, Johnson had confided to [[Brian Paddick]] he was unsure how he would maintain his lifestyle on the mayoral salary of £140,000 a year.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=360}} He agreed to continue his ''Daily Telegraph'' column, thus earning a further £250,000 a year.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=361}} His team believed this would cause controversy and made him promise to donate 20% of his ''Daily Telegraph'' salary to a charitable cause. Johnson resented this, and ultimately did not pay the full 20%.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=362}} Controversy erupted when on the [[BBC]]'s ''[[HARDtalk]]'' he referred to the £250,000 salary as "chicken feed"; this was at the time approximately 10 times the average yearly wage for a British worker.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=363}}<ref>{{Cite news |date=14 July 2009 |title=Mayor's £250,000 'chicken feed' |work=BBC News |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/8148899.stm |access-date=2 January 2010 |archive-date=13 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220113000358/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/8148899.stm |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Mulholland |first=Hélène |date=14 July 2009 |title=Johnson condemned for describing £250,000 deal as 'chicken feed' |work=The Guardian |location=London |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/jul/14/boris-johnson-telegraph-chicken-feed |access-date=1 April 2010 |archive-date=6 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206061858/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/jul/14/boris-johnson-telegraph-chicken-feed |url-status=live }}</ref>
[[File:Boris Johnson -opening bell at NASDAQ-14Sept2009-3c.jpg|thumb|Johnson at the opening of NASDAQ in 2009]]
During his first administration, Johnson was embroiled in several personal scandals. After moving to a new house in Islington, he built a shed without obtaining [[planning permission]]; after neighbours complained, he dismantled it.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=396–397|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=308}} The press also accused him of having an affair with Helen Macintyre and of fathering her child, allegations that he did not deny.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=407–410|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2pp=330–331}}<ref name="theguardian2">{{Cite news |last=Mulholland |first=Helene |date=15 December 2010 |title=No censure for Boris Johnson over relationship with unpaid City Hall adviser |work=The Guardian |location=London |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/dec/15/no-censure-boris-johnson-city-hall-adviser |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=2 December 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201202040258/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/dec/15/no-censure-boris-johnson-city-hall-adviser |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Mulholland |first=Hélène |date=20 July 2010 |title=Boris Johnson pressed for full details of the appointment of his alleged lover |work=The Guardian |location=London |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/jul/20/boris-johnson-mayor-2012-macintyre |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=6 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206062215/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/jul/20/boris-johnson-mayor-2012-macintyre |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Telegraph210513">{{Cite news |date=21 May 2013 |title=Public has right to know about Boris Johnson's secret lovechild, court rules |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/10070055/Public-has-right-to-know-about-Boris-Johnsons-secret-lovechild-court-rules.html |url-status=live |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130616032220/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/10070055/Public-has-right-to-know-about-Boris-Johnsons-secret-lovechild-court-rules.html |archive-date=16 June 2013 |access-date=5 May 2021 |url-access=limited}}</ref> Johnson was accused of warning [[Damian Green]] that police were planning to arrest him; Johnson denied the claims.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=380–385|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2pp=305–308}} He was accused of [[cronyism]],{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=407}} in particular for appointing [[Veronica Wadley]] as the chair of London's [[Arts Council]].{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=401–402}}<ref>{{Cite news |last=Mulholland |first=Hélène |date=9 October 2009 |title=Ken Livingstone claims Boris Johnson tried to 'pay off' former Evening Standard editor |work=The Guardian |location=London |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/oct/09/boris-johnson-ken-livingstone-standard |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=6 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206062227/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/oct/09/boris-johnson-ken-livingstone-standard |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Coates |first=Sam |date=8 October 2009 |title=Boris Johnson 'broke rules' by proposing ally for top London arts job |work=[[The Times]] |location=London |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/boris-johnson-broke-rules-by-proposing-ally-for-top-london-arts-job-bj57sz2kgtv |url-access=subscription |access-date=16 April 2020 |archive-date=1 August 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200801060948/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/boris-johnson-broke-rules-by-proposing-ally-for-top-london-arts-job-bj57sz2kgtv |url-status=live }}</ref> In the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal|parliamentary expenses scandal]], he was accused of excessive expenses claims for taxis.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=392–395}}
Johnson remained a popular figure in London with a strong celebrity status in the city.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=446}}

====Policies====
[[File:LTZ1851-21-20240402-184553.jpg|thumb|right|The [[New Routemaster]] bus introduced by Johnson's administration]]

Johnson made no major changes to the mayoral system of the previous administration.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=373}} However, he did reverse several other measures implemented by Livingstone: ending the city's oil deal with Venezuela, abolishing ''[[The Londoner]]'' newsletter, and scrapping the half-yearly inspections of [[Hackney carriage|black cabs]], which was reinstated three years later.{{sfnm|1a1=Edwards|1a2=Isaby|1y=2008|1p=211|2a1=Purnell|2y=2011|2p=373}} Abolishing the western wing of the [[London congestion charge|congestion charging]] zone,{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=443}} he cancelled plans to increase the congestion charge for [[four-wheel drive|four-wheel-drive vehicles]].{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=391}} He was subsequently accused of failing to publish an independent report on air pollution commissioned by the [[Greater London Authority]], which revealed the city breached legal limits on [[nitrogen dioxide]] levels.<ref name="tele">{{Cite news |date=17 May 2016 |title=Boris Johnson accused of hiding study linking air pollution and deprived schools |work=The Daily Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/05/17/boris-johndon-accused-of-hiding-study-linking-air-pollution-and/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/05/17/boris-johndon-accused-of-hiding-study-linking-air-pollution-and/ |archive-date=10 January 2022 |url-status=live |url-access=limited |access-date=5 May 2021}}{{cbignore}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Mortimer |first=Caroline |date=16 May 2016 |title=Boris Johnson accused of burying report on the number of schools in London's most polluted areas |work=The Independent |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-accused-of-burying-report-on-the-number-of-deprived-schools-in-londons-most-polluted-a7033016.html |access-date=24 August 2017 |archive-date=12 May 2022 |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220512/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-accused-of-burying-report-on-the-number-of-deprived-schools-in-londons-most-polluted-a7033016.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

Johnson retained Livingstone projects such as [[Crossrail]] and the [[2012 Olympic Games]], but was accused of trying to take credit for them.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=390}} He introduced a public bicycle scheme that had been mooted by Livingstone's administration; colloquially known as "[[Boris Bikes]]", the part privately financed system was a significant financial loss but proved popular.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hoscik |first=Martin |date=19 December 2012 |title=Exclusive: TfL reveals how much Barclays has paid for Cycle Hire scheme |url=http://www.mayorwatch.co.uk/exclusive-tfl-reveals-how-much-barclays-has-paid-for-cycle-hire-scheme/201223704/ |website=MayorWatch |access-date=20 May 2015 |archive-date=20 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720102134/https://www.mayorwatch.co.uk/exclusive-tfl-reveals-how-much-barclays-has-paid-for-cycle-hire-scheme/201223704/ |url-status=live }}</ref>{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=414–416|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=307}} Despite Johnson's support of cycling, and his much-publicised identity as a cyclist, some cycling groups argued he had failed to make the city's roads safer for cyclists.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=442–443}} As per his election pledge, he commissioned the development of the [[New Routemaster]] buses for central London.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1p=417|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=307}} He also ordered the construction of a [[Emirates Air Line (cable car)|cable car system]] that crossed the [[River Thames]] between the [[Greenwich Peninsula]] and the [[Royal Docks]].{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=417–418}}

[[File:BorisBikes.jpg|left|thumb|Johnson implemented Livingstone's idea of a public bicycle system; the result was dubbed the [[Santander Cycles|"Boris Bike"]].]]

Johnson's first policy initiative was a ban on drinking alcohol on public transport.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1p=265|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=288}}<ref name="lgovpr20080507">{{cite press release |title=Mayor unveils plan to ban alcohol on the transport network |date=6 May 2008 |publisher=Greater London Authority |url=http://www.london.gov.uk/view_press_release.jsp?releaseid=16793 |access-date=7 May 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513075018/http://www.london.gov.uk/view_press_release.jsp?releaseid=16793 |archive-date=13 May 2008}}</ref> He announced plans to extend pay-as-you-go [[Oyster cards]] to national rail services in London.<ref name="es_oystersie">{{cite news |last=Waugh |first=Paul |date=12 May 2008 |title=Boris plans to 'Oysterise' overground rail services by next May |work=Evening Standard |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/boris-plans-to-oysterise-overground-rail-services-by-next-may-6690497.html |access-date=21 November 2013 |archive-date=21 February 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221195348/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/boris-plans-to-oysterise-overground-rail-services-by-next-may-6690497.html |url-status=live }}</ref> A pledge in Johnson's manifesto was to retain Tube ticket offices, in opposition to Livingstone's proposal to close up to 40.<ref name="2008_transport_manifesto">{{cite news |last=Johnson |first=Boris |title=Saying No To Ticket Office Closures |page=38 |work=Getting Londoners Moving (Transport Manifesto for the 2008&nbsp;Mayoral election) |publisher=Back Boris campaign |url=http://image.guardian.co.uk/sys-files/Guardian/documents/2009/04/27/Transportmanifesto.pdf |access-date=21 November 2013 |archive-date=23 April 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100423195938/http://image.guardian.co.uk/sys-files/Guardian/documents/2009/04/27/Transportmanifesto.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref> On 2 July 2008, the Mayor's office announced the closure plan was to be abandoned.<ref name="es_kenplan">{{cite news |last=Murray |first=Dick |date=2 July 2008 |title=Mayor scraps Ken plan to axe 40 Tube ticket offices |work=Evening Standard |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor-scraps-ken-plan-to-axe-40-tube-ticket-offices-6869816.html |access-date=21 November 2013 |archive-date=21 February 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221180841/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor-scraps-ken-plan-to-axe-40-tube-ticket-offices-6869816.html |url-status=live }}</ref> On 21 November 2013, [[Transport for London]] announced that all London Underground ticket offices would close by 2015.<ref name="bbc_borisplan">{{cite news |date=21 November 2013 |title=London Underground in 24-hour plans as ticket offices shut |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-25025888 |access-date=17 February 2015 |archive-date=21 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150221160332/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-25025888 |url-status=live }}</ref> In financing these projects, Johnson's administration borrowed £100&nbsp;million,{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=437}} while public transport fares were increased by 50%.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=416}}

During his first term, Johnson was perceived as having moved leftward on certain issues, supporting the [[Living wage in the United Kingdom|London Living Wage]] and endorsing an amnesty for illegal migrants.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=388}} He tried placating critics who had deemed him a bigot by appearing at [[Pride London|London's gay pride parade]] and praising ethnic minority newspapers.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=374–375}} Johnson broke from the traditional protocol of those in public office not publicly commenting on other nations' elections by endorsing [[Barack Obama]] for the [[2008 United States presidential election]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Mulholland |first=Hélène |date=1 August 2008 |title=Barack Obama gets backing from Boris Johnson |work=The Guardian |location=London |url=https://www.theguardian.com/global/2008/aug/01/boris.barackobama |access-date=1 April 2010 |archive-date=20 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720095111/https://www.theguardian.com/global/2008/aug/01/boris.barackobama |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Prince |first=Rosa |date=1 August 2008 |title=Boris Johnson backs Barack Obama as US President |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/london-mayor-election/mayor-of-london/2484162/Boris-Johnson-backs-Barack-Obama-as-US-President.html |url-status=live |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120912005110/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/london-mayor-election/mayor-of-london/2484162/Boris-Johnson-backs-Barack-Obama-as-US-President.html |archive-date=12 September 2012 |access-date=5 May 2021 |url-access=limited}}</ref>

====Relations with the police, finance, and the media====
[[File:2011 London riots.jpg|thumb|right|Johnson's response to the 2011 London riots was criticised]]
Johnson appointed himself chair of the [[Metropolitan Police Authority]] (MPA), and in October 2008 successfully pushed for the resignation of Metropolitan Police Commissioner [[Ian Blair]], after Blair was criticised for allegedly handing contracts to friends and for his handling of the [[death of Jean Charles de Menezes]].{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=377–278|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=304}}<ref>{{cite news |date=2 October 2008 |title=Britain's top policeman resigns |work=BBC News |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7648664.stm |access-date=1 April 2010 |archive-date=23 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200423070657/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7648664.stm |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=O'Neill |first1=Sean |last2=Fresco |first2=Adam |last3=Coates |first3=Sam |date=3 October 2008 |title=Boris Johnson forces Sir Ian Blair to quit as police chief |work=The Times |location=London |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/boris-johnson-forces-sir-ian-blair-to-quit-as-police-chief-qcmtwr7ff70 |url-access=subscription |access-date=16 April 2020 |archive-date=31 July 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200731153913/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/boris-johnson-forces-sir-ian-blair-to-quit-as-police-chief-qcmtwr7ff70 |url-status=live }}</ref> This earned Johnson respect among Conservatives, who interpreted it as his first act of strength.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=379}} Johnson resigned as chairman of the MPA in January 2010,{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=388}} but throughout his mayoralty was highly supportive of the Metropolitan Police, particularly during the controversy surrounding the [[death of Ian Tomlinson]].{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=387–388}} Overall crime in London fell during his administration, but his claim that serious youth crime had decreased proved to be false, and he acknowledged the error.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=436}}<ref>{{Cite news |last=Donovan |first=Tim |date=16 November 2011 |title=London mayor admits 'caveats' in youth crime statistics |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-15765557 |access-date=21 June 2018 |archive-date=6 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220606022515/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-15765557 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was criticised for his response to the [[2011 London riots]].{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=429–432|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2pp=333–335}}

[[File:BorisOC2010.jpg|thumb|left|Johnson lights the flame at the 2010 [[London Youth Games]] opening ceremony]]

Johnson championed London's financial sector and denounced what he saw as "banker bashing" following the [[financial crisis of 2007–08]],{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1p=400|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=324}} condemning the [[anti-capitalist]] [[Occupy London]] movement that appeared in 2011.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=439–440}} He collected donations from the city's wealthy for a charitable enterprise, the Mayor's Fund, which he had established to aid disadvantaged youths. It initially announced the fund would raise £100&nbsp;million, but by 2010 it had only earnt £1.5&nbsp;million.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=414}} He also maintained extensive personal contacts throughout the British media,{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=389}} which resulted in widespread favourable press coverage of his administration.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=389}} In turn he remained largely supportive of his friends in the media, including [[Rupert Murdoch]], during the [[News International phone hacking scandal]].{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=424–425}}

The formation of the Forensic Audit Panel was announced on 8 May 2008. The panel was tasked with monitoring and investigating financial management at the [[London Development Agency]] and the [[Greater London Authority]].<ref name="lgovpr20080508">{{Cite press release |title=Mayor of London announces new Forensic Audit Panel to investigate GLA and LDA |date=8 May 2008 |publisher=Greater London Authority |url=http://www.london.gov.uk/view_press_release.jsp?releaseid=16814 |access-date=7 May 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080518065203/http://www.london.gov.uk/view_press_release.jsp?releaseid=16814 |archive-date=18 May 2008}}</ref> Johnson's announcement was criticised by Labour for the perceived politicisation of this nominally independent panel.<ref>{{Cite web |date=9 May 2008 |title=Labour accuse Mayor of 'Tory witch hunt' |url=http://www.mayorwatch.co.uk/Labour-Accuse-Mayor-of-Tory-Witch-Hunt-article_id-1616.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513014713/http://www.mayorwatch.co.uk/Labour-Accuse-Mayor-of-Tory-Witch-Hunt-article_id-1616.html |archive-date=13 May 2008 |access-date=12 September 2013 |publisher=MayorWatch}}</ref> The head of the panel, [[Patience Wheatcroft]], was married to a Conservative councillor<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2006/jul/17/mediaguardiantop100200638 |title=The Media Guardian 100 – 87 Patience Wheatcroft |date=17 July 2006 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |issn=0261-3077 |access-date=11 December 2016 |archive-date=8 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190608023333/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2006/jul/17/mediaguardiantop100200638 |url-status=live }}</ref> and three of the four remaining panel members also had close links to the Conservatives.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Stephen Greenhalgh – Conservative Home |url=http://www.conservativehome.com/tag/stephen-greenhalgh |access-date=25 June 2016 |archive-date=22 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622121535/https://www.conservativehome.com/tag/stephen-greenhalgh |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Barney |first=Katharine |date=15 July 2008 |title=Ken Livingstone refuses to appear before LDA audit panel |work=Evening Standard |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/ken-livingstone-refuses-to-appear-before-lda-audit-panel-6863880.html |access-date=25 June 2016 |archive-date=30 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220730052313/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/ken-livingstone-refuses-to-appear-before-lda-audit-panel-6863880.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

====Re-election campaign====
Up for re-election in 2012, Johnson again hired Crosby to orchestrate his campaign.{{sfn|Gimson|2012|p=338}}
Before the election, Johnson published ''Johnson's Life of London'', a work of popular history that historian [[A. N. Wilson]] characterised as a "coded plea" for votes.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=447–448}}
Polls suggested that while Livingstone's approach to transport was preferred, voters in London placed greater trust in Johnson on crime and the economy.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=440}} Johnson's campaign emphasised the accusation that Livingstone was guilty of [[tax evasion]], for which Livingstone called Johnson a "bare-faced liar".{{sfn|Crines|2013|p=3}} Political scientist Andrew Crines believed that Livingstone's campaign focused on criticising Johnson rather than presenting an alternate and progressive vision of London's future.{{sfn|Crines|2013|p=2}} Johnson was [[2012 London mayoral election|re-elected]].<ref name="BBC5May12">{{Cite news |date=5 May 2012 |title=London mayor: Boris Johnson wins second term by tight margin 5&nbsp;May 2012 Last updated at 01:35 |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-17946742 |access-date=5 May 2012 |archive-date=17 June 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120617195552/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-17946742 |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Second term: 2012–2016===
[[File:Boris 2012.jpg|thumb|right|Johnson at the [[2012 Summer Olympics]]]]
After a successful bid under Livingstone in 2005, London hosted the [[2012 Summer Olympics]], with Johnson as board co-chair.<ref>{{Cite web |title=The Mayor of London – 2012 Olympics |url=http://www.london2012.com/about-us/the-people-delivering-the-games/stakeholders/the-mayor-of-london/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120729172513/http://www.london2012.com/about-us/the-people-delivering-the-games/stakeholders/the-mayor-of-london/ |archive-date=29 July 2012 |access-date=11 December 2012 |publisher=London 2012}}</ref> He improved transportation around London by making more tickets available and adding buses around the capital when thousands of spectators were temporary visitors.<ref>{{Cite news |date=30 July 2012 |title=Boris Johnson on London 2012 Olympics tickets and transport |work=The Guardian (video) |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/video/2012/jul/30/boris-johnson-olympics-tickets-transport-video |access-date=11 December 2012 |archive-date=6 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206062207/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/video/2012/jul/30/boris-johnson-olympics-tickets-transport-video |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=22 July 2012 |title=London 2012: Boris Johnson says capital is prepared |work=BBC News |url=http://bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18944191 |access-date=11 December 2012 |archive-date=31 October 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121031135315/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18944191 |url-status=live }}</ref> Johnson was accused of covering up pollution ahead of the games by deploying dust suppressants to remove air particulates near monitoring stations.<ref name=tele/> In November 2013, Johnson announced major changes to the operation of the [[London Underground]], including the extension of operating hours. All staffed ticket offices were replaced with automated ticketing systems.<ref name="bbc_tube_ticket">{{Cite news |date=21 November 2013 |title=Every Tube ticket office to close |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-25025888 |access-date=21 November 2013 |archive-date=21 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150221160332/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-25025888 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="es_shakeup">{{Cite news |last=Beard |first=Matthew |date=21 November 2013 |title=950 London Underground staff to lose their jobs in Tube ticket office shake-up |work=Evening Standard |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/transport/950-london-underground-staff-to-lose-their-jobs-in-tube-ticket-office-shakeup-8954060.html |access-date=21 November 2013 |archive-date=27 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131127051512/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/transport/950-london-underground-staff-to-lose-their-jobs-in-tube-ticket-office-shakeup-8954060.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

Johnson was close friends with American entrepreneur<ref>{{Cite news |date=23 September 2019 |title=PM Defends Actions over Conflict of Interest Claims |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-49794693 |access-date=23 September 2019 |archive-date=7 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220707164351/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-49794693 |url-status=live }}</ref> and model [[Jennifer Arcuri]], with ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' describing him as a regular visitor to her flat,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Bulman |first=May |date=22 September 2019 |title=Boris Johnson facing questions over relationship with ex-model Jennifer Arcuri |work=The Independent |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/boris-johnson-jennifer-arcuri-model-london-mayor-friendship-conflict-interest-a9115211.html |access-date=26 September 2019 |archive-date=12 May 2022 |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220512/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/boris-johnson-jennifer-arcuri-model-london-mayor-friendship-conflict-interest-a9115211.html |url-status=live }}</ref> and implying they were in a sexual relationship.<ref name="sky">{{Cite news |last=Coates |first=Sam |date=25 September 2019 |title=Boris Johnson breaks silence on relationship with entrepreneur Jennifer Arcuri |publisher=[[Sky News]] |url=https://news.sky.com/story/boris-johnson-refuses-six-times-to-answer-questions-about-funding-for-close-friend-11817579 |access-date=23 September 2019 |archive-date=31 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220331165900/https://news.sky.com/story/boris-johnson-refuses-six-times-to-answer-questions-about-funding-for-close-friend-11817579 |url-status=live }}</ref> Arcuri and her company, Innotech, were awarded substantial government grants, and Johnson intervened to allow her onto three trade mission trips.<ref>{{Cite web |date=22 September 2019 |title=Boris Johnson Facing Questions over Giving Public Money to American Woman |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/boris-johnson-jennifer-arcuri_uk_5d8794f3e4b0849d472ad0dc |website=HuffPost |access-date=22 September 2019 |archive-date=31 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220331165909/https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/boris-johnson-jennifer-arcuri_uk_5d8794f3e4b0849d472ad0dc |url-status=live }}</ref> ''The Sunday Times'' said in September 2019 that Johnson failed to declare his personal relationship as a conflict of interest.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Weaver |first=Matthew |date=22 September 2019 |title=Boris Johnson urged to justify 'awarding public funds to close friend' |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/sep/22/boris-johnson-urged-to-justify-awarding-public-funds-to-close-friend-jennifer-arcuri |access-date=26 September 2019 |archive-date=26 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190926150320/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/sep/22/boris-johnson-urged-to-justify-awarding-public-funds-to-close-friend-jennifer-arcuri |url-status=live }}</ref> The Greater London Authority referred the matter to the [[Independent Office for Police Conduct]] (IOPC) "so it can assess whether or not it is necessary to investigate the former mayor of London for the criminal offence of misconduct in public office", for the Mayor is also London's [[police and crime commissioner]].<ref>{{cite news |date=27 September 2019 |title=PM's links to Arcuri referred to police watchdog |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-49859321 |access-date=13 October 2019 |archive-date=17 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220517100105/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-49859321 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 9 November 2019 it was revealed that the IOPC had decided to publish its report after the general election on 12 December.<ref>{{cite news |last=Townsend |first=Mark |date=10 November 2019 |title=Fury as decision on police inquiry into PM shelved until after election |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/nov/09/boris-johnson-jennifer-arcuri-iopc-delay-announcement-investigation |access-date=11 November 2019 |archive-date=10 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191110225836/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/nov/09/boris-johnson-jennifer-arcuri-iopc-delay-announcement-investigation |url-status=live}}</ref> The IOPC eventually issued its report in May 2020, concluding that, although there was no basis for any criminal charge, there was evidence that the close relationship between Johnson and Arcuri had influenced decisions, that Johnson should have declared an interest, and that his failure to do this could have breached the London Assembly's code of conduct.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/may/21/boris-johnson-will-not-face-criminal-inquiry-over-jennifer-arcuri|last=Weaver|first=Matthew|title=Boris Johnson will not face criminal inquiry over Jennifer Arcuri|work=The Guardian|date=21 May 2020|access-date=22 May 2020|archive-date=21 May 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200521232837/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/may/21/boris-johnson-will-not-face-criminal-inquiry-over-jennifer-arcuri|url-status=live}}<!--clarification of the story: the "GLA Oversight Committee" is a committee of the London Assembly--></ref>

In 2015, Johnson criticised then-presidential candidate [[Donald Trump]]'s false comments that there were [[No-go area#United Kingdom|no-go zones in London]] inaccessible for non-Muslims. Johnson said Trump was "betraying a quite stupefying ignorance that makes him frankly unfit to hold the office of President of the United States",<ref name="Waugh">{{cite news |last=Waugh |first=Paul |title=Boris slams Trump: he's 'out of his mind' |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2015/12/09/boris-johnson-slams-donal_n_8758292.html |access-date=25 August 2019 |work=HuffPost |date=9 December 2015 |archive-date=9 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170909043755/http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2015/12/09/boris-johnson-slams-donal_n_8758292.html |url-status=live}}</ref> becoming the first senior politician in the UK to declare Trump unfit for office, but rejecting calls for him to be banned from the country.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dathan |first=Matt |title=Boris Johnson says Donald Trump 'betrays a stupefying ignorance that makes him unfit to be US President' |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-says-donald-trump-betrays-a-stupefying-ignorance-that-makes-him-unfit-to-be-us-a6766871.html |access-date=25 August 2019 |work=The Independent |date=9 December 2015 |archive-date=12 May 2022 |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220512/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-says-donald-trump-betrays-a-stupefying-ignorance-that-makes-him-unfit-to-be-us-a6766871.html |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2016, he said he was "genuinely worried that [Trump] could become president", telling ITV's [[Tom Bradby]] that being mistaken for Trump in New York was "one of the worst moments" of his life.<ref name="Telegraph160321">{{cite news |last=McCann |first=Kate |date=21 March 2016 |title=Boris Johnson: 'I was mistaken for Donald Trump' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/boris-johnson/12200562/Boris-Johnson-I-was-mistaken-for-Donald-Trump.html |url-status=live |work=The Telegraph |archive-url=https://archive.today/20160702131836/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/boris-johnson/12200562/Boris-Johnson-I-was-mistaken-for-Donald-Trump.html |archive-date=2 July 2016 |access-date=5 May 2021 |url-access=limited}}</ref>

Johnson did not run for a third mayoral and stepped down on 5 May 2016 following [[2016 London mayoral election|the election]]. A [[YouGov]] poll commissioned at the end of Johnson's term revealed that 52% of Londoners believed he did a "good job" while 29% believed he did a "bad job".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://yougov.co.uk/news/2016/05/05/mayor-boris-public-verdict/|title=Mayor Boris: the public verdict|first=Will|last=Dahlgreen|website=[[YouGov]]|access-date=17 July 2018|archive-date=18 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180718234445/https://yougov.co.uk/news/2016/05/05/mayor-boris-public-verdict/|url-status=live}}</ref>

==Return to Parliament==
Johnson initially said that he would not return to the House of Commons while mayor.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=446}} After much media speculation, in August 2014 he sought selection as the Conservative candidate for the [[safe seat]] of [[Uxbridge and South Ruislip]] at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/boris-johnson-declares-he-will-stand-in-uxbridge-and-south-ruislip-9691619.html|title=Boris Johnson declares he will stand in Uxbridge and South Ruislip|last=de Peyer|first=Robin|date=26 August 2014|work=Evening Standard|access-date=26 August 2014|archive-date=26 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826172017/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/boris-johnson-declares-he-will-stand-in-uxbridge-and-south-ruislip-9691619.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/sep/12/boris-johnson-tory-candidate-uxbridge-south-ruislip|title=Boris Johnson selected to stand for Tories in Uxbridge and South Ruislip|last=Johnston|first=Chris|date=12 September 2014|work=The Guardian|access-date=30 March 2015|location=London|archive-date=6 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206062451/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/sep/12/boris-johnson-tory-candidate-uxbridge-south-ruislip|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Swinford|first1=Steven|last2=Holehouse|first2=Matthew|date=12 September 2014|title=Boris Johnson selected to stand for Tories in Uxbridge and South Ruislip|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/general-election-2015/11093857/Boris-Johnson-selected-to-stand-for-Tories-in-Uxbridge-and-South-Ruislip.html|url-status=live|work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|archive-url=https://archive.today/20150404211708/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/general-election-2015/11093857/Boris-Johnson-selected-to-stand-for-Tories-in-Uxbridge-and-South-Ruislip.html|archive-date=4 April 2015|access-date=5 May 2021|url-access=limited}}</ref> In the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], Johnson was elected. There was speculation that he had returned to Parliament because he wanted to replace Cameron as Conservative leader and prime minister.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.londonlovesbusiness.com/business-news/politics/boris-johnson-lacks-the-skills-to-be-prime-minister-says-tory-chairman/3431.article|title=Boris Johnson lacks the skills to be prime minister, says Tory chairman|last=Bennett|first=Asa|date=17 September 2012|access-date=8 October 2012|publisher=LondonlovesBusiness.com|archive-date=7 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121007233049/http://www.londonlovesbusiness.com/business-news/politics/boris-johnson-lacks-the-skills-to-be-prime-minister-says-tory-chairman/3431.article|url-status=dead}}</ref>

===Brexit campaign: 2015–2016===
{{Main|Vote Leave}}
In February 2016, Johnson endorsed [[Vote Leave]] in the "Out" campaign for the [[2016 European Union membership referendum]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-35626621 |title=Boris Johnson says UK is better off outside the EU |date=21 February 2016 |access-date=21 February 2016 |work=BBC News |archive-date=21 February 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160221191306/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-35626621 |url-status=live }}</ref> Following this announcement, which was interpreted by financial markets as making Brexit more probable, the [[pound sterling]] slumped by nearly 2% against the US dollar, reaching its lowest level since March 2009.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wearden |first=Graeme |title=Pound hits seven-year low after Boris Johnson's Brexit decision |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/live/2016/feb/22/pound-falls-city-gets-brexit-jitters-business-live |access-date=22 February 2016 |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=22 February 2016 |archive-date=6 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206062530/https://www.theguardian.com/business/live/2016/feb/22/pound-falls-city-gets-brexit-jitters-business-live |url-status=live }}</ref>

In April 2016, in response to a comment by President [[Barack Obama]] that Britain should remain in the European Union, Johnson wrote an "ancestral dislike" of Britain owing to his "part-Kenyan" background may have shaped Obama's views.<ref name="controversial">{{cite news |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/36793900/boris-johnsons-most-controversial-foreign-insults |title=Boris Johnson's most controversial foreign insults |work=[[BBC Newsbeat]] |date=14 July 2016 |access-date=18 April 2018 |archive-date=24 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201124002947/http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/36793900/boris-johnsons-most-controversial-foreign-insults |url-status=live }}</ref> Several politicians condemned his comments as racist and unacceptable.<ref name="ObamaSmear">{{cite news |title=Obama hits back at Boris Johnson's alleged smears |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36112694 |access-date=23 April 2016 |work=BBC News |date=22 April 2016 |archive-date=6 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206062352/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36112694 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="ToIApril16">{{cite news |last=Lawless |first=Jill |title=London mayor under fire for 'loaded' criticism of 'part-Kenyan' Obama |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/london-mayor-under-fire-for-loaded-criticism-of-part-kenyan-obama/ |access-date=23 April 2016 |work=[[The Times of Israel]] |location=Jerusalem |date=22 April 2016 |archive-date=6 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206062443/https://www.timesofisrael.com/london-mayor-under-fire-for-loaded-criticism-of-part-kenyan-obama/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Obama">{{cite news |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36112694 |title=Obama hits back at Boris Johnson's alleged smears |work=BBC News |date=22 April 2016 |access-date=18 April 2018 |archive-date=6 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206062352/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36112694 |url-status=live }}</ref> Conversely, former Conservative Party leader [[Iain Duncan Smith]] and [[UK Independence Party]] (UKIP) leader [[Nigel Farage]] defended them.<ref name="ObamaSmear" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-was-not-racist-to-suggest-barack-obamas-part-kenyan-heritage-made-him-dislike-britain-a6999261.html |title=Boris Johnson was not racist about Barack Obama, Iain Duncan Smith insists |date=25 April 2016 |work=The Independent |location=London |last=Stone |first=Jon |access-date=26 April 2016 |archive-date=26 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426165001/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-was-not-racist-to-suggest-barack-obamas-part-kenyan-heritage-made-him-dislike-britain-a6999261.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

Johnson supported Vote Leave's statement that the government was committed to [[Turkish accession to the EU]]. Vote Leave was accused of implying that 80&nbsp;million Turks would come to the UK if it stayed in the EU. When interviewed in January 2019, he said he had not mentioned Turkey during the campaign.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-46926119 |title=Brexit: Did Boris Johnson talk Turkey during referendum campaign? |work=BBC News |date=18 January 2019 |access-date=24 January 2019 |archive-date=6 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206062518/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-46926119 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.voteleavetakecontrol.org/letter_to_the_prime_minister_and_foreign_secretary_getting_the_facts_clear_on_turkey.html |title=Letter to the Prime Minister and Foreign Secretary – Getting the facts clear on Turkey |date=16 June 2016 |website=VoteLeave |access-date=24 January 2019 |archive-date=20 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920114612/http://www.voteleavetakecontrol.org/letter_to_the_prime_minister_and_foreign_secretary_getting_the_facts_clear_on_turkey.html |url-status=live }}</ref> On 22&nbsp;June 2016, Johnson declared 23&nbsp;June could be "Britain's independence day" in a televised debate.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wilkinson |first=Michael |date=21 June 2016 |title=EU debate: Boris Johnson says Brexit will be 'Britain's independence day' as Ruth Davidson attacks 'lies' of Leave campaign in front of 6,000-strong Wembley audience |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/21/eu-debate-boris-johnson-vs-sadiq-khan-in-final-bbc-showdown-with/ |url-status=live |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |archive-url=https://archive.today/20160622165556/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/21/eu-debate-boris-johnson-vs-sadiq-khan-in-final-bbc-showdown-with/ |archive-date=22 June 2016 |url-access=limited |access-date=5 May 2021}}</ref>

Following the victory of the "Leave" campaign, Cameron resigned. Johnson was widely regarded as the front-runner to succeed him.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/24/boris-johnson-favourite-to-replace-david-cameron-as-pm-after-brexit |title=Boris Johnson Favourite to replace David Cameron as PM after Brexit |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=24 June 2016 |access-date=30 June 2016 |archive-date=6 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206062547/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/24/boris-johnson-favourite-to-replace-david-cameron-as-pm-after-brexit |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Cowburn |first=Ashley |date=30 June 2016 |title=Michael Gove's statement on running for Tory leadership against Boris Johnson |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/michael-goves-statement-on-running-for-tory-leadership-against-boris-johnson-read-it-in-full-a7110596.html |work=The Independent |location=London |access-date=30 June 2016 |archive-date=12 May 2022 |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220512/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/michael-goves-statement-on-running-for-tory-leadership-against-boris-johnson-read-it-in-full-a7110596.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Johnson announced he would not stand in the [[2016 Conservative Party leadership election|Conservative leadership election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36672591|title=Boris Johnson rules himself out of Conservative leader race|work=BBC News|date=30 June 2016|access-date=30 June 2016|archive-date=1 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701043501/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36672591|url-status=live}}</ref> Shortly before this, Michael Gove, hitherto a Johnson ally, concluded that Johnson "cannot provide the leadership or build the team for the task ahead".<ref>{{cite news |last=Witte |first=Griff |date=30 June 2016 |title=Stung by a betrayal, former London mayor Boris Johnson ends bid to lead Britain |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/boris-johnsons-path-to-british-prime-ministership-scrambled-by-allys-defection/2016/06/30/c8c7476e-3df8-11e6-9e16-4cf01a41decb_story.html |newspaper=The Washington Post |access-date=30 June 2016 |archive-date=6 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206062624/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/boris-johnsons-path-to-british-prime-ministership-scrambled-by-allys-defection/2016/06/30/c8c7476e-3df8-11e6-9e16-4cf01a41decb_story.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Hughes |first=Laura |date=30 June 2016 |title=Conservative MPs in uproar as Boris Johnson 'rips party apart' by withdrawing from leadership contest after ambush by Michael Gove |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/30/boris-johnson-wont-run-for-prime-minister-after-michael-gove-ent/ |url-status=live |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |archive-url=https://archive.today/20160701032453/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/30/boris-johnson-wont-run-for-prime-minister-after-michael-gove-ent/ |archive-date=1 July 2016 |access-date=5 May 2021 |url-access=limited}}</ref> ''The Daily Telegraph'' called Gove's comments "the most spectacular political assassination in a generation".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Swinford |first1=Steven |last2=Hope |first2=Christopher |last3=Dominiczak |first3=Peter |author2-link=Christopher Hope (journalist) |title=Boris Johnson's allies accuse Michael Gove of 'systematic and calculated plot' to destroy his leadership hopes |url=https://www.msn.com/en-gb/news/uknews/boris-johnsons-allies-accuse-michael-gove-of-systematic-and-calculated-plot-to-destroy-his-leadership-hopes/ar-AAhPpwa?ocid=spartandhp |url-status=dead |work=The Telegraph |date=1 July 2016 |access-date=16 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819030551/http://www.msn.com/en-gb/news/uknews/boris-johnsons-allies-accuse-michael-gove-of-systematic-and-calculated-plot-to-destroy-his-leadership-hopes/ar-AAhPpwa?ocid=spartandhp |archive-date=19 August 2016 |via=MSN News}}</ref> Johnson endorsed [[Andrea Leadsom]]'s candidature, but she dropped out, leaving Theresa May to be elected uncontested.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Asthana |first1=Anushka |last2=Mason |first2=Rowena |date=4 July 2016 |title=Boris Johnson endorses Andrea Leadsom in Tory leadership bid |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/04/boris-johnson-endorses-andrea-leadsom-in-tory-leadership-bid |work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=5 July 2016 |archive-date=5 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160705141255/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/04/boris-johnson-endorses-andrea-leadsom-in-tory-leadership-bid |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Foreign Secretary: 2016–2018===
{{Main|Boris Johnson as Foreign Secretary}}
[[File:Boris johnson (cropped).jpg|thumb|Official portrait of Johnson as Foreign Secretary]]
May appointed Johnson [[Foreign Secretary|foreign secretary]] in July 2016.<ref name="BloombergFSec">{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-07-13/boris-johnson-appointed-u-k-foreign-secretary-in-may-government|title=Boris Johnson Appointed U.K. Foreign Secretary in May Government|last=Hutton|first=Robert|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.|access-date=13 July 2016|archive-date=13 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160713214652/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-07-13/boris-johnson-appointed-u-k-foreign-secretary-in-may-government|url-status=live}}</ref> Analysts saw the appointment as a tactic to weaken Johnson politically: the new positions of "[[Brexit secretary]]" and [[international trade secretary]] left the foreign secretary as a figurehead.<ref name="BloombergFSec"/><ref name="GoodForMay">{{cite news |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/staggers/2016/07/sending-boris-johnson-foreign-office-bad-britain-good-theresa-may |title=Sending Boris Johnson to the Foreign Office is bad for Britain, good for Theresa May |date=14 July 2016 |access-date=14 July 2016 |first=Stephen |last=Bush |work=New Statesman |archive-date=6 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206062706/https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/staggers/2016/07/sending-boris-johnson-foreign-office-bad-britain-good-theresa-may |url-status=live }}</ref> Johnson's appointment ensured he would often be out of the country and unable to mobilise backbenchers against her, while forcing him to take responsibility for problems caused by withdrawing from the EU.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/boris-johnson-als-britischer-aussenminister-der-muellmann-von-number-10-kommentar-a-1102927.html |title=Boris Johnson als Außenminister: Der Prügelknabe |first=Thomas |last=Hüetlin |language=de |trans-title=Boris Johnson as Foreign Secretary: The whipping boy |work=[[Der Spiegel]] |date=14 July 2016 |access-date=14 July 2016 |archive-date=6 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206062713/https://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/boris-johnson-als-britischer-aussenminister-der-muellmann-von-number-10-kommentar-a-1102927.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="NewYorker">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/john-cassidy/the-huge-challenge-facing-theresa-may |title=The Huge Challenge Facing Theresa May |first=John |last=Cassidy |date=13 July 2016 |access-date=14 July 2016 |magazine=[[The New Yorker]] |archive-date=15 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160715074715/http://www.newyorker.com/news/john-cassidy/the-huge-challenge-facing-theresa-may |url-status=live }}</ref>

Some journalists and foreign politicians criticised Johnson's appointment because of his controversial statements about other countries.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/13/boris-johnson-diplomacy-not-synonymous |title=Boris Johnson and diplomacy are not synonymous |date=13 July 2016 |access-date=14 July 2016 |work=The Guardian |first=Patrick |last=Wintour |archive-date=14 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160714061951/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/13/boris-johnson-diplomacy-not-synonymous |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="FSecReactions">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-36790977 |title=Boris Johnson is foreign secretary: The world reacts |date=14 July 2016 |access-date=14 July 2016 |work=BBC News |archive-date=14 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160714050618/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-36790977 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="GuardianReactions">{{cite news |last1=Malkin |first1=Bonnie |last2=Oltermann |first2=Philip |last3=Phillips |first3=Tom |title='Maybe the Brits are just having us on': the world reacts to Boris Johnson as foreign minister |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/14/maybe-the-brits-are-just-having-us-on-the-world-reacts-to-boris-johnson-as-foreign-minister |work=The Guardian |date=14 July 2016 |access-date=14 July 2016 |archive-date=14 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160714042917/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/14/maybe-the-brits-are-just-having-us-on-the-world-reacts-to-boris-johnson-as-foreign-minister |url-status=live }}</ref> His tenure attracted criticism from diplomats and foreign policy experts.<ref name="bbc">{{cite news|date=9 July 2018|title=Boris Johnson: What did he achieve as foreign secretary?|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-44767848|access-date=10 January 2021|archive-date=12 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210112061828/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-44767848|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="theguardian3">{{Cite news|last=Hopkins|first=Nick|date=18 July 2019|title=What diplomats really think about Boris Johnson|work=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/18/what-diplomats-really-think-about-boris-johnson|access-date=10 January 2021|issn=0261-3077|archive-date=12 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210112112454/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/18/what-diplomats-really-think-about-boris-johnson|url-status=live}}</ref> A number of diplomats, FCO staff and foreign ministers who worked with Johnson compared his leadership unfavourably to previous foreign secretaries for his perceived lack of conviction or substantive positions on foreign policy issues.<ref name="bbc"/><ref name="theguardian3"/> A senior official in Obama's government suggested Johnson's appointment would push the US further towards [[Germany–United States relations|Germany]] at the expense of the [[Special Relationship]] with the UK.<ref name="ITV20160714">{{cite news |url=http://www.itv.com/news/2016-07-13/reaction-boris-johnson-foreign-secretary-united-states-of-america/ |title=Boris Johnson's appointment as Foreign Secretary has not gone down well in the United States |first=Robert |last=Moore |date=14 July 2016 |access-date=14 July 2016 |work=ITV News |archive-date=6 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206062700/https://www.itv.com/news/2016-07-13/reaction-boris-johnson-foreign-secretary-united-states-of-america |url-status=live }}</ref> On one occasion Egyptian president [[Abdel Fattah el-Sisi]] walked out of a meeting with Johnson after a meeting did not "get beyond the pleasantries".<ref name="bbc"/>[[File:President Donald J. Trump and the British Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs Boris Johnson (37425398262).jpg|thumb|Johnson with US president [[Donald Trump]] in 2017 [[UNGA]]|left]]

Johnson's visit to Turkey in September 2016 was somewhat tense because he had won [[Douglas Murray (author)|Douglas Murray]]'s offensive poetry competition about the President of Turkey, [[Recep Tayyip Erdoğan]], four months earlier.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/05/boris-johnson-wins-the-spectators-president-erdogan-offensive-poetry-competition/|title=Boris Johnson wins The Spectator's President Erdogan Offensive Poetry competition|last=Murray|first=Douglas|date=18 May 2016|work=The Spectator|access-date=31 March 2017|archive-date=22 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722114604/https://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/05/boris-johnson-wins-the-spectators-president-erdogan-offensive-poetry-competition/|url-status=dead}}</ref> When questioned by a journalist whether he would apologise for the poem, Johnson dismissed the matter as "trivia".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/09/boris-johnson-refuses-apologise-insulting-president-erdogan/|title=Boris Johnson refuses to apologise for his President Erdogan poem|author=Steerpike|date=27 September 2016|work=The Spectator|access-date=31 March 2017|archive-date=9 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191209035848/https://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/09/boris-johnson-refuses-apologise-insulting-president-erdogan/|url-status=dead}}</ref> Johnson pledged to help [[Accession of Turkey to the European Union|Turkey join the EU]] and expressed support for Erdogan's government.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.eu/article/boris-johnson-uk-will-help-turkey-join-the-eu/|title=Boris Johnson: UK will help Turkey join the EU|date=28 September 2016|work=[[Politico]]|access-date=1 October 2016|archive-date=6 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206062810/https://www.politico.eu/article/boris-johnson-uk-will-help-turkey-join-the-eu/|url-status=live}}</ref> Johnson described the [[Gülen movement]] as a "cult" and supported [[2016–present purges in Turkey|Turkey's post-coup purges]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Boris Johnson says he will help Turkey hunt for Gulenists in the UK |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/boris-johnson-pledges-to-help-turkey-get-to-the-bottom-of-gulenist-links-in-the-uk-2016-9 |work=[[Business Insider]] |date=28 September 2016 |access-date=26 July 2019 |archive-date=8 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220608210837/https://www.businessinsider.com/boris-johnson-pledges-to-help-turkey-get-to-the-bottom-of-gulenist-links-in-the-uk-2016-9 |url-status=live }}</ref>
Johnson supported the [[Saudi Arabian–led intervention in Yemen]] and refused to block UK arms sales to Saudi Arabia.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-urged-to-back-probe-into-international-law-violations-during-yemen-war-a7321496.html |title=Boris Johnson urged to back probe into international law violations in Yemen |work=The Independent |date=21 September 2016 |access-date=24 August 2017 |archive-date=16 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220516152829/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-urged-to-back-probe-into-international-law-violations-during-yemen-war-a7321496.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/sep/05/mps-to-urge-ban-on-uk-arms-sales-to-saudi-arabia |title=Boris Johnson defends UK arms sales to Saudi Arabia |work=The Guardian |date=5 September 2016 |access-date=26 September 2016 |archive-date=6 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206062748/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/sep/05/mps-to-urge-ban-on-uk-arms-sales-to-saudi-arabia |url-status=live }}</ref> In September 2016, human rights groups accused him of blocking the UN inquiry into Saudi war crimes in Yemen.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/boris-johnson-yemen-criticised-human-rights-watch-amnesty-international-blocking-war-crimes-inquiry-a7330136.html |title=Boris Johnson criticised by human rights groups after blocking inquiry into war crimes in Yemen |work=The Independent |date=27 September 2016 |access-date=24 August 2017 |archive-date=11 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220711094920/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/boris-johnson-yemen-criticised-human-rights-watch-amnesty-international-blocking-war-crimes-inquiry-a7330136.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Given the UK-Saudi alliance, in December 2016, he attracted attention for commenting the Saudis were akin to the Iranians in "puppeteering and playing [[Iran–Saudi Arabia proxy conflict|proxy wars]]".<ref name="bbc.co.uk">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-38245902|title=Boris Johnson accuses Saudi Arabia of 'playing proxy wars'|date=8 December 2016|access-date=4 May 2017|work=BBC News|archive-date=9 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609070313/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-38245902|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Tovey|first=Alan|date=8 March 2015|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/industry/defence/11455304/Charted-the-worlds-biggest-arms-importers.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/industry/defence/11455304/Charted-the-worlds-biggest-arms-importers.html |archive-date=10 January 2022 |url-status=live|title=Charted: the world's biggest arms importers|work=The Telegraph|access-date=5 May 2021|url-access=limited}}{{cbignore}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/12/08/boris-johnson-theresa-may-odds-pm-rebukes-foreign-secretary/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/12/08/boris-johnson-theresa-may-odds-pm-rebukes-foreign-secretary/ |archive-date=10 January 2022 |url-status=live|title=Row over Saudi Arabia comments blows open rift between Theresa May and Boris Johnson|first=Peter|last=Dominiczak|date=8 December 2016|work=The Daily Telegraph|url-access=limited|access-date=5 May 2021}}{{cbignore}}</ref> In November 2017, Johnson told the [[Foreign Affairs Select Committee]] that [[Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe]] – a British-Iranian citizen imprisoned in Iran after being arrested for training citizen journalists and bloggers in a [[BBC World Service Trust]] project – had been "simply teaching people journalism". Facing criticism, Johnson stated he had been misquoted and that nothing he said had justified Zaghari-Ratcliffe's sentence.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-41890885|title=Fears for Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe after Boris Johnson remark|work=BBC News|date=6 November 2017|access-date=7 November 2017|archive-date=7 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107000818/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-41890885|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Rawlinson|first=Kevin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/nov/07/boris-johnson-to-call-iran-in-wake-of-comments-about-jailed-briton|title=Boris Johnson to call Iran in wake of comments about jailed Briton|work=The Guardian|date=7 November 2017|access-date=7 November 2017|archive-date=7 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107083414/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/nov/07/boris-johnson-to-call-iran-in-wake-of-comments-about-jailed-briton|url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2018, Johnson backed<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.breakingnews.ie/world/boris-johnson-defends-iran-nuclear-deal-after-israeli-claims-840284.html|title=Boris Johnson defends Iran nuclear deal after Israeli claims|date=1 May 2018|access-date=16 May 2018|archive-date=10 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190610060854/https://www.breakingnews.ie/world/boris-johnson-defends-iran-nuclear-deal-after-israeli-claims-840284.html|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/may/09/uk-will-not-follow-trump-in-ditching-iran-deal-boris-johnson-vows|title=UK will not follow Trump in ditching Iran deal, Boris Johnson vows|last=Wintour|first=Patrick|date=9 May 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=21 July 2018|archive-date=6 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206063117/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/may/09/uk-will-not-follow-trump-in-ditching-iran-deal-boris-johnson-vows|url-status=live}}</ref> the [[Iran nuclear deal framework]], despite Donald Trump's withdrawal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/article/2018/may/08/trump-withdrew-us-iran-nuclear-deal-heres-what-you/|title=Trump pulls US out of Iran deal: Here's what to know|website=PolitiFact|access-date=12 July 2019|archive-date=20 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190620035332/https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/article/2018/may/08/trump-withdrew-us-iran-nuclear-deal-heres-what-you/|url-status=live}}</ref>[[File:Boris Johnson in the British Virgin Islands after Irma.jpg|thumb|Johnson visiting the [[British Virgin Islands]] after [[Hurricane Irma]]]]

In April 2017, Johnson said that [[Status of Gibraltar|Gibraltar's sovereignty]] was "not going to change" after Brexit.<ref>{{cite news |title=Brexit and Gibraltar: May laughs off Spain 'war' talk |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-39475127 |work=BBC News |date=3 April 2017 |access-date=22 July 2019 |archive-date=16 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220516152829/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-39475127 |url-status=live }}</ref> Johnson promised while in [[Northern Ireland]] that Brexit would leave the Irish border "absolutely unchanged".<ref>{{cite news |title=How would Boris Johnson solve the Irish border problem? |url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2019/06/how-would-boris-johnson-solve-irish-border-problem |work=New Statesman |date=12 June 2019 |access-date=22 July 2019 |archive-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406193216/https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2019/06/how-would-boris-johnson-solve-irish-border-problem |url-status=live }}</ref> Johnson visited [[Anguilla]] and [[Tortola]] in September 2017 to confirm the UK's commitment to helping restore [[British Virgin Islands|British territories]] devastated by [[Hurricane Irma]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bvtnews.com/news/french-british-officials-view-irmas-damage-vow-island-aid.html |title=French, British officials view Irma's damage, vow island aid |access-date=13 September 2017 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914035407/http://bvtnews.com/news/french-british-officials-view-irmas-damage-vow-island-aid.html |archive-date=14 September 2017 }}</ref>
In September 2017, he was criticised for reciting lines from [[Rudyard Kipling]]'s poem ''[[Mandalay (poem)|Mandalay]]'' while visiting a [[Myanmar]] temple; the British ambassador, who was with him, suggested it was "not appropriate".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/2017-09-30/ambassador-stops-boris-johnson-quoting-colonial-poem-in-burmese-temple/|title=Ambassador stops Boris Johnson 'reciting colonial poem' in Burmese temple|date=30 September 2017|access-date=4 November 2017|publisher=ITV|archive-date=6 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206062940/https://www.itv.com/news/2017-09-30/ambassador-stops-boris-johnson-quoting-colonial-poem-in-burmese-temple|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/boris-johnson-caught-on-camera-quoting-kipling-poem-in-burmese-temple-a3647431.html|title=Boris Johnson 'caught on camera quoting Kipling poem in Burmese temple'|first=Patrick|last=Grafton-Green|date=30 September 2017|work=Evening Standard|access-date=30 September 2017|archive-date=6 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206062945/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/boris-johnson-caught-on-camera-quoting-kipling-poem-in-burmese-temple-a3647431.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/sep/30/boris-johnson-caught-on-camera-reciting-kipling-in-myanmar-temple|title=Boris Johnson caught on camera reciting Kipling in Myanmar temple|first=Robert|last=Booth|date=30 September 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=4 October 2017|archive-date=3 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003230022/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/sep/30/boris-johnson-caught-on-camera-reciting-kipling-in-myanmar-temple|url-status=live}}</ref> In October 2017, he faced criticism for stating the Libyan city of [[Sirte]] could become an economic success like [[Dubai]]: "all they have to do is clear the dead bodies away".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-41490174 |title=Boris Johnson Libya 'dead bodies' comment provokes anger |date=4 October 2017 |work=BBC News |access-date=4 October 2017 |archive-date=3 October 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003235522/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-41490174 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=5 October 2017 |title=Is Boris Johnson really unsackable? |url=https://www.economist.com/britain/2017/10/05/is-boris-johnson-really-unsackable |url-status=live |newspaper=[[The Economist]] |archive-url=https://archive.today/20210430170216/https://www.economist.com/britain/2017/10/05/is-boris-johnson-really-unsackable |archive-date=30 April 2021 |access-date=5 May 2021 |url-access=subscription}}</ref>

Initially favouring a less hostile approach to Russia,<ref>{{cite news |last=Webber |first=Esther |title=I was a fool to think we could reset relations with Russia, says Johnson |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/i-was-a-fool-to-think-we-could-reset-relations-with-russia-says-johnson-vpm2wgr9k |access-date=2 May 2022 |work=The Times |date=14 February 2018 |archive-date=2 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220502231740/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/i-was-a-fool-to-think-we-could-reset-relations-with-russia-says-johnson-vpm2wgr9k |url-status=live }}</ref> Johnson soon backed a more aggressive policy.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Kremlin conundrum facing Boris Johnson |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/the-kremlin-conundrum-facing-boris-johnson-q6l336t29 |work=The Times |date=23 July 2019 |url-access=subscription |access-date=16 April 2020 |archive-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406193211/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/the-kremlin-conundrum-facing-boris-johnson-q6l336t29 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=What has Boris Johnson said about other countries and their leaders? |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-49014791 |work=BBC News |date=24 July 2019 |access-date=26 July 2019 |archive-date=1 July 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200701111427/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-49014791 |url-status=live }}</ref> Following the March 2018 [[poisoning of Sergei and Yulia Skripal]] in [[Salisbury]], an act which the UK government blamed on Russia,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-43367515|title=PM under pressure over Russian spy case|date=12 March 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=28 March 2018|archive-date=25 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180325073938/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-43367515|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Boris Johnson accused of making misleading Russia Novichok claim in DW interview |url=http://www.dw.com/en/boris-johnson-accused-of-making-misleading-russia-novichok-claim-in-dw-interview/a-43251856 |publisher=Deutsche Welle |date=4 April 2018 |access-date=24 July 2019 |archive-date=1 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220201012922/https://www.dw.com/en/boris-johnson-accused-of-making-misleading-russia-novichok-claim-in-dw-interview/a-43251856 |url-status=live }}</ref> Johnson compared [[Vladimir Putin]]'s hosting of the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|World Cup in Russia]] to [[Adolf Hitler]]'s hosting of the [[Olympic Games in Berlin]] in 1936.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/mar/21/boris-johnson-compares-russian-world-cup-to-hitlers-1936-olympics |title=Boris Johnson compares Russian World Cup to Hitler's 1936 Olympics |last=Wintour |first=Patrick |date=21 March 2018 |work=The Guardian |access-date=28 March 2018 |archive-date=22 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180322225603/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/mar/21/boris-johnson-compares-russian-world-cup-to-hitlers-1936-olympics |url-status=live }}</ref> Russia's Foreign Ministry denounced Johnson's "unacceptable and unworthy" parallel towards Russia, a "nation that [[World War II casualties of the Soviet Union|lost millions of lives]] in fighting Nazism".<ref>{{cite news |title=Sergei Skripal: Chemical weapons inspectors arrive in Salisbury to investigate nerve agent attack |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/salisbury-chemical-weapons-inspectors-international-arrive-investigate-nerve-agent-attack-a8267546.html |last=Osborne |first=Samuel |work=The Independent |date=21 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619063045/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/salisbury-chemical-weapons-inspectors-international-arrive-investigate-nerve-agent-attack-a8267546.html |archive-date=19 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Johnson described the [[Nord Stream&nbsp;2]] gas pipeline from Russia to Germany as "divisive" and a "threat" that left Europe dependent on a "malign Russia" for its [[Russia in the European energy sector|energy supplies]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Boris Johnson joins US in criticising Russia to Germany gas pipeline |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/may/22/boris-johnson-joins-us-criticising-russia-germany-gas-pipeline-nord-stream-2 |work=The Guardian |date=22 May 2018 |access-date=26 July 2019 |archive-date=26 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726235724/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/may/22/boris-johnson-joins-us-criticising-russia-germany-gas-pipeline-nord-stream-2 |url-status=live }}</ref>

Johnson condemned the [[Rohingya genocide|persecution]] of [[Rohingya Muslims]] in Myanmar,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/frontpage/direct-cargo-flights-dhaka-uk-lift-ban-shortly-1532539|title=Direct Cargo Flights from Dhaka: UK to lift ban shortly|work=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]|date=10 February 2018|access-date=22 July 2019|archive-date=23 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723000423/https://www.thedailystar.net/frontpage/direct-cargo-flights-dhaka-uk-lift-ban-shortly-1532539|url-status=live}}</ref> comparing the situation with the [[Palestinian refugees|displacement of Palestinians]] in 1948.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/foreign-affairs/2018/02/09/boris-johnson-rohingya-crisis-humanitarian-disaster/ |title=Boris Johnson for quick repatriation of Rohingyas |work=[[Dhaka Tribune]] |date=9 February 2018 |access-date=22 July 2019 |archive-date=22 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722233937/https://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/foreign-affairs/2018/02/09/boris-johnson-rohingya-crisis-humanitarian-disaster/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Johnson supported the [[Turkish military operation in Afrin|Turkish invasion of northern Syria]] aimed at ousting the [[People's Protection Units|Syrian Kurds]] from [[Afrin, Syria|Afrin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aa.com.tr/en/europe/uk-turkey-has-legitimate-interest-in-border-security/1038748|title=UK: Turkey has legitimate interest in border security|date=22 January 2018|publisher=[[Anadolu Agency]]|access-date=22 July 2019|archive-date=22 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722233943/https://www.aa.com.tr/en/europe/uk-turkey-has-legitimate-interest-in-border-security/1038748|url-status=live}}</ref> He accused the [[UNHRC]] of focusing disproportionately on the [[Israeli–Palestinian conflict]] and Israel's [[Israeli-occupied territories|occupation]] of the [[Palestinian territories]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Britain condemns 'anti-Israel bias' at UN Human Rights Council |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/britain-condemns-anti-israel-bias-at-un-human-rights-council/ |work=[[The Times of Israel]] |date=18 June 2018 |access-date=23 July 2019 |archive-date=16 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220516210339/https://www.timesofisrael.com/britain-condemns-anti-israel-bias-at-un-human-rights-council/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

[[File:Javad Zarif meeting with UK foreign minister Boris Johnson in Tehran 2017-12-09 02.jpg|thumb|left|Johnson meeting with Iranian foreign minister [[Mohammad Javad Zarif]] in Tehran in December 2017]]
In a September 2017 op-ed, Johnson reiterated the UK would regain control of £350m a week after Brexit, suggesting it go to the [[National Health Service]] (NHS).<ref>{{Cite news|last=Johnson|first=Boris|date=15 September 2017 |title=My vision for a bold, thriving Britain enabled by Brexit|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/09/15/boris-johnson-vision-bold-thriving-britain-enabled-brexit/|url-status=live|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|issn=0307-1235 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20170915205019/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/09/15/boris-johnson-vision-bold-thriving-britain-enabled-brexit/|archive-date=15 September 2017|access-date=5 May 2021|url-access=limited}}</ref> Cabinet colleagues subsequently criticised him for reviving the assertion.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/sep/17/boris-johnson-slapped-down-statistics-chief-fresh-350m-brexit-claim|title=Boris Johnson left isolated as row grows over £350m post-Brexit claim|last=Asthana|first=Anushka|date=17 September 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=18 September 2017|issn=0261-3077|archive-date=17 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170917223917/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/sep/17/boris-johnson-slapped-down-statistics-chief-fresh-350m-brexit-claim|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="beebsplit">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-41301049|title=Brexit: Boris Johnson and stats chief in row over £350m figure|work=BBC News|access-date=21 June 2018|archive-date=31 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220331170046/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-41301049|url-status=live}}</ref> Following the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]], Johnson denied media reports he intended to challenge May's leadership.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/boris-johnson-denies-plot-topple-uk-pm-theresa-47965138 |title=Boris Johnson denies plot to topple UK PM Theresa May |access-date=11 June 2017 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170611110240/http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/boris-johnson-denies-plot-topple-uk-pm-theresa-47965138 |archive-date=11 June 2017}}</ref> In a February 2018 letter to May, Johnson suggested that Northern Ireland may have to accept border controls after Brexit and that it would not seriously affect trade, having initially said a hard border would be unthinkable.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2018/02/28/boris-johnson-accuses-remainers-trying-use-irish-border-issue/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2018/02/28/boris-johnson-accuses-remainers-trying-use-irish-border-issue/ |archive-date=10 January 2022 |url-status=live |title=Boris Johnson accuses Remainers of trying to use Irish border issue to stop the UK leaving the EU |last=Maidment |first=Jack |date=28 February 2018 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |url-access=limited |access-date=5 May 2021}}{{cbignore}}</ref> In June, he was reported as having said "fuck business" when asked about corporate concerns regarding a 'hard' Brexit.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Crisp |first1=James |last2=Foster |first2=Peter |last3=Rayner |first3=Gordon |date=23 June 2018 |title=EU diplomats shocked by Boris's 'four-letter reply' to business concerns about Brexit |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2018/06/23/eu-diplomats-shocked-boriss-four-letter-reply-business-concerns/ |url-status=live |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |archive-url=https://archive.today/20180623084046/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2018/06/23/eu-diplomats-shocked-boriss-four-letter-reply-business-concerns/ |archive-date=23 June 2018 |access-date=5 May 2021 |url-access=limited}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/jun/24/tide-turning-brexit-will-of-people-boris-johnson|title=Enough already: in the national interest, we must stop a hard Brexit|date=24 June 2018|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=24 June 2018|archive-date=6 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206063103/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/jun/24/tide-turning-brexit-will-of-people-boris-johnson|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenational.scot/news/16310206.EU_diplomats_reveal_Boris_Johnson_said__f__k_business__over_Brexit_fears/|title=EU diplomats reveal Boris Johnson said 'f**k business' over Brexit fears|date=23 June 2018|work=The National|access-date=24 June 2018|archive-date=28 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180828213801/http://www.thenational.scot/news/16310206.EU_diplomats_reveal_Boris_Johnson_said__f__k_business__over_Brexit_fears/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-44618154|title=Johnson challenged over 'Brexit expletive'|date=26 June 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=27 June 2018|archive-date=6 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206063131/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-44618154|url-status=live}}</ref>

[[File:Boris Johnson with Gordon Brown in London - 2018 (27295267767).jpg|thumb|Johnson with former UK prime minister [[Gordon Brown]] in May 2018]]
Secret recordings obtained by ''[[BuzzFeed News]]'' in June 2018 revealed Johnson's dissatisfaction with Prime Minister Theresa May's negotiating style, accusing her of being too collaborative with the European Union in Brexit negotiations. Comparing May's approach to that of the US president Donald Trump – who at the time was engaged in a combative trade war with the EU because it raised tariffs on metal – Johnson said: "Imagine Trump doing Brexit. He'd go in bloody hard&nbsp;... There'd be all sorts of breakdowns, all sorts of chaos. Everyone would think he'd gone mad. But actually you might get somewhere." He accused individuals of scaremongering over a Brexit "meltdown", saying "No panic. ''[[Pro bono publico]]'', no bloody panic. It's going to be all right in the end."<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pitas |first1=Costas |title=Brace for a possible 'Brexit meltdown' but don't panic, Johnson says -BuzzFeed |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-eu-johnson/brace-for-a-possible-brexit-meltdown-but-dont-panic-johnson-says-buzzfeed-idUSKCN1J40LJ |access-date=25 August 2019 |work=Reuters |date=8 June 2018 |archive-date=25 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190825164238/https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-eu-johnson/brace-for-a-possible-brexit-meltdown-but-dont-panic-johnson-says-buzzfeed-idUSKCN1J40LJ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In April 2018, Johnson travelled to Italy to attend a party at the [[Palazzo Terranova]], owned by the former [[KGB]] agent [[Alexander Lebedev]] and hosted by his son [[Evgeny Lebedev|Evgeny]]. He travelled without security protection or other officials,<ref name="Culbertson 2022 a393">{{cite web | last=Culbertson | first=Alix | title=Boris Johnson fails to provide further details of meeting with ex-KGB agent Alexander Lebedev | website=Sky News | date=26 July 2022 | url=https://news.sky.com/story/boris-johnson-fails-to-provide-further-details-of-meeting-with-ex-kgb-agent-alexander-lebedev-12659456 | access-date=28 June 2023 | archive-date=28 June 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230628084349/https://news.sky.com/story/boris-johnson-fails-to-provide-further-details-of-meeting-with-ex-kgb-agent-alexander-lebedev-12659456 | url-status=live }}</ref> and did not document the trip, which led to accusations of Johnson having misled parliament.<ref name="Maidment 2022 r017">{{cite web | last=Maidment | first=Jack | title=Boris Johnson accused of misleading Parliament over meeting with Alexander Lebedev | website=The Telegraph | date=7 July 2022 | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2022/07/07/boris-johnson-accused-misleading-parliament-meeting-alexander/ | access-date=28 June 2023 | archive-date=28 June 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230628092935/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2022/07/07/boris-johnson-accused-misleading-parliament-meeting-alexander/ | url-status=live }}</ref> In June 2023, it was revealed that Lord Simon McDonald, the most senior civil servant of his department, was not aware of the trip. Johnson stated that "no government business was discussed" at the event as far as he was aware.<ref name="The Independent 2022 e651">{{cite web | title=UK's Boris Johnson defends meeting ex-KGB agent at party | website=The Independent | date=26 July 2022 | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-ap-evgeny-lebedev-london-conservative-party-b2131696.html | access-date=28 June 2023 | archive-date=28 June 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230628085232/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-ap-evgeny-lebedev-london-conservative-party-b2131696.html | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Financial Times 2023 b191">{{cite web | title=Boris Johnson faces fresh questions over 2018 party at Lebedev villa | website=Financial Times | date=27 June 2023 | url=https://www.ft.com/content/53d32fbc-a1e5-495b-b068-cf7d7a202f78 | access-date=28 June 2023 | archive-date=28 June 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230628044856/https://www.ft.com/content/53d32fbc-a1e5-495b-b068-cf7d7a202f78 | url-status=live }}</ref> Lebedev's villa was monitored by the Italian secret service at the time, who, according to a [[Channel 4]] documentary, suspected it to be used for espionage activities.<ref name="Crerar 2023 n661">{{cite web | last=Crerar | first=Pippa | title=Italy 'was monitoring Lebedev villa at time of Boris Johnson visit' | website=The Guardian | date=26 June 2023 | url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2023/jun/26/italy-was-monitoring-lebedev-villa-at-time-of-boris-johnson-visit-documentary-claims | access-date=28 June 2023 | archive-date=27 June 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230627195227/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2023/jun/26/italy-was-monitoring-lebedev-villa-at-time-of-boris-johnson-visit-documentary-claims | url-status=live }}</ref> Johnson granted a peerage to [[Evgeny Lebedev|Evgeny]] in 2020, against the advice of the [[MI6]], and met with criticism over potential security concerns.<ref name="Freeman 2022 b237">{{cite web | last=Freeman | first=Colin | title=Boris Johnson faces fresh pressure over Lord Lebedev's peerage after oligarch father sanctioned | website=The Telegraph | date=21 May 2022 | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/world-news/2022/05/21/russian-oligarch-alexander-lebedev-hit-sanctions-canada/ | access-date=28 June 2023 | archive-date=28 June 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230628092935/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/world-news/2022/05/21/russian-oligarch-alexander-lebedev-hit-sanctions-canada/ | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="BBC News 2022 t584">{{cite news | title=Boris Johnson met Russian oligarch Lebedev without aides | website=BBC News | date=6 July 2022 | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-62068421 | access-date=28 June 2023 | archive-date=28 June 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230628092935/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-62068421 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Reporters 2022 o388">{{cite web | title=Evgeny Lebedev: MI6 warned Boris Johnson about peerage for Russian oligarch two years ago | website=The Telegraph | date=13 March 2022 | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2022/03/13/evgeny-lebedev-mi6-warned-boris-johnson-peerage-russian-oligarch/ | access-date=28 June 2023 | archive-date=28 June 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230628092936/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2022/03/13/evgeny-lebedev-mi6-warned-boris-johnson-peerage-russian-oligarch/ | url-status=live }}</ref>

In July 2018, three days after the [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom|cabinet]] had its meeting to agree on a [[The future relationship between the United Kingdom and the European Union|Brexit strategy]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-44749993 |title=At-a-glance: The new UK Brexit plan agreed at Chequers |date=7 July 2018 |work=BBC News |access-date=9 July 2018 |archive-date=6 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206063118/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-44749993 |url-status=live }}</ref> Johnson, along with Brexit secretary [[David Davis (British politician)|David Davis]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jul/08/david-davis-resigns-as-brexit-secretary-reports-say |title=Brexit secretary David Davis resigns plunging government into crisis |last=Stewart |first=Heather |date=9 July 2018 |work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=9 July 2018 |archive-date=31 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731123700/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jul/08/david-davis-resigns-as-brexit-secretary-reports-say |url-status=live }}</ref> resigned his post.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jul/09/boris-johnson-resigns-as-foreign-secretary-brexit |title=May's plan 'sticks in the throat', says Boris Johnson as he resigns over Brexit |date=9 July 2018 |work=The Guardian |location=London |first1=Heather |last1=Stewart |first2=Pippa |last2=Crerar |first3=Dan |last3=Sabbagh |access-date=9 July 2018 |archive-date=31 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831034544/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jul/09/boris-johnson-resigns-as-foreign-secretary-brexit |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Return to the backbenches: 2018–2019===
Johnson returned to the role of a [[backbench MP]]. In July, he delivered a resignation speech, stating "it is not too late to save Brexit".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-44871629|title=Johnson: It is not too late to save Brexit|date=18 July 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=18 July 2018|archive-date=6 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206063209/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-44871629|url-status=live}}</ref> In January 2019, Johnson came under criticism for remarks he had made during the 2016 Leave campaign regarding the prospect of Turkish accession to the European Union; he denied making such remarks.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2019-01-18/boris-johnson-under-attack-over-turkey-claim/|title=Boris Johnson under attack over Turkey claim|website=[[ITV News]]|date=18 January 2019|access-date=21 January 2019|archive-date=21 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121233545/https://www.itv.com/news/2019-01-18/boris-johnson-under-attack-over-turkey-claim/|url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2019, he was criticized for saying that expenditure on investigating historic allegations of child abuse was money "spaffed up the wall".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/uk/boris-johnson-hits-out-at-police-spending-on-historic-child-abuse-probes-37909038.html|title=Boris Johnson hits out at police spending on historic child abuse probes|access-date=13 March 2019|work=[[The Belfast Telegraph]]|archive-date=28 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328231217/https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/uk/boris-johnson-hits-out-at-police-spending-on-historic-child-abuse-probes-37909038.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-47560192|title=Boris Johnson historical child sex abuse comments 'horrific'|work=BBC News|date=13 March 2019|access-date=13 March 2019|archive-date=14 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190314010848/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-47560192|url-status=live}}</ref>

====Journalism====
In July 2018, Johnson signed a 12‑<!--nb hyphen -->month contract to write articles for the [[Telegraph Media Group]].<ref name="gov">{{cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/732866/180808_Boris_Johnson_The_Telegraph.pdf|title=ACOBA Letter to Johnson|date=8 August 2018|access-date=9 August 2018|archive-date=9 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180809183849/https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/732866/180808_Boris_Johnson_The_Telegraph.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Advisory Committee on Business Appointments]] (ACOBA) reported that this was a breach of the [[Ministerial Code]].<ref name="gov"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-45121976|title=Johnson's Telegraph contract broke rules|date=9 August 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=9 August 2018|archive-date=6 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206063225/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-45121976|url-status=live}}</ref> Johnson was ordered to apologise for failing to declare £50,000 of earnings. The [[Parliamentary Commissioner for Standards]] found the errors were not inadvertent, and that Johnson had failed on nine occasions to make declarations within the rules.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/boris-johnson-ordered-to-apologise-to-parliament-for-failing-to-declare-earnings-2018-12|title=Boris Johnson ordered to apologise to Parliament for failing to declare earnings|first=Adam|last=Bienkov|website=[[Business Insider]]|access-date=8 December 2018|date=6 December 2018|archive-date=9 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190609143258/https://www.businessinsider.com/boris-johnson-ordered-to-apologise-to-parliament-for-failing-to-declare-earnings-2018-12|url-status=live}}</ref>

In September 2018, Johnson wrote: "We have opened ourselves to perpetual political blackmail. We have wrapped a suicide vest around the British constitution – and handed the detonator to [[Michel Barnier]]." Senior Tories heavily criticised him, with [[Alan Duncan]] of the Foreign Office vowing to ensure the comments marked "the political end of Boris Johnson".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/sep/09/boris-johnson-calls-theresa-may-chequers-brexit-plan-suicide-vest|title=Tories condemn Boris Johnson for Brexit 'suicide vest' remarks|first=Peter|last=Walker|date=9 September 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=9 September 2018|archive-date=6 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206063258/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/sep/09/boris-johnson-calls-theresa-may-chequers-brexit-plan-suicide-vest|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/boris-johnson-disgusting-criticism-theresa-may-conservative-row-chequers-plan-suicide-vest-a8529621.html|title=Open warfare between top Tories over Boris Johnson 'suicide vest' jibe at May|work=The Independent|access-date=9 September 2018|archive-date=6 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206063302/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/boris-johnson-disgusting-criticism-theresa-may-conservative-row-chequers-plan-suicide-vest-a8529621.html|url-status=live}}</ref> In April 2019, the [[Independent Press Standards Organisation]] ruled that a claim in a 6&nbsp;January 2019 article in ''The Daily Telegraph'', "The British people won't be scared into backing a woeful Brexit deal nobody voted for", authored by Johnson,<ref name="Telegraph-2019-01">{{cite news |last1=Johnson |first1=Boris |date=6 January 2019 |title=The British people won't be scared into backing a woeful Brexit deal nobody voted for |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/01/06/british-people-wont-scared-backing-woeful-brexit-deal-nobody/ |url-status=live |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |archive-url=https://archive.today/20190107194346/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/01/06/british-people-wont-scared-backing-woeful-brexit-deal-nobody/ |archive-date=7 January 2019 |access-date=5 May 2021 |url-access=limited}}</ref> that a no-deal [[Brexit]] was "by some margin preferred by the British public" was false, and "represented a failure to take care over the accuracy of the article in breach of Clause 1 (i)" of its guidelines, and required that a correction be published.<ref name="IPSO-2019-04">{{cite web |title=00154-19 Stirling v The Daily Telegraph |url=https://www.ipso.co.uk/rulings-and-resolution-statements/ruling/?id=00154-19 |publisher=[[Independent Press Standards Organisation]] |access-date=12 April 2019 |archive-date=17 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190717141950/https://www.ipso.co.uk/rulings-and-resolution-statements/ruling/?id=00154-19 |url-status=live }}</ref>

====2019 Conservative Party leadership election====
{{main|2019 Conservative Party leadership election}}
[[File:Back Boris logo.png|thumb|The logo used by Johnson's leadership campaign in 2019]]
On 12 June 2019, Johnson launched his campaign for the [[2019 Conservative Party leadership election|Conservative Party leadership election]], saying, "we must leave the EU on 31&nbsp;October."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2019/06/full-text-boris-johnson-launches-his-tory-leadership-campaign/ |title=Full text: Boris Johnson launches his Tory leadership campaign |website=The Spectator |date=12 June 2019 |access-date=12 June 2019 |archive-date=23 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723151948/https://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2019/06/full-text-boris-johnson-launches-his-tory-leadership-campaign/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> On the campaign trail, Johnson warned of "catastrophic consequences for voter trust in politics" if the government pushed the EU for further delays. He advocated removing the [[Backstop agreement|backstop]] from any Brexit deal. On 25 and 26&nbsp;August, he announced plans to retain £7 or £9&nbsp;billion of the £39&nbsp;billion divorce payment the UK is due to transfer to the EU upon withdrawal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/boris-johnson-threatens-eu-over-brexit-divorce-bill-and-raises-general-election-stakes-zwb8xjp6z|title=Boris Johnson threatens EU over Brexit divorce bill and raises general election stakes|work=The Times|last1=Shipman|first1=Tim|last2=Wheeler|first2=Caroline|last3=Urwin|first3=Rosamund|date=25 August 2019|url-access=subscription|access-date=14 April 2020|archive-date=8 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108104511/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/boris-johnson-threatens-eu-over-brexit-divorce-bill-and-raises-general-election-stakes-zwb8xjp6z|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.sky.com/story/boris-johnson-chances-of-brexit-deal-improving-now-my-messages-have-landed-11793797 |title=Boris Johnson: 'Chances of Brexit deal improving now my messages have landed' |publisher=[[Sky News]] |last=Heffer |first=Greg |date=26 August 2019 |access-date=14 April 2020 |archive-date=4 June 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200604022802/https://news.sky.com/story/boris-johnson-chances-of-brexit-deal-improving-now-my-messages-have-landed-11793797 |url-status=live }}</ref> Johnson initially<!-- ?? when ?? ---> pledged to cut income tax for earners of more than £50,000 but backed away from this plan in June 2019 after coming under criticism in a televised [[BBC]] debate.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tory-leadership-debate-boris-johnson-no-deal-brexit-rory-stewart-tax-cut-bbc-a8964566.html |title=Boris Johnson backs down on key campaign promises during Tory leadership debate |date=18 June 2019 |website=The Independent |access-date=21 June 2019 |archive-date=19 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190719163745/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tory-leadership-debate-boris-johnson-no-deal-brexit-rory-stewart-tax-cut-bbc-a8964566.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

Johnson was elected leader with 92,153 votes (66%) to Hunt's 46,656 (34%).<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Heather |title=Boris Johnson elected new Tory leader |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/23/boris-johnson-elected-new-tory-leader-prime-minister |access-date=23 July 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=23 July 2019 |archive-date=15 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200415132811/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/23/boris-johnson-elected-new-tory-leader-prime-minister |url-status=live }}</ref>

