===First term (July–December 2019)===
{{Wikisource|Boris Johnson: First Speech as Prime Minister}}
On 24&nbsp;July 2019, the day following Johnson's election as Conservative Party leader, Queen [[Elizabeth&nbsp;II]] accepted [[Theresa May]]'s resignation and appointed Johnson as prime minister. This made Johnson the first prime minister to be born outside [[territorial evolution of the British Empire|British territories]].<ref>{{Cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|url=https://www.theamerican.co.uk/pr/ne-Boris-Johnson-First-US-Born-UK-PM|title=Boris Johnson Becomes First US born Prime Minister of Britain|date=23 July 2019|magazine=[[The American (magazine)|The American]]|location=United Kingdom|access-date=23 December 2019|archive-date=31 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220331170345/https://www.theamerican.co.uk/pr/ne-Boris-Johnson-First-US-Born-UK-PM|url-status=live}}</ref> Johnson appointed [[Dominic Cummings]] as his senior advisor.<ref>{{Cite news|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-49101464|title = Who are Boris Johnson's key advisers?|work = BBC News|date = 30 July 2019|access-date = 10 August 2019|archive-date = 20 July 2022|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20220720122645/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-49101464|url-status = live}}</ref>

====Brexit policy====
[[File:Johnson met with Macron for Brexit issue.jpg|thumb|Johnson discussing Brexit with French president [[Emmanuel Macron]] in Paris]]
[[File:Johnson signed Brexit Withdrawal Agreement.jpg|thumb|Johnson signing the Brexit Withdrawal Agreement]]
In his [[s:Boris Johnson: First Speech as Prime Minister|first speech as PM]], Johnson said that the United Kingdom would leave the European Union on 31&nbsp;October 2019 with or [[no deal Brexit|without a deal]], and promised to remove the [[Irish backstop]] from the withdrawal agreement.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/live/2019/jul/24/boris-johnson-prepares-to-enter-downing-st-and-name-cabinet-theresa-may-prime-minister-live-news|title=Boris Johnson cabinet: Sajid Javid, Priti Patel and Dominic Raab given top jobs – live news|first=Andrew|last=Sparrow|date=24 July 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=24 July 2019|archive-date=4 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210104084138/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/live/2019/jul/24/boris-johnson-prepares-to-enter-downing-st-and-name-cabinet-theresa-may-prime-minister-live-news|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Westlake |first1=M. |author-link=Martin Westlake |title=Outside the EU: Options for Britain |date=2020 |publisher=Agenda Publishing |isbn=978-1-78821-312-7 |pages=168–169 |jstor=j.ctv16qjx9d.20}}</ref> Johnson declared his intention to [[Brexit negotiations in 2019|re-open negotiations]], but talks did not immediately resume as the EU refused to accept Johnson's condition that the backstop be removed.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Woodcock |first1=Andrews |title=Boris Johnson set for Brexit deadlock after admitting no progress made with EU withdrawal agreement |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-brexit-eu-withdrawal-agreement-deadline-deal-leave-a9026001.html |access-date=30 July 2021 |work=The Independent |date=29 July 2019 |archive-date=30 July 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210730204547/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-brexit-eu-withdrawal-agreement-deadline-deal-leave-a9026001.html |url-status=live }}</ref> On 28&nbsp;August 2019, UK and EU negotiators agreed to resume regular meetings.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/aug/29/time-to-step-up-tempo-of-brexit-talks-says-bullish-boris-johnson | title = Time to step up tempo of Brexit talks, says bullish Boris Johnson | author = Heather Stewart, Severin Carrell and Jennifer Rankin | newspaper = The Guardian | date = 29 August 2019 | access-date = 30 August 2019 | archive-date = 29 August 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190829231603/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/aug/29/time-to-step-up-tempo-of-brexit-talks-says-bullish-boris-johnson | url-status = live }}</ref>

Also on 28&nbsp;August 2019, Johnson declared he had asked the Queen to [[Prorogation in the United Kingdom|prorogue Parliament]] from 10&nbsp;September, reducing the time in which Parliament could block a no-deal Brexit and causing a [[2019 British prorogation controversy|political controversy]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/aug/28/chancellor-sajid-javid-fast-tracked-spending-review-fuels-talk-of-early-election |title=Boris Johnson asks Queen to suspend parliament |last1=Elgot |first1=Jessica |date=28 August 2019 |work=The Guardian |access-date=28 August 2019 |last2=Stewart |first2=Heather |issn=0261-3077 |archive-date=14 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914021918/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/aug/28/chancellor-sajid-javid-fast-tracked-spending-review-fuels-talk-of-early-election |url-status=live }}</ref> The Queen at [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]] approved prorogation later the same day, and it began on 10&nbsp;September, scheduled to last until 14&nbsp;October.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2019/aug/28/spending-review-set-for-next-week-fuels-election-speculation-live?page=with:block-5d668a668f08ea59f447a9f1#block-5d668a668f08ea59f447a9f1|title=Brexit: Queen consents to suspension of parliament for five weeks – live news|date=28 August 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=28 August 2019|archive-date=28 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190828160847/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2019/aug/28/spending-review-set-for-next-week-fuels-election-speculation-live?page=with:block-5d668a668f08ea59f447a9f1#block-5d668a668f08ea59f447a9f1|url-status=live}}</ref> Some suggested<ref>{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Simon |last2=Graham |first2=Chris |title='A very British coup': How Europe reacted to Boris Johnson suspending parliament in Brexit push |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/08/28/backstop-wont-withdrawn-back-promise-say-eu-leaders/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/08/28/backstop-wont-withdrawn-back-promise-say-eu-leaders/ |archive-date=10 January 2022 |url-status=live |access-date=5 May 2021 |work=The Telegraph |date=29 August 2019 |url-access=limited}}{{cbignore}}</ref> that this prorogation amounted to a [[self-coup]], and on 31&nbsp;August 2019, protests occurred throughout the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news |title=Parliament suspension: Thousands protest across the UK |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-49534940 |access-date=2 September 2019 |publisher=BBC |date=31 August 2019 |archive-date=2 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902004924/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-49534940 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ferguson |first1=Donna |last2=Murphy |first2=Simon |last3=Townsend |first3=Mark |last4=Wall |first4=Tom |title=From Bodmin to Berlin, crowds vent their fury at Boris Johnson's 'coup' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/aug/31/bodmin-to-berlin-crowds-vent-fury-boris-johnson-coup |access-date=2 September 2019 |work=[[The Observer]] |date=31 August 2019 |archive-date=4 June 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200604004719/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/aug/31/bodmin-to-berlin-crowds-vent-fury-boris-johnson-coup |url-status=live }}</ref> By 2&nbsp;September 2019, three separate court cases challenging Johnson's action were in progress or scheduled to take place,<ref>{{cite news |last1=MacAskill |first1=Andrew |last2=James |first2=William |title=Factbox: UK government ensnared in court battles over suspending parliament |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-courtcases-factbox-idUSKCN1VK1LK |access-date=2 September 2019 |work=Reuters |date=30 August 2019 |archive-date=1 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190901225849/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-courtcases-factbox-idUSKCN1VK1LK |url-status=live }}</ref> and on 11&nbsp;September, three Scottish judges ruled the prorogation of the UK Parliament to be unlawful.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Carrell |first1=Severin |title=Scottish judges rule Boris Johnson's prorogation unlawful |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/sep/11/scottish-judges-rule-boris-johnsons-prorogation-unlawful |access-date=11 September 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=11 September 2019 |archive-date=4 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404093342/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/sep/11/scottish-judges-rule-boris-johnsons-prorogation-unlawful |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Brexit: Scottish judges rule Parliament suspension is unlawful |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-49661855 |access-date=11 September 2019 |work=BBC News |date=11 September 2019 |archive-date=11 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911091938/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-49661855 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 12&nbsp;September, Johnson denied lying to the Queen over suspension of the Parliament, while a Belfast Court rejected claims that his Brexit plans would have a negative impact on Northern Ireland's peace policy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cbs6albany.com/news/nation-world/johnson-denies-lying-to-queen-court-rejects-brexit-case|title=Johnson denies lying to queen; court rejects Brexit case|access-date=12 September 2019|website=6News|date=12 September 2019|archive-date=6 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406221727/https://cbs6albany.com/news/nation-world/johnson-denies-lying-to-queen-court-rejects-brexit-case|url-status=live}}</ref> On 24 September, the Supreme Court ruled unanimously that Johnson's advice to prorogue Parliament was unlawful, and therefore the prorogation was rendered null.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bowcott |first=Owen |date=24 September 2019 |title=Boris Johnson's suspension of parliament unlawful, supreme court rules |url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2019/sep/24/boris-johnsons-suspension-of-parliament-unlawful-supreme-court-rules-prorogue |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |access-date=24 September 2019 |archive-date=26 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190926203833/https://www.theguardian.com/law/2019/sep/24/boris-johnsons-suspension-of-parliament-unlawful-supreme-court-rules-prorogue |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Supreme Court: Suspending Parliament was unlawful, judges rule |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-49810261 |work=[[BBC News]] |location=London |date=24 September 2019 |access-date=24 September 2019 |archive-date=24 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190924095005/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-49810261 |url-status=live }}</ref>

When Parliament resumed on 3&nbsp;September 2019, Johnson indicated he would call a general election under the [[Fixed-term Parliaments Act]] after opposition and rebel Conservative MPs successfully voted against the government to take control of the order of business to prevent a no-deal exit.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/09/03/brexit-latest-news-boris-johnson-no-deal-vote-general-election/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/09/03/brexit-latest-news-boris-johnson-no-deal-vote-general-election/ |archive-date=10 January 2022 |url-status=live|title=Brexit vote result: Boris Johnson demands general election after rebel MPs seize control of Commons agenda|last1=Rayner|first1=Gordon|date=3 September 2019|work=The Telegraph|access-date=5 May 2021|last2=Sheridan|first2=Danielle |url-access=limited|issn=0307-1235}}{{cbignore}}</ref> Despite government opposition, the [[Benn Act]], a bill to block a no-deal exit, passed the Commons on 4&nbsp;September 2019, causing Johnson to propose a general election on 15&nbsp;October.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49580185|title=MPs back bill aimed at blocking no-deal Brexit|date=4 September 2019|access-date=5 September 2019|archive-date=4 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190904191629/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49580185|url-status=live}}</ref> His motion was unsuccessful as it failed to command the support of two-thirds of the House.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49584907|title=Johnson's call for general election rejected by MPs|date=4 September 2019|access-date=5 September 2019|archive-date=29 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191129122504/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49584907|url-status=live}}</ref>

In October 2019, following bilateral talks between Johnson and [[Taoiseach]] [[Leo Varadkar]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-49995133|title=Brexit: Boris Johnson and Leo Varadkar 'can see pathway to a deal'|work=BBC News|date=10 October 2019|access-date=23 December 2019|archive-date=30 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191030080611/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-49995133|url-status=live}}</ref> the UK and EU agreed to a [[Brexit withdrawal agreement#Revisions in 2019|revised deal]], which [[Brexit and the Irish border#2019 renegotiation: New protocol|replaced the backstop]] with a new [[Northern Ireland Protocol]].<ref name="bbcNewDeal">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-50083026|title=Brexit: What is in Boris Johnson's new deal with the EU?|work=BBC News|date=21 October 2019|access-date=23 December 2019|archive-date=22 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222170733/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-50083026|url-status=live}}</ref>

====First Cabinet====
{{main|First Johnson ministry}}
[[File:Johnson's 1st cabinet meeting.jpg|thumb|Johnson holding his first cabinet meeting at [[10 Downing Street]], 25 July 2019]]
Johnson [[2019 British cabinet formation|appointed]] his [[First Johnson ministry|Cabinet]] on 24&nbsp;July 2019,<ref name="BBC25">{{cite news |title=Boris Johnson: Does his cabinet reflect 'modern Britain'? |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49034735 |access-date=25 July 2019 |work=BBC News |date=25 July 2019 |archive-date=25 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725151341/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49034735 |url-status=live }}</ref> dismissing 11 senior ministers and accepting the resignation of six others.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/boris-johnson-the-godfather-takes-his-retribution-in-massacre-of-cabinet-ministers-zxr5vvk00 |url-access=subscription |title=Boris Johnson the Godfather takes his retribution in massacre of cabinet ministers |last1=Swinford |first1=Steven |last2=Chorley |first2=Matt |work=The Times |date=25 July 2019 |access-date=27 July 2019 |archive-date=27 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727000529/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/boris-johnson-the-godfather-takes-his-retribution-in-massacre-of-cabinet-ministers-zxr5vvk00 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/24/philip-hammond-quits-johnson-fully-aligned-chancellor-gauke-stewart |title='Summer's day massacre' may spell backbench trouble for Boris Johnson |last=Syal |first=Rajeev |work=The Guardian |date=24 July 2019 |access-date=27 July 2019 |archive-date=24 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724145240/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/24/philip-hammond-quits-johnson-fully-aligned-chancellor-gauke-stewart |url-status=live }}</ref> The mass dismissal was the most extensive postwar Cabinet reorganisation without a change in the ruling party.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-cabinet-reshuffle-ministers-brexit-a9019726.html |last=Woodcock |first=Andrew |title=Boris Johnson dismantles cabinet in reshuffle, building government around people who delivered Brexit vote |work=Independent |date=25 July 2019 |access-date=27 July 2019 |archive-date=25 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725164336/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-cabinet-reshuffle-ministers-brexit-a9019726.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2019/jul/25/cabinet-massacre-what-the-papers-say-about-boris-johnsons-arrival-in-no-10 |last=Lyons |first=Kate |title='Cabinet massacre': what the papers say about Boris Johnson's arrival in No 10 |work=The Guardian |date=25 July 2019 |access-date=27 July 2019 |archive-date=27 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727034518/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2019/jul/25/cabinet-massacre-what-the-papers-say-about-boris-johnsons-arrival-in-no-10 |url-status=live }}</ref>

Among other appointments, Johnson made [[Dominic Raab]] the [[First Secretary of State]] and foreign secretary and appointed [[Sajid Javid]] and [[Priti Patel]] as the [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] and [[Home Secretary]], respectively.

====Loss of working majority====
On 3&nbsp;September 2019, [[Phillip Lee (politician)|Phillip Lee]] [[crossed the floor]] to the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] following a disagreement with Johnson's [[Brexit]] policy. This left the government without a [[working majority]] in the House of Commons.<ref>{{cite news |title=Boris Johnson loses majority after Tory MP defects during speech |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/philip-lee-tory-lib-dem-defection-boris-johnson-majority-brexit-commons-a9090356.html |access-date=3 September 2019 |work=The Independent |date=3 September 2019 |archive-date=2 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191202115439/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/philip-lee-tory-lib-dem-defection-boris-johnson-majority-brexit-commons-a9090356.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Later that day, [[September 2019 suspension of rebel Conservative MPs|21 Conservative MPs]] had the party [[Whip (politics)|whip]] withdrawn for defying party orders and supporting an opposition motion.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/conservative-party/news/106279/twenty-one-tory-rebels-lose-party-whip |title=Twenty-one Tory rebels lose party whip after backing bid to block no-deal Brexit |date=4 September 2019 |website=PoliticsHome.com |access-date=5 September 2019 |archive-date=15 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115083300/https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/conservative-party/news/106279/twenty-one-tory-rebels-lose-party-whip |url-status=live }}</ref> (The whip was restored to 10 former Conservative ministers on 29&nbsp;October.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-50221856 |title=Restoration of Conservative Whip |date=29 October 2019 |work=BBC News |access-date=4 December 2019 |archive-date=12 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220612093301/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-50221856 |url-status=live }}</ref>)
[[File:Boris Johnson after 2019 General election.png|thumb|Johnson giving a speech in December 2019 after the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]]]]
On 5&nbsp;September 2019, Johnson's brother [[Jo Johnson]] resigned from the government and announced that he would step down as MP, describing his position as "torn between family and national interest".<ref name="bbc2">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49594793 |title=PM's brother quits as Tory MP and minister |date=5 September 2019 |access-date=5 September 2019 |work=BBC News |archive-date=5 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905105232/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49594793 |url-status=live }}</ref> Two days later, [[Amber Rudd]] resigned as [[Secretary of State for Work and Pensions]] and from the Conservative Party, describing the withdrawal of the party whip as an "assault on decency and democracy".<ref>{{cite news |last=Shipman |first=Tim |date=7 September 2019 |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/exclusive-amber-rudd-resigns-from-cabinet-and-quits-tories-06dqxcjct |title=Exclusive: Amber Rudd resigns from cabinet and quits Tories |work=[[The Sunday Times]] |issn=0140-0460 |access-date=5 May 2021 |url-access=limited |archive-date=9 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190909083014/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/exclusive-amber-rudd-resigns-from-cabinet-and-quits-tories-06dqxcjct |url-status=live }}</ref>

====2019 general election====
{{main|2019 United Kingdom general election}}
In October 2019, Parliament was dissolved, and an election called for 12&nbsp;December. The election resulted in the Conservative Party winning 43.6% of the vote and a parliamentary landslide majority of 80 seats.<ref>{{cite news |work=BBC News |title=General Election 2019: What's behind the Conservative victory? |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2019-50774061 |access-date=13 December 2019 |archive-date=7 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220607203520/https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2019-50774061 |url-status=live }}</ref> A key slogan used in the Conservative campaign was "[[Get Brexit Done]]".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Perrigo |first1=Billy |title='Get Brexit Done.' The Slogan That Won Britain's Election |url=https://time.com/5749478/get-brexit-done-slogan-uk-election/ |access-date=11 December 2021 |magazine=Time |date=13 December 2019 |archive-date=30 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130160101/https://time.com/5749478/get-brexit-done-slogan-uk-election/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Second term (December 2019 – September 2022)===
====Second Cabinet====
{{main|Second Johnson ministry|2020 British cabinet reshuffle|2021 British cabinet reshuffle}}
[[File:Chancellor announces additional support to protect businesses.jpg|thumb|Johnson appointed [[Rishi Sunak]] (right) as [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] in the [[2020 British cabinet reshuffle|February 2020 cabinet reshuffle]]]]
Johnson [[2020 British cabinet reshuffle|reshuffled his cabinet]] in February 2020.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-51491662 |title=Sajid Javid resigns as chancellor |date=13 February 2020 |work=BBC News |access-date=13 February 2020 |archive-date=13 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200213152120/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-51491662 |url-status=live }}</ref> Five Cabinet ministers were sacked, including the [[Northern Ireland secretary]] [[Julian Smith (politician)|Julian Smith]], a decision that was criticised by several politicians and commentators following his success in restoring the [[Northern Ireland Executive]] devolved government.<ref name="Walker">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/feb/13/julian-smith-sacked-as-boris-johnson-reshuffles-cabinet|title=Smith, Leadsom and McVey out as Johnson reshuffles cabinet|date=13 February 2020|author=Walker, Peter|work=The Guardian|access-date=18 July 2021|archive-date=30 November 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201130021613/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/feb/13/julian-smith-sacked-as-boris-johnson-reshuffles-cabinet|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] [[Sajid Javid]] resigned from the Cabinet and was replaced by [[Rishi Sunak]]; Javid later returned to Johnson's Cabinet as [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]] in June 2021 following the resignation of [[Matt Hancock]].<ref name="JavResign">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51491662|title=Cabinet reshuffle: Sajid Javid resigns as chancellor|website=BBC News|date=13 February 2020|access-date=18 July 2021|archive-date=13 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200213120158/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51491662|url-status=live}}</ref>

Johnson reshuffled his cabinet again in September 2021. Changes included the dismissal of [[Secretary of State for Education|Education Secretary]] [[Gavin Williamson]] who had received significant criticism for his handling of disruption to education during the COVID-19 pandemic. [[Dominic Raab]] was moved from foreign secretary to [[Deputy Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|deputy prime minister]] and [[Secretary of State for Justice|justice secretary]]. Raab was replaced as foreign secretary by [[Liz Truss]].<ref>{{Cite news|date=15 September 2021|title=Cabinet reshuffle: Raab moved from foreign secretary to deputy PM|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-58571935|access-date=15 September 2021|archive-date=15 September 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210915190724/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-58571935|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Heffer|first=Greg|date=15 September 2021|title=Cabinet reshuffle: Gavin Williamson sacked and Dominic Raab moved from foreign secretary|url=https://news.sky.com/story/cabinet-reshuffle-gavin-williamson-departs-education-department-as-dominic-raab-demoted-to-justice-secretary-12408644|access-date=15 September 2021|publisher=Sky News|archive-date=15 September 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210915152533/https://news.sky.com/story/cabinet-reshuffle-gavin-williamson-departs-education-department-as-dominic-raab-demoted-to-justice-secretary-12408644|url-status=live}}</ref>

====COVID-19 pandemic====
{{main|British government response to the COVID-19 pandemic|COVID-19 vaccination programme in the United Kingdom}}
{{See also|COVID-19 contracts in the United Kingdom|COVID-19 pandemic in the United Kingdom}}

[[File:Boris Johnson giving a COVID-19 press conference.jpg|thumb|Johnson delivering a press conference on [[COVID-19]], 31 July 2020]]
The [[COVID-19 pandemic in the United Kingdom|COVID-19 pandemic]] emerged as a serious crisis within the first few months of Johnson's second term.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Stewart |first1=Heather |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/20/london-pubs-cinemas-and-gyms-may-close-in-covid-19-clampdown |title=Boris Johnson announces closure of all UK pubs and restaurants |date=20 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=20 March 2020 |last2=Walker |first2=Peter |issn=0261-3077 |archive-date=23 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211223083059/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/20/london-pubs-cinemas-and-gyms-may-close-in-covid-19-clampdown |url-status=live }}</ref> Johnson's non-attendance of five [[COBR]] briefings during the early months and the failure of the UK government to prepare for and control the outbreak has been criticised.<ref>{{Cite news|last3=Leake|first3=Jonathan|last2=Arbuthnot|first2=George|last1=Calvert|first1=Jonathan|title=Coronavirus: 38 days when Britain sleepwalked into disaster|work=[[The Times]]|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/coronavirus-38-days-when-britain-sleepwalked-into-disaster-hq3b9tlgh|access-date=1 January 2021|issn=0140-0460|archive-date=11 October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201011232444/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/coronavirus-38-days-when-britain-sleepwalked-into-disaster-hq3b9tlgh|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Walker|first=Peter|date=19 April 2020|title=Boris Johnson missed five coronavirus Cobra meetings, Michael Gove says|work=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/19/michael-gove-fails-to-deny-pm-missed-five-coronavirus-cobra-meetings|access-date=1 January 2021|issn=0261-3077|archive-date=21 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421042002/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/19/michael-gove-fails-to-deny-pm-missed-five-coronavirus-cobra-meetings|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last1=Helm|first1=Toby|last2=Graham-Harrison|first2=Emma|last3=McKie|first3=Robin|date=19 April 2020|title=How did Britain get its coronavirus response so wrong?|work=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/18/how-did-britain-get-its-response-to-coronavirus-so-wrong|access-date=1 January 2021|issn=0261-3077|archive-date=5 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210105024419/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/18/how-did-britain-get-its-response-to-coronavirus-so-wrong|url-status=live}}</ref> The UK was among the last major{{Clarify|date=October 2021|reason=what is a "major" state? }} European states to close schools, ban public events and order a [[COVID-19 lockdowns|lockdown]].<ref name="dw-20200401">{{cite news|date=1 April 2020|title=Coronavirus: What are the lockdown measures across Europe?|publisher=Deutsche Welle|url=https://www.dw.com/en/coronavirus-what-are-the-lockdown-measures-across-europe/a-52905137|access-date=13 April 2020|archive-date=6 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406164106/https://www.dw.com/en/coronavirus-what-are-the-lockdown-measures-across-europe/a-52905137|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="imperial-20200330">{{cite report|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/media/imperial-college/medicine/mrc-gida/2020-03-30-COVID19-Report-13.pdf|title=Estimating the number of infections and the impact of non-pharmaceutical interventions on COVID-19 in 11 European countries|date=30 March 2020|work=Department of Infectious Disease Epidemiology|publisher=Imperial College London|doi=10.25561/77731|page=5|access-date=13 April 2020|last1=Flaxman|first1=S.|last2=Mishra|first2=S.|last3=Gandy|first3=A.|last4=Unwin|first4=H.|last5=Coupland|first5=H.|last6=Mellan|first6=T.|last7=Zhu|first7=H.|last8=Berah|first8=T.|last9=Eaton|first9=J.|last10=Perez Guzman|first10=P.|last11=Schmit|first11=N.|last12=Cilloni|first12=L.|last13=Ainslie|first13=K.|last14=Baguelin|first14=M.|last15=Blake|first15=I.|last16=Boonyasiri|first16=A.|last17=Boyd|first17=O.|last18=Cattarino|first18=L.|last19=Ciavarella|first19=C.|last20=Cooper|first20=L.|last21=Cucunuba Perez|first21=Z.|last22=Cuomo-Dannenburg|first22=G.|last23=Dighe|first23=A.|last24=Djaafara|first24=A.|last25=Dorigatti|first25=I.|last26=Van Elsland|first26=S.|last27=Fitzjohn|first27=R.|last28=Fu|first28=H.|last29=Gaythorpe|first29=K.|last30=Geidelberg|first30=L.|display-authors=1|archive-date=12 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412231121/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/media/imperial-college/medicine/mrc-gida/2020-03-30-COVID19-Report-13.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref> This response is thought by some scientists to have contributed to the UK's high death toll from COVID-19, which {{as of|2021|1|lc=y}} was among the highest in the world.<ref name="reuters_2">{{Cite news|last=Sandle|first=Andrew MacAskill, Paul|date=25 January 2021|title=Anger and grief as United Kingdom's COVID-19 death toll nears 100,000|work=Reuters|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-britain-deaths-idUSKBN29U13M|access-date=25 January 2021|archive-date=25 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210125113025/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-britain-deaths-idUSKBN29U13M|url-status=live}}</ref>{{update inline|date=March 2023}}

''Reuters'' reported that scientists were critical of Johnson both for acting too slowly to stop the spread of COVID-19 and for mishandling the government's response;<ref name="reuters">{{Cite news|title=50,000 COVID-19 deaths and rising. How the UK keeps failing.|url=https://www.reuters.com/investigates/special-report/health-coronavirus-britain-newwave/|date=24 November 2020|access-date=1 January 2021|work=Reuters|archive-date=23 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210123220302/https://www.reuters.com/investigates/special-report/health-coronavirus-britain-newwave/|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Politico'' quoted [[Chief Medical Officer for England|Chief Medical Officer]] [[Chris Whitty]] as saying that an earlier initial lockdown would have significantly lowered the death toll.<ref>{{Cite web|date=10 June 2020|title=Scientists turn on Boris Johnson over UK's coronavirus response|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/scientists-turn-on-boris-johnson-over-uks-coronavirus-response-covid-19/|access-date=1 January 2021|website=Politico|archive-date=18 December 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201218130401/https://www.politico.eu/article/scientists-turn-on-boris-johnson-over-uks-coronavirus-response-covid-19/|url-status=live}}</ref> The ''[[BMJ]]'' published several editorials critical of the policies adopted during the country's public health response.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Scally |first1=Gabriel |last2=Jacobson |first2=Bobbie |last3=Abbasi |first3=Kamran |title=The UK's public health response to covid-19 |url=https://www.bmj.com/content/369/bmj.m1932 |access-date=20 February 2022 |journal=BMJ |date=15 May 2020 |pages=m1932 |doi=10.1136/bmj.m1932 |archive-date=4 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220204162518/https://www.bmj.com/content/369/bmj.m1932 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ham |first1=Chris |title=The UK's poor record on covid-19 is a failure of policy learning |url=https://www.bmj.com/content/372/bmj.n284 |access-date=20 February 2022 |journal=BMJ |date=1 February 2021 |pages=n284 |doi=10.1136/bmj.n284 |archive-date=16 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220216175016/https://www.bmj.com/content/372/bmj.n284 |url-status=live }}</ref> Johnson's public communication over the virus and the UK's test and trace system were also criticised.<ref name="reuters"/><ref>{{Cite web|last=Yong|first=Ed|date=16 March 2020|title=The U.K.'s Coronavirus 'Herd Immunity' Debacle|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2020/03/coronavirus-pandemic-herd-immunity-uk-boris-johnson/608065/|access-date=25 January 2021|website=The Atlantic|archive-date=11 July 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210711122536/https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2020/03/coronavirus-pandemic-herd-immunity-uk-boris-johnson/608065/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Macaskill |first1=Andrew |last2=Grey |first2=Stephen |last3=McNeill |first3=Ryan |last4=Stecklow |first4=Steve |last5=Wilkes |first5=Tommy |last6=Marshall |first6=Andrew R. C. |title=50,000 COVID-19 deaths and rising. How the UK keeps failing. |url=https://www.reuters.com/investigates/special-report/health-coronavirus-britain-newwave/ |access-date=20 February 2022 |work=Reuters |date=24 November 2020 |archive-date=23 January 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210123220302/https://www.reuters.com/investigates/special-report/health-coronavirus-britain-newwave/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 3&nbsp;March 2020 Johnson claimed to have shaken hands with COVID-19 patients in hospital on the same day that [[Scientific Advisory Group for Emergencies|SAGE]] had advised the government to warn the public not to shake hands and minimise physical contact,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mason|first=Rowena|date=5 May 2020|title=Boris Johnson boasted of shaking hands on day Sage warned not to|work=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/may/05/boris-johnson-boasted-of-shaking-hands-on-day-sage-warned-not-to|access-date=1 January 2021|issn=0261-3077|archive-date=2 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210102021856/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/may/05/boris-johnson-boasted-of-shaking-hands-on-day-sage-warned-not-to|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Coronavirus: Boris Johnson was shaking hands as some scientists were calling for it to stop|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-boris-johnson-was-shaking-hands-as-some-scientists-were-calling-for-it-to-stop-11983606|date=5 May 2020|access-date=1 January 2021|work=Sky News|archive-date=22 December 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201222074805/https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-boris-johnson-was-shaking-hands-as-some-scientists-were-calling-for-it-to-stop-11983606|url-status=live}}</ref> though it was unclear whether the hospital he visited actually contained any coronavirus patients.<ref name="NORTH">{{cite news |last1=Wildman |first1=Sam |title=Silence over Boris Johnson coronavirus claim following KGH visit |url=https://www.northantstelegraph.co.uk/news/people/silence-over-boris-johnson-coronavirus-claim-following-kgh-visit-2071521 |access-date=3 February 2022 |work=Northamptonshire Telegraph |date=4 March 2020 |archive-date=3 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220203003350/https://www.northantstelegraph.co.uk/news/people/silence-over-boris-johnson-coronavirus-claim-following-kgh-visit-2071521 |url-status=live }}</ref> He continued to shake hands publicly in the following days.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Payne |first1=Sebastian |last2=Cookson |first2=Clive |title=Boris Johnson shook hands 'continuously' despite science panel warnings |url=https://www.ft.com/content/91c8b10f-7e76-4686-8d53-35b2af0c1a2e |access-date=2 February 2022 |work=Financial Times |date=5 May 2020 |archive-date=17 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211217153558/https://www.ft.com/content/91c8b10f-7e76-4686-8d53-35b2af0c1a2e |url-status=live }}</ref> On 23&nbsp;March, a [[COVID-19 lockdown in the United Kingdom|COVID-19 lockdown]] was imposed throughout the UK, except for a few limited purposes, backed up by [[The Health Protection (Coronavirus, Restrictions) (England) Regulations 2020|new legal powers]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Picheta |first=Rob |date=24 March 2020 |publisher=[[CNN]] |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/23/uk/uk-coronavirus-lockdown-gbr-intl/index.html |title=Boris Johnson issues stay-at-home order, sending UK into lockdown to fight coronavirus pandemic |access-date=16 April 2020 |archive-date=15 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200415191835/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/23/uk/uk-coronavirus-lockdown-gbr-intl/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref>
[[File:Boris Johnson returns to work after Coronavirus.jpg|left|thumb|Johnson giving a speech in April 2020 after recovering from [[COVID-19]]]]
On 27&nbsp;March, it was announced that Johnson had tested positive for [[COVID-19]].<ref name="CoronaBJ">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52060791 |title=PM Boris Johnson tests positive for coronavirus |date=27 March 2020 |work=BBC News |access-date=27 March 2020 |archive-date=23 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200423071833/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52060791 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 5&nbsp;April, he was admitted to a hospital.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52177125 |title=PM admitted to hospital over virus symptoms |date=5 April 2020 |work=BBC News |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-date=15 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200415132842/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52177125 |url-status=live }}</ref> The next day, he was moved to the hospital's intensive care unit.<ref>{{cite news |title=UK PM Boris Johnson taken to intensive care |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52192604 |work=BBC News |date=6 April 2020 |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-date=23 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200423071843/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52192604 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="IT Reactions Guardian">{{cite web |last=Rawlinson |first=Kevin |title=Coronavirus: Boris Johnson taken into intensive care – live updates |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/apr/06/coronavirus-live-news-boris-johnson-admitted-to-hospital-as-trump-again-touts-hydroxychloroquine |website=The Guardian |date=6 April 2020 |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-date=6 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206063351/https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/apr/06/coronavirus-live-news-boris-johnson-admitted-to-hospital-as-trump-again-touts-hydroxychloroquine |url-status=live }}</ref> Johnson left intensive care on 9&nbsp;April,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-britain-johnson-idUSKCN21R34I |title=UK PM Johnson leaves intensive care, remains under observation |date=9 April 2020 |work=Reuters |access-date=9 April 2020 |archive-date=9 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200409232504/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-britain-johnson-idUSKCN21R34I |url-status=live }}</ref> and left hospital three days later to recuperate at [[Chequers]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Boris Johnson discharged from hospital |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52262012 |work=BBC News |date=12 April 2020 |access-date=12 April 2020 |archive-date=21 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421230515/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52262012 |url-status=live }}</ref> After a fortnight at Chequers, he returned to Downing Street on 26&nbsp;April.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Boris Johnson's return to work 'a boost for the country' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/amp/uk-politics-52431913 |work=BBC News |date=26 April 2020 |access-date=27 April 2020 |archive-date=27 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200427045605/https://www.bbc.com/news/amp/uk-politics-52431913 |url-status=live }}</ref> Johnson later said that he had been given [[Oxygen therapy|emergency oxygen]] while in intensive care, and that doctors had made preparations in case he died.<ref>{{cite web|title=U.K.'s Boris Johnson says doctors prepared to announce his death as he fought COVID-19|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/u-k-s-boris-johnson-says-doctors-prepared-announce-his-n1198871|date=3 May 2020|access-date=9 November 2021|publisher=NBC News|archive-date=9 November 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211109164652/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/u-k-s-boris-johnson-says-doctors-prepared-announce-his-n1198871|url-status=live}}</ref>

A [[Dominic Cummings scandal|scandal]] in May 2020 involved Johnson's chief political advisor [[Dominic Cummings]], who made a trip with his family to [[Durham, England|Durham]] during the March 2020 lockdown while experiencing COVID-19 symptoms. Both Cummings and Johnson rejected widespread calls that Cummings resign.<ref>{{cite news|date=26 May 2020|title=A site for sore eyes? How Dominic Cummings put Barnard Castle on the map|work=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2020/may/26/a-site-for-sore-eyes-how-dominic-cummings-put-barnard-castle-on-the-map|access-date=27 May 2020|issn=0261-3077|archive-date=28 May 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200528203509/https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2020/may/26/a-site-for-sore-eyes-how-dominic-cummings-put-barnard-castle-on-the-map|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=25 May 2020|title=No 10 'chaos' as 'defiant' PM defends Cummings|work=[[BBC News]]|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-the-papers-52793529|access-date=27 May 2020|archive-date=26 May 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200526041814/https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-the-papers-52793529|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Why Is the U.K. in an Uproar Over a Boris Johnson Adviser's COVID Road Trip?|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/05/dominic-cummings-durham-johnson.html|last=Keating|first=Joshua|date=26 May 2020|website=Slate|access-date=27 May 2020|archive-date=28 May 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200528090439/https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/05/dominic-cummings-durham-johnson.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Johnson's defence of Cummings and his refusal to sack him caused a widespread backlash.<ref>{{cite news|date=24 May 2020|title=Boris Johnson backs Dominic Cummings over lockdown breach|author=Sebastian Payne|url=https://www.ft.com/content/3e3569ca-01b4-40af-b291-747f482bbe9b|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200524185912/https://www.ft.com/content/3e3569ca-01b4-40af-b291-747f482bbe9b|url-status=dead|archive-date=24 May 2020|work=Financial Times|access-date=10 July 2021}}</ref> This resulted in a loss of confidence in the government and specifically its response to the pandemic, referred to as 'the Cummings effect' in ''[[The Lancet]]''. Concerns were raised in the study that this could affect the public's compliance with pandemic restrictions.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Fancourt|first1=Daisy|last2=Steptoe|first2=Andrew|last3=Wright|first3=Liam|date=15 August 2020|title=The Cummings effect: politics, trust, and behaviours during the COVID-19 pandemic|journal=[[The Lancet]]|volume=396|issue=10249|pages=464–465|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(20)31690-1|issn=0140-6736|pmid=32771083|pmc=7613216 |doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Knapton|first=Sarah|date=6 August 2020|title='Dominic Cummings effect' has led to major loss of confidence in Government, study reveals|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2020/08/06/dominic-cummings-effect-has-led-major-loss-confidence-government/|url-status=live|work=The Telegraph|issn=0307-1235|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200807112203/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2020/08/06/dominic-cummings-effect-has-led-major-loss-confidence-government/|archive-date=7 August 2020|access-date=5 May 2021|url-access=limited}}</ref>

The Johnson ministry was [[Controversies regarding COVID-19 contracts in the United Kingdom|accused of cronyism in their assignment of contracts]] related to the pandemic response. Procurement of government contracts for key COVID-19 supplies became less transparent as a result of emergency measures bypassing the usual competitive tendering process.<ref name="PogCal">{{cite news |last1=Pogrund |first1=Gabriel |last2=Calver |first2=Tom |date=15 November 2020 |title=Chumocracy first in line as ministers splash Covid cash |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/chumocracy-first-in-line-as-ministers-splash-covid-cash-7wb5b8q0w |work=[[The Sunday Times]] |access-date=5 May 2021 |url-access=limited |archive-date=15 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201115051647/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/chumocracy-first-in-line-as-ministers-splash-covid-cash-7wb5b8q0w |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="GuardChums">{{cite news |last1=Conn |first1=David |last2=Pegg |first2=David |last3=Evans |first3=Rob |last4=Garside |first4=Juliette |last5=Lawrence |first5=Felicity |title='Chumocracy': how Covid revealed the new shape of the Tory establishment |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/nov/15/chumocracy-covid-revealed-shape-tory-establishment |access-date=15 November 2020 |work=[[The Observer]] |date=15 November 2020 |archive-date=15 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201115124803/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/nov/15/chumocracy-covid-revealed-shape-tory-establishment |url-status=live }}</ref> In October 2020 Johnson conceded that the UK's [[NHS Test and Trace|test and trace]] system and its specially developed [[NHS COVID-19|contact tracing app]], which had been criticised for their cost and operational issues, had caused "frustrations".<ref name="reuters"/><ref>{{Cite news|date=14 September 2020|title='Utter shambles': GPs and medics decry NHS test-and-trace system|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/sep/14/utter-shambles-gps-and-medics-decry-nhs-test-and-trace-system|access-date=17 January 2021|work=The Guardian|archive-date=25 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210125183455/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/sep/14/utter-shambles-gps-and-medics-decry-nhs-test-and-trace-system|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|date=22 October 2020|title=Covid: NHS Test and Trace needs to improve, PM concedes|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-54650029|access-date=17 January 2021|archive-date=13 November 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201113060301/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-54650029|url-status=live}}</ref>
[[File:Boris Johnson hosts virtual G7 meeting (2).jpg|thumb|Johnson hosts virtual G7 meeting in February 2021]]
Johnson reportedly resisted calls from SAGE and within the government to enact a second lockdown throughout September as COVID-19 infections rose.<ref name=":0a">{{Cite news|date=15 March 2021|title=Ministers frustrated with PM's 'mistakes' ahead of Covid second wave|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-56406393|access-date=20 March 2021|archive-date=18 March 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210318065012/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-56406393|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Ray|first=Siladitya|title=Report: Boris Johnson Said U.K. Should 'Ignore' Covid-19 At The Start Of The Pandemic|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/siladityaray/2021/03/16/report-boris-johnson-said-uk-should-ignore-covid-19-at-the-start-of-the-pandemic/|access-date=20 March 2021|website=Forbes|archive-date=18 March 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210318141630/https://www.forbes.com/sites/siladityaray/2021/03/16/report-boris-johnson-said-uk-should-ignore-covid-19-at-the-start-of-the-pandemic/|url-status=live}}</ref> In April 2021 Johnson denied allegations he had said he would rather "[[let the bodies pile high in their thousands]]" on 30&nbsp;October 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rayner|first=Gordon|date=26 April 2021|title='Let the bodies pile high': What really happened on night Boris Johnson was accused of outburst|work=The Telegraph|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2021/04/26/let-bodies-pile-high-really-happened-night-boris-johnson-accused/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2021/04/26/let-bodies-pile-high-really-happened-night-boris-johnson-accused/ |archive-date=10 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|access-date=27 May 2021|issn=0307-1235}}{{cbignore}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Covid: Boris Johnson's 'bodies pile high' comments prompt criticism|work=BBC News|date=26 April 2021|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-56890714|access-date=27 May 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210426204816/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-56890714|archive-date=26 April 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Peston|first=Robert|date=26 April 2021|title=Johnson 'did make bodies pile high in their thousands' comment, writes Peston|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2021-04-26/robert-peston-boris-johnson-did-make-bodies-pile-high-in-their-thousands-comment|access-date=27 May 2021|website=ITV News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210427003119/https://www.itv.com/news/2021-04-26/robert-peston-boris-johnson-did-make-bodies-pile-high-in-their-thousands-comment|archive-date=27 April 2021}}</ref> The government enacted a second national lockdown on 31&nbsp;October.<ref name="theguardian4">{{Cite news|last=Syal|first=Rajeev|date=20 December 2020|title=Boris Johnson's Covid flip-flops: the pledges upended by reality|work=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/dec/20/boris-johnsons-covid-flip-flops-the-pledges-upended-by-reality|access-date=5 January 2021|issn=0261-3077|archive-date=4 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210104012215/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/dec/20/boris-johnsons-covid-flip-flops-the-pledges-upended-by-reality|url-status=live}}</ref> Throughout December 2020 COVID-19 cases across the UK rose significantly, straining emergency services and hospitals.<ref name="bloomberg">{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-01-04/johnson-hits-england-with-full-lockdown-as-nhs-faces-deep-crisis |title=U.K. Bets 2 Million Vaccine Shots a Week Will End Lockdown |publisher=Bloomberg L.P. |date=4 January 2021 |access-date=5 January 2021 |archive-date=7 January 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107043134/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-01-04/johnson-hits-england-with-full-lockdown-as-nhs-faces-deep-crisis |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-55362681 |title=Pressure on hospitals 'at a really dangerous point' |work=BBC News |date=18 December 2020 |access-date=5 January 2021 |archive-date=18 December 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201218155311/https://www.bbc.com/news/health-55362681 |url-status=live }}</ref> In response, the government enacted further restrictions to large parts of southern and eastern England and on 21&nbsp;December shortened a planned household mixing period over Christmas.<ref name="cnn2">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/12/19/uk/christmas-covid-strain-restrictions-intl-gbr/index.html|title=Boris Johnson backtracks on relaxing Christmas rules after scientists warn new Covid-19 variant is spreading faster|first1=Amy|last1=Woodyatt|first2=Lindsay|last2=Isaac|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=20 December 2020|access-date=31 December 2020|archive-date=29 December 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201229235518/https://www.cnn.com/2020/12/19/uk/christmas-covid-strain-restrictions-intl-gbr/index.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

Britain began [[COVID-19 vaccination in the United Kingdom|its COVID-19 vaccination programme]] in December 2020.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.bmj.com/content/372/bmj.n421 |last=Baraniuk |first=Chris |title=Covid-19: How the UK vaccine rollout delivered success, so far |journal=BMJ (Clinical Research Ed.) |date=18 February 2021 |volume=372 |pages=n421 |doi=10.1136/bmj.n421 |pmid=33602672 |s2cid=231946710 |access-date=16 January 2021 |doi-access=free |archive-date=18 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210218102221/https://www.bmj.com/content/372/bmj.n421 |url-status=live  | issn=1756-1833 }}</ref> Half of UK adults had received at least their first vaccine dose by 20&nbsp;March 2021.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-56469092 |title=Covid-19: Record day for UK with 711,156 vaccinations given |work=BBC News |date=20 March 2021 |access-date=20 March 2021 |archive-date=20 March 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210320132207/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-56469092 |url-status=live }}</ref> A third lockdown for the whole of England was introduced on 6&nbsp;January 2021.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-55554550 |title=Covid: England's third national lockdown legally comes into force |work=BBC News |date=6 January 2022 |access-date=17 January 2022 |archive-date=9 January 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210109231547/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-55554550 |url-status=live }}</ref> Record numbers of infections and daily deaths were recorded in the UK throughout January, and the government began exploring quarantine procedures on arrival.<ref>{{Cite news|date=26 January 2021|title=UK Covid deaths: Why the 100,000 toll is so bad|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-55757790|access-date=26 January 2021|archive-date=26 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210126174749/https://www.bbc.com/news/health-55757790|url-status=live}}</ref> Johnson said he was "deeply sorry" and "take[s] full responsibility" as the UK passed 100,000 deaths from COVID-19, the first European country to do so, on 26&nbsp;January.<ref>{{Cite news|date=26 January 2021|title=Covid deaths: UK passes milestone of 100,000|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-55814751|access-date=26 January 2021|archive-date=26 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210126173607/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-55814751|url-status=live}}</ref>
[[File:Boris Johnson greets Joe Biden before the G7 Cornwall Summit.jpg|thumb|Johnson with US president [[Joe Biden]] at the [[47th G7 summit|G7 summit]] in Cornwall, 10 June 2021]]
In July 2021 Johnson announced that most generalised public health restrictions in England would be lifted and replaced by recommendations. This took place despite an increase in cases driven by the [[Delta variant]].<ref>{{cite web|date=12 July 2021|title=Johnson: England to lift last virus restrictions on July 19|url=https://apnews.com/article/europe-business-health-government-and-politics-coronavirus-pandemic-3776cfdb1c180720b9ea000a2c65618b|access-date=9 November 2021|website=AP News|archive-date=9 November 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211109164652/https://apnews.com/article/europe-business-health-government-and-politics-coronavirus-pandemic-3776cfdb1c180720b9ea000a2c65618b|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Ellyatt|first=Holly|date=19 July 2021|title=England takes leap into the unknown, lifting Covid rules as cases surge|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/07/19/uk-lifts-all-remaining-covid-restrictions-despite-cases-surging.html|access-date=9 November 2021|publisher=[[CNBC]]|archive-date=9 November 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211109164652/https://www.cnbc.com/2021/07/19/uk-lifts-all-remaining-covid-restrictions-despite-cases-surging.html|url-status=live}}</ref> In September 2021 Johnson was pictured in a cabinet meeting, with "at least 30 people crammed shoulder-to-shoulder", without anyone wearing masks and with all windows apparently closed, contradicting government advice.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2021/sep/17/boris-johnsons-revamped-cabinet-meet-for-half-time-pep-talk|title=Johnson's revamped cabinet cram into office – with no masks|author=Peter Walker|work=The Guardian|date=17 September 2021|access-date=21 September 2021|archive-date=21 September 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210921071506/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2021/sep/17/boris-johnsons-revamped-cabinet-meet-for-half-time-pep-talk|url-status=live}}</ref> Johnson was also photographed without a face mask during a visit to a hospital in November.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Dominic Raab defends Boris Johnson after PM is pictured not wearing mask on hospital visit|url=https://news.sky.com/story/dominic-raab-defends-boris-johnson-after-pm-is-pictured-not-wearing-mask-on-hospital-visit-12464422|access-date=9 November 2021|publisher=Sky News|archive-date=9 November 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211109092119/https://news.sky.com/story/dominic-raab-defends-boris-johnson-after-pm-is-pictured-not-wearing-mask-on-hospital-visit-12464422|url-status=live}}</ref>

In December 2021 more stringent "Plan B" restrictions for England were put forward, a partial renewal of previous measures due to the increased incidence of the [[SARS-CoV-2 Omicron variant]]. These proposals included face coverings to be required in more public settings, guidance to [[work from home]] wherever possible, and requirements of [[COVID passports in the United Kingdom|COVID-19 passports]] to enter certain venues.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gillett |first1=Francesca |last2=Lee |first2=Dulcie |title=Covid: New Plan B rules on working from home and masks announced for England |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-59585307 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=8 December 2021 |access-date=14 December 2021 |archive-date=4 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220704205007/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-59585307 |url-status=live }}</ref> The government experienced the largest rebellion of Conservative MPs during Johnson's premiership, in opposition to these measures.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Swinford |first1=Steven |last2=Zeffman |first2=Henry |title=Johnson suffers biggest rebellion of premiership |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/johnson-pushes-through-plan-b-despite-largest-rebellion-of-his-premiership-jxw0hq3gg |work=The Times |url-access=limited |date=14 December 2021 |access-date=14 December 2021 |archive-date=20 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220420204607/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/johnson-pushes-through-plan-b-despite-largest-rebellion-of-his-premiership-jxw0hq3gg |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Penna |first1=Dominic |last2=Fisher |first2=Lucy |last3=Nanu |first3=Maighna |title=Politics latest news: Boris Johnson suffers huge rebellion as MPs vote in favour of Covid passports |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2021/12/14/boris-johnson-news-covid-vaccine-passport-vote-tory-rebellion/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2021/12/14/boris-johnson-news-covid-vaccine-passport-vote-tory-rebellion/ |archive-date=10 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |work=The Telegraph |date=14 December 2021}}{{cbignore}}</ref>

==== Immigration ====
{{Further|Modern immigration to the United Kingdom}}
In 2019, Johnson promised to reduce net migration to the United Kingdom (the number of people immigrating minus the number emigrating) below 250,000 per year by the next election.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rishi Sunak refuses to stick to Boris Johnson's pledge on bringing net migration below 250,000 |url=https://news.sky.com/story/rishi-sunak-refuses-to-commit-to-cutting-net-migration-to-level-set-in-2019-tory-manifesto-12883019 |work=Sky News |date=18 May 2023}}</ref> In 2021 net migration to the UK was 488,000,<ref>{{cite news |title=Net migration rises to new record calendar year figure of 606,000 in the 12 months to December 2022 |url=https://news.sky.com/story/net-migration-rises-to-new-record-figure-of-606-000-in-the-year-to-december-2022-12888478 |work=Sky News |date=25 May 2023}}</ref><ref name="ons.gov.uk-25-05-2023"/> up from 184,000 in 2019 before the COVID-19 pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |title=Latest UK migration statistics: The key numbers |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/office-for-national-statistics-people-ukraine-hong-kong-health-b2452365.html |work=The Independent |date=23 November 2023}}</ref> Most of the migrants came from non-EU countries. As a result of Brexit, more EU nationals left the UK than arrived.<ref name="ons.gov.uk-25-05-2023">{{cite news |title=Long-term international migration, provisional: year ending December 2022 |url=https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/populationandmigration/internationalmigration/bulletins/longterminternationalmigrationprovisional/yearendingdecember2022#non-eu-reason-for-migration |work=[[Office for National Statistics]] |date=25 May 2023}}</ref>

In 2021, Johnson's government launched a [[British National (Overseas)#Expanded access to UK residence|scheme for Hongkongers]] following the [[2020 Hong Kong national security law|Hong Kong national security law]], with more than 200,000 Hong Kong residents immigrating to the UK.<ref>{{cite web |title=Safe and Legal (Humanitarian) routes to the UK |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/immigration-system-statistics-year-ending-march-2024/safe-and-legal-humanitarian-routes-to-the-uk#british-national-overseas-bno-route |publisher=Home Office |access-date=23 May 2024}}</ref>

Long-term net migration to the UK reached a record high of 764,000 in 2022,<ref>{{cite news |title=Migration: How many people come to the UK and how are the salary rules changing? |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-48785695 |work=BBC News |date=23 May 2024}}</ref> with immigration at 1.26 million and emigration at 493,000.<ref>{{cite news |title=Net migration drops to 685,000 after hitting record levels, as even more arrived in UK last year than previously thought |url=https://www.lbc.co.uk/news/net-migration-drops-to-685-000/ |date=23 May 2024 |work=[[LBC]]}}</ref>

====Legislative agenda====
At the [[2021 State Opening of Parliament|State Opening of Parliament on 11&nbsp;May 2021]], a range of proposed laws were announced, including the [[Dissolution and Calling of Parliament Bill]], which would restore the [[royal prerogative]] to dissolve Parliament; a [[Higher Education (Freedom of Speech) Bill]] to combat [[deplatforming]] at universities;<ref name="Metro 11-05-2021">{{cite news|url=https://metro.co.uk/2021/05/11/queens-speech-2021-all-the-new-laws-unveiled-in-the-queens-speech-today-14556784/|last=Brown|first=Faye|date=11 May 2021|title=All the new laws unveiled in the Queen's Speech today|work=Metro|access-date=1 June 2021|archive-date=2 June 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210602213816/https://metro.co.uk/2021/05/11/queens-speech-2021-all-the-new-laws-unveiled-in-the-queens-speech-today-14556784/|url-status=live}}</ref> an [[Online Safety Act 2023|Online Safety Bill]] that would impose a statutory [[duty of care]] on online companies and empower [[Ofcom]] to block particular websites;<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-57071977|title=Government lays out plans to protect users online|work=[[BBC News]]|last=Wakefield|first=Jane|date=12 May 2021|access-date=12 May 2021|archive-date=12 May 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210512020234/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-57071977|url-status=live}}</ref> and an [[Animal Welfare (Sentience) Bill]] that would legally recognise animal sentience. Further laws would introduce [[voter identification laws|mandatory voter identification]] at general elections, reform the national immigration system, and implement a [[Levelling up policy of the Boris Johnson government|levelling up policy]] to reduce imbalances between areas.<ref name="Metro 11-05-2021" />

====2021 Downing Street refurbishment controversy====
{{Further|2021 Downing Street refurbishment controversy}}
In April 2021 Cummings alleged that Johnson had arranged for donors to "secretly pay" for renovations on the private residence at 11 Downing Street.<ref name=":0b">{{Cite news|date=28 April 2021|title=Downing Street refurbishment: What is the row over Boris Johnson's flat?|work=[[BBC News]]|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-56878663|access-date=29 April 2021|archive-date=29 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210429012531/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-56878663|url-status=live}}</ref> On 27 April Johnson asked the Cabinet Secretary, [[Simon Case]], to hold a review about the refurbishment.<ref>{{Cite news|date=27 April 2021|title=Boris Johnson's flat: Top official to review funding of revamp|work=[[BBC News]]|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-56883078|access-date=29 April 2021|archive-date=29 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210429004234/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-56883078|url-status=live}}</ref> On 28 April, the [[Electoral Commission (United Kingdom)|Electoral Commission]] announced it had opened a formal investigation.<ref>{{Cite news|date=28 April 2021|title=Electoral Commission to investigate Boris Johnson's Downing Street flat renovations|work=[[BBC News]]|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-56915307|access-date=29 April 2021|archive-date=28 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210428222553/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-56915307|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last1=Allegretti|first1=Aubrey|last2=Elgot|first2=Jessica|date=28 April 2021|title=Electoral Commission launches inquiry into Boris Johnson flat refurb|work=[[The Guardian]]|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2021/apr/28/electoral-commission-launches-inquiry-into-boris-johnson-flat-refurb|access-date=29 April 2021|archive-date=29 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210429002311/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2021/apr/28/electoral-commission-launches-inquiry-into-boris-johnson-flat-refurb|url-status=live}}</ref> On the same day Johnson said that he had not broken any laws over the refurbishment and had met the requirements he was obliged to meet.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Wright|first1=Oliver|last2=Swinford|first2=Steven|last3=Zeffman|first3=Henry|date=29 April 2021|title=Downing St concern at 'paper trail' over Boris Johnson's flat redecoration|work=[[The Times]]|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/downing-st-concern-at-paper-trail-over-boris-johnsons-flat-redecoration-qg8vjqj2z|url-status=live|url-access=subscription|access-date=29 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210428231545/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/downing-st-concern-at-paper-trail-over-boris-johnsons-flat-redecoration-qg8vjqj2z|archive-date=28 April 2021}}</ref> During [[Prime Minister's Questions]], the leader of the opposition, [[Keir Starmer]], asked: "Who ''initially'' paid for the redecoration of his Downing Street flat?"; Johnson responded: "I paid for Downing Street's refurbishment personally."<ref>{{cite web |title=Commons Chamber 28th April 2021 |url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2021-04-28/debates/1e6e4033-a1be-4b3c-ab2c-e35376c9a748/CommonsChamber |website=UK Parliament |access-date=30 April 2021 |archive-date=30 April 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210430111347/https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2021-04-28/debates/1e6e4033-a1be-4b3c-ab2c-e35376c9a748/CommonsChamber |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 28 May [[Lord Geidt]] published a report on the allegations which concluded that Johnson did not breach the Ministerial Code and that no conflict, or reasonably perceived conflict, of interest arose. However, Lord Geidt expressed that it was "unwise" for Johnson to have proceeded without "more rigorous regard for how this would be funded".<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Walker|first1=Peter|last2=Allegretti|first2=Aubrey|date=28 May 2021|title=Boris Johnson acted unwisely over flat refurbishment, report finds|work=[[The Guardian]]|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2021/may/28/boris-johnson-acted-unwisely-over-flat-refurbishment-report-finds|access-date=29 May 2021|archive-date=28 May 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210528235256/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2021/may/28/boris-johnson-acted-unwisely-over-flat-refurbishment-report-finds|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|date=29 May 2021|title=Downing Street flat: PM cleared of misconduct but acted unwisely, says watchdog|work=[[BBC News]]|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-57280418|access-date=29 May 2021|archive-date=28 May 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210528235222/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-57280418|url-status=live}}</ref> The Electoral Commission reported on 9 December that it found that the Conservative Party had failed to follow the law in not accurately reporting donations to the party from Lord Brownlow and imposed a £17,800 fine on the party.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Quinn|first=Ben|date=9 December 2021|title=Downing Street refurb: the money trail, inquiries and questions still to answer|work=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2021/dec/09/downing-street-refurb-the-money-trail-inquiries-and-questions-still-to-answer|access-date=30 July 2022|archive-date=31 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220331171313/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2021/dec/09/downing-street-refurb-the-money-trail-inquiries-and-questions-still-to-answer|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":1a">{{Cite news|last=Rodger|first=Hannah|date=9 December 2021|title=Tories fined over £52,000 undeclared donation for Boris Johnson's luxury Downing Street flat refurb|work=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/politics/19773037.tories-fined-52-000-undeclared-donation-boris-johnsons-luxury-downing-street-flat-refurb/|access-date=11 December 2021|archive-date=11 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211211231908/https://www.heraldscotland.com/politics/19773037.tories-fined-52-000-undeclared-donation-boris-johnsons-luxury-downing-street-flat-refurb/|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]'' said the commission's report outlined how, in March, all the money paid by Brownlow and his company had been reimbursed, as had the payments made by the Conservative Party and Cabinet Office.<ref name=":1a" /> Downing Street had said at the time that the full cost of the works had been met personally by the prime minister.<ref name=":1a" />

====Owen Paterson controversy====
{{See also|Owen Paterson#Lobbying and breach of Commons advocacy rules|United Kingdom parliamentary second jobs controversy}}
In November 2021 Johnson backed a motion to block the suspension of [[Owen Paterson]], a Conservative MP found to have abused his position by the [[Parliamentary Commissioner for Standards|independent standards commissioner]] after undertaking paid lobbying.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Maclellan |first1=Kylie |title=UK PM's party slammed for backing overhaul of system that polices lawmakers |url=https://www.reuters.com/world/uk/uk-parliament-votes-shake-up-rules-halt-suspension-conservative-lawmaker-2021-11-03/ |access-date=4 November 2021 |work=Reuters |date=3 November 2021 |archive-date=30 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220730052615/https://www.reuters.com/world/uk/uk-parliament-votes-shake-up-rules-halt-suspension-conservative-lawmaker-2021-11-03/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The motion called for the creation of a new Conservative-majority committee to examine reforms of the standards investigation process.<ref>{{cite news |title=Owen Paterson: Anger as Tory MP avoids suspension in rule shake-up |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-59154221 |access-date=4 November 2021 |work=BBC News |date=3 November 2021 |archive-date=4 November 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211104004818/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-59154221 |url-status=live }}</ref> Many Conservative MPs refused to support the motion, and 13 defied a [[three-line whip]] to vote against it.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Woodcock |first1=Andrew |title=Tories vote to tear up sleaze rules after MP found guilty of paid lobbying |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/owen-paterson-commons-sleaze-standards-b1950763.html |access-date=4 November 2021 |work=The Independent |date=3 November 2021 |archive-date=4 November 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211104002315/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/owen-paterson-commons-sleaze-standards-b1950763.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Following the announcement by opposition parties that they would boycott the new committee, and faced with a backlash in the media and from MPs of all parties, the government announced that a new vote would take place on whether Paterson should be suspended.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-59163961 |title=Owen Paterson row: Government U-turn over MPs' conduct plan |work=BBC News |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=4 November 2021 |access-date=4 November 2021 |archive-date=4 November 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211104105140/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-59163961 |url-status=live }}</ref> Paterson announced his resignation as an MP the same day.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tory MP Owen Paterson resigns amid standards row |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-59167783 |access-date=4 November 2021 |work=BBC News |date=4 November 2021 |archive-date=4 November 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211104144530/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-59167783 |url-status=live }}</ref> A [[2021 North Shropshire by-election|by-election]] in Paterson's former constituency of [[North Shropshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North Shropshire]] saw the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] candidate, [[Helen Morgan (politician)|Helen Morgan]], overturn a Conservative majority of nearly 23,000,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-shropshire-59693102 |title=Tories lose North Shropshire seat they held for nearly 200 years |work=[[BBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211217084843/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-shropshire-59693102 |archive-date=17 December 2021 |url-status=live}}</ref> the [[United Kingdom by-election records#Largest swings|seventh largest swing in United Kingdom by-election history]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/north-shropshire-lib-dems-shock-win-as-tory-by-election-defeat-piles-pressure-on-johnson-12497814 |title=North Shropshire: Liberal Democrats pull off shock win as Tory by-election defeat piles further pressure on Boris Johnson |date=17 December 2021 |first=Alan |last=McGuinness |publisher=[[Sky News]] |access-date=17 December 2021 |archive-date=17 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211217051250/https://news.sky.com/story/north-shropshire-lib-dems-shock-win-as-tory-by-election-defeat-piles-pressure-on-johnson-12497814 |url-status=live }}</ref>

====Partygate scandal====
{{main|Partygate}}
[[File:Christmas 2019 Downing Street Decoration (1).jpg|thumb|Downing Street, where some of the gatherings took place<ref name="bbc12/4/2022">{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dhGDfeo8pRM|title=Partygate: UK PM and chancellor apologise for breaking law in lockdown – BBC News|date=12 April 2022 |via=YouTube|access-date=30 July 2022|archive-date=22 July 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220722190650/https://www.youtube.com/watch?app=desktop&v=dhGDfeo8pRM|url-status=live}}</ref>]]
In December 2021 reports emerged that [[Partygate|social gatherings of government and Conservative Party staff]] in Downing Street had taken place ahead of Christmas 2020 against COVID-19 regulations. Johnson denied these allegations.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Stone |first1=Jon |title=Boris Johnson says 'rules were followed' at No 10 party as Sunak denies attending |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-rishi-sunak-downing-street-party-b1971373.html |work=The Independent |date=7 December 2021 |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=25 May 2022 |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220525/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-rishi-sunak-downing-street-party-b1971373.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Cheese and wine? UK PM's staff joked about alleged lockdown party |url=https://www.reuters.com/world/uk/covid-rules-were-not-broken-downing-street-party-uks-johnson-says-2021-12-07/ |work=Reuters |date=7 December 2021 |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=31 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220531100830/https://www.reuters.com/world/uk/covid-rules-were-not-broken-downing-street-party-uks-johnson-says-2021-12-07/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Following a leaked video showing Downing Street staff joking about a "fictional party", at a press conference rehearsal recorded days after one alleged party took place, Johnson apologised for the contents of the video and suggested he had been misled but had now ordered an inquiry.<ref>{{cite news |title=PM accused of lying after No 10 officials caught joking about Christmas party |last1=Walker |first1=Peter |last2=Allegretti |first2=Aubrey |last3=Grierson |first3=Jamie |date=7 December 2021 |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2021/dec/07/leaked-video-shows-no-10-officials-joking-about-holding-christmas-party |access-date=9 December 2021 |archive-date=9 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211209002840/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2021/dec/07/leaked-video-shows-no-10-officials-joking-about-holding-christmas-party |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|date=8 December 2021|title=PMQs: Boris Johnson sorry for offence caused by aides joking about lockdown party|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-59580640|access-date=8 December 2021|archive-date=8 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211208121845/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-59580640|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 10 January 2022, [[ITV News]] reported that a planned party had taken place on 20 May 2020, during the first lockdown. ITV had obtained an email sent by principal private secretary [[Martin Reynolds (civil servant)|Martin Reynolds]] to staff inviting them to "socially distanced drinks" in the garden of No. 10.<ref name="BYOB">{{cite news |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2022-01-10/email-proves-downing-street-staff-held-drinks-party-at-height-of-lockdown |last=Brand |first=Paul |title=Email proves Downing Street staff held drinks party at height of lockdown |work=ITV News |date=10 January 2022 |access-date=12 January 2022 |archive-date=20 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220120084744/https://www.itv.com/news/2022-01-10/email-proves-downing-street-staff-held-drinks-party-at-height-of-lockdown |url-status=live }}</ref> At the time, people outdoors were not allowed to meet more than one person from outside their household.<ref name="sky12/1/2022">{{cite news |url=https://news.sky.com/story/downing-street-lockdown-party-what-were-the-covid-rules-on-20-may-2020-and-how-many-cases-were-there-12513487 |last=Keay |first=Lara |title=What were the rules on 20 May 2020, what happened in Downing Street, and was Boris Johnson at the party? |publisher=Sky News |date=12 January 2022 |access-date=12 January 2022 |archive-date=11 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220111124233/https://news.sky.com/story/downing-street-lockdown-party-what-were-the-covid-rules-on-20-may-2020-and-how-many-cases-were-there-12513487 |url-status=live }}</ref> Two eyewitnesses later alleged that Johnson and Symonds attended, contradicting Johnson's insistence in December 2021 that there were "no parties".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-59946784 |title='Is this for real?' No escape for No 10 from party claims |date=10 January 2022 |work=BBC News |access-date=12 January 2022 |archive-date=11 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220111182500/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-59946784 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="BYOB"/>

On 12 January 2022, Johnson apologised to MPs in the Commons for "attending an event in the Downing Street garden during the first lockdown",<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-59961535 |title=Downing Street party: PM to face MPs following revelations |date=12 January 2022 |work=BBC News |access-date=12 January 2022 |url-status=live |archive-date=12 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220112024830/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-59961535 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/jan/12/boris-johnson-admits-attending-downing-street-party-during-lockdown |last1=Walker |first1=Peter |last2=Stewart |first2=Heather |title=Boris Johnson admits attending Downing Street party during lockdown |work=The Guardian |date=12 January 2022 |access-date=12 January 2022 |url-status=live |archive-date=12 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220112122819/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/jan/12/boris-johnson-admits-attending-downing-street-party-during-lockdown }}</ref> stating he believed it was "a work event".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2022-01-12/johnson-faces-demands-to-come-clean-over-bring-your-own-booze-party |title=Boris Johnson admits he attended lockdown-breaking party but claims he thought it was work event |work=ITV News |date=12 January 2022 |access-date=12 January 2022 |archive-date=12 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220112001823/https://www.itv.com/news/2022-01-12/johnson-faces-demands-to-come-clean-over-bring-your-own-booze-party |url-status=live }}</ref> He said that MPs should await the outcome of the independent inquiry, led by senior civil servant [[Sue Gray (civil servant)|Sue Gray]], which he said "will report as soon as possible".<ref name="CTQ"/> There were calls across the House for Johnson to resign.<ref name="CTQ">{{Cite news|date=12 January 2022|title=Boris Johnson faces calls to quit after lockdown party apology |work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-59967930|access-date=12 January 2022|archive-date=12 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220112124556/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-59967930|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="bbc12/1/2022">{{Cite news|date=13 January 2022 |title=Boris Johnson: Senior Tories urge PM to quit after party apology|work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-59972859|url-status=live|archive-date=27 July 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220727161206/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-59972859}}</ref>
[[File:Sue Gray report Fig 9.jpg|thumb|An image of Johnson at a social gathering, from [[Sue Gray's report]] into the [[partygate]] scandal.]]
On 19 January, [[Bury South]] MP [[Christian Wakeford]] defected from the Conservative Party to the Labour Party.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bury South MP Christian Wakeford resigns from Conservative to join Labour |url=https://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/19858532.bury-south-mp-christian-wakeford-resigns-conservative-join-labour/ |work=Bury Times |date=19 January 2022 |access-date=19 January 2022 |archive-date=19 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220119115747/https://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/19858532.bury-south-mp-christian-wakeford-resigns-conservative-join-labour/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Conservative former minister [[David Davis (British politician)|David Davis]] called for Johnson to resign, quoting [[Leo Amery]] calling on [[Neville Chamberlain]] to resign during the [[Norway Debate]] in 1940, and saying: "You have sat there too long for all the good you have done. In the name of God, go."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/david-davis-boris-johnson-pmqs-b1996225.html |title='In the name of God, go': Tory MP David Davis tells Boris Johnson to quit |first=Rob |last=Merrick |work=The Independent |date=19 January 2022 |access-date=19 January 2022 |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220525/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/david-davis-boris-johnson-pmqs-b1996225.html |archive-date=25 May 2022 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-politics-60046632 |title=Boris Johnson: Tory MP defects as ex-minister tells Johnson to go |work=BBC News |date=19 January 2022 |access-date=19 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220119110911/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-politics-60046632 |archive-date=19 January 2022 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=19 January 2022 |title=The story behind David Davis's 'In the name of God, go' quote |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/in-the-name-of-god-go-meaning-leo-amery-neville-chamberlain-quote-david-davis-boris-johnson-1411614 |access-date=19 April 2022 |website=[[i (newspaper)|i]] |url-status=live |archive-date=19 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220419193936/https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/in-the-name-of-god-go-meaning-leo-amery-neville-chamberlain-quote-david-davis-boris-johnson-1411614 }}</ref>

On 25 January, the [[Metropolitan Police]]'s chief commander, [[Cressida Dick]], announced that they were commencing investigations into the Downing Street Parties.<ref>{{cite news |title=Police to investigate No 10 lockdown parties |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-60123850 |access-date=25 January 2022 |date=25 January 2022 |archive-date=25 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220125101652/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-60123850 |url-status=live }}</ref> An abbreviated version of the [[Sue Gray report]] into the controversy was released on 31 January, where Gray concluded there was a "failure of leadership" over the events that she had examined. The release of the full report was delayed pending the Metropolitan Police's investigation.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-60210893 |title=Sue Gray: No 10 pledges updated report after police inquiry finishes |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=31 January 2022 |access-date=3 February 2022 |url-status=live |archive-date=3 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220203165526/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-60210893 }}</ref>

In April 2022, Johnson was issued a [[fixed penalty notice]] as police determined that he committed a criminal offence by breaching the COVID-19 lockdown regulations.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Payne |first1=Sebastian |last2=Wright |first2=Robert |last3=Pickard |first3=Jim |last4=Cameron-Chileshe |first4=Jasmine |title=Boris Johnson, wife Carrie and Rishi Sunak fined over Covid lockdown breaches |url=https://www.ft.com/content/d37b20a6-04f4-47af-9d37-a81157ba173f |work=[[Financial Times]]|location=London|publisher=The Financial Times Ltd|date=12 April 2022}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/apr/12/boris-johnson-and-rishi-sunak-fined-for-breaking-covid-lockdown-laws |title=Boris Johnson defies calls to quit after he and Rishi Sunak fined |first1=Rowena |last1=Mason |first2=Aubrey |last2=Allegretti |date=12 April 2022 |website=The Guardian |access-date=13 April 2022 |archive-date=9 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220709005208/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/apr/12/boris-johnson-and-rishi-sunak-fined-for-breaking-covid-lockdown-laws |url-status=live }}</ref> Johnson therefore became the first prime minister in British history to have been sanctioned for breaking the law while in office.<ref name="Scott-2022">{{cite news |last=Scott |first=Jennifer |date=12 April 2022 |title=Boris Johnson and Rishi Sunak to be fined over lockdown parties |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-61083402 |access-date=12 April 2022 |archive-date=12 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220412124621/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-61083402 |url-status=live }}</ref>

According to Downing Street insiders, Johnson was involved in instigating a party on the occasion of [[Lee Cain]] leaving Number 10. What had begun as press office drinks became a party after Johnson arrived, gave a speech and poured drinks for staff. [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]'s deputy leader, [[Angela Rayner]] said, "If the latest reports are true, it would mean that not only did the prime minister attend parties, but he had a hand in instigating at least one of them. He has deliberately misled the British people at every turn. The prime minister has demeaned his office."<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wheeler |first1=Caroline |last2=Yorke |first2=Harry |location=London |title=Boris Johnson has cleared so many hurdles, but he may yet come a cropper |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/boris-johnson-has-cleared-so-many-hurdles-but-he-may-yet-come-a-cropper-dxqg77h28 |work=[[The Sunday Times]] |publisher=[[News UK]] |date=16 April 2022 |access-date=30 July 2022 |url-status=live |archive-date=28 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220528041317/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/boris-johnson-has-cleared-so-many-hurdles-but-he-may-yet-come-a-cropper-dxqg77h28 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Cameron-Chileshe |first1=Jasmine |location=London |title=Johnson accused of demeaning his office after new partygate claims |url=https://www.ft.com/content/498ea736-0868-42a1-a7c9-c9a2d4e33e2e |work=[[Financial Times]] |publisher=Financial Times Ltd |date=17 April 2022 |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=22 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220422055351/https://www.ft.com/content/498ea736-0868-42a1-a7c9-c9a2d4e33e2e |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Wells |first1=Ione |title=Partygate: No easy return for Boris Johnson after Easter break |location=London |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-61140292 |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher=BBC |date=18 April 2022 |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=6 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220606151038/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-61140292 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Sparrow |first1=Andrew |date=17 April 2022 |location=London |title=Report of Boris Johnson pouring drinks 'implies he started lockdown party' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/apr/17/report-of-boris-johnson-pouring-drinks-implies-he-started-lockdown-party-says-labour-partygate |work=The Guardian |access-date=30 July 2022 |url-status=live |archive-date=20 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220720212702/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/apr/17/report-of-boris-johnson-pouring-drinks-implies-he-started-lockdown-party-says-labour-partygate }}</ref> On 21 April, MPs voted to refer Johnson to the [[Commons Select Committee of Privileges|Parliamentary Privileges Committee]] to investigate whether he knowingly misled Parliament.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-politics-61143220|title=Boris Johnson: PM's response to party fine a joke, Starmer tells MPs|website=BBC News|date=19 April 2022 |access-date=30 July 2022|archive-date=19 June 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220619230048/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-politics-61143220|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Steve Baker (politician)|Steve Baker]] said Johnson's "marvellous contrition... only lasted as long as it took to get out of the headmaster's study".<ref>{{cite news|last=Ford Rojas|first=John-Paul|date=21 April 2022|title='The gig's up': Senior Tory backbencher Steve Baker says PM should be 'long gone'|url=https://news.sky.com/story/the-gigs-up-senior-tory-backbencher-steve-baker-says-pm-should-be-long-gone-12595026|publisher=Sky News|access-date=10 July 2022|archive-date=16 July 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220716130711/https://news.sky.com/story/the-gigs-up-senior-tory-backbencher-steve-baker-says-pm-should-be-long-gone-12595026|url-status=live}}</ref>

Following the [[2022 United Kingdom local elections|May 2022 local elections]], many leading Conservatives in areas where the Conservatives had done badly blamed Johnson and calling on Johnson to resign.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mason|first1=Rowena|last2=Stewart|first2=Heather|last3=Allegretti|first3=Aubrey|date=6 May 2022|title=Tory council leaders point finger at Johnson after election losses blamed on Partygate|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/may/06/local-elections-2022-tory-council-leaders-point-finger-at-johnson-after-losses-blamed-on-partygate|work=The Guardian|access-date=10 July 2022|archive-date=27 June 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220627212933/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/may/06/local-elections-2022-tory-council-leaders-point-finger-at-johnson-after-losses-blamed-on-partygate|url-status=live}}</ref> On 6 June, [[Graham Brady]] announced that the threshold for a vote on Johnson's leadership had been passed; the vote was scheduled for later that same day.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Walker |first1=Peter |title=Boris Johnson to face no-confidence vote today as scores of Tory MPs call on him to go |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/jun/06/boris-johnson-face-confidence-vote-scores-tory-mps-call-on-him-to-go |access-date=6 June 2022 |work=The Guardian |date=6 June 2022 |archive-date=6 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220606071522/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/jun/06/boris-johnson-face-confidence-vote-scores-tory-mps-call-on-him-to-go |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 3 March 2023, an interim report from the [[Commons Select Committee of Privileges]] said there was evidence that "strongly suggests" breaches of coronavirus regulations would have been "obvious" to Johnson.<ref name="interimP" /> The report also said "There is evidence that those who were advising Mr Johnson about what to say to the press and in the House were themselves struggling to contend that some gatherings were within the rules".<ref name="interimP" /> Johnson said none of the evidence showed he "knowingly" misled Parliament.<ref name="interimP" /> The report stated that the Commons may have been misled on multiple occasions and Johnson "did not correct the statements [at the] earliest opportunity".<ref name="interimP" /> The committee also stated that Johnson had "personal knowledge" over lockdown gatherings in No 10, which he could have disclosed.<ref name="interimP">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-64836425 Johnson may have misled Parliament over parties, say MPs] ''[[BBC]]''</ref>

====Starmer slur controversy====
[[File:Keir Starmer and Boris Johnson.jpg|thumb|Johnson with [[Keir Starmer]] and former prime minister [[Theresa May]], 14 November 2021]]
While speaking in the House of Commons in January 2022, Johnson falsely blamed Starmer for the non-prosecution of the serial sex offender [[Jimmy Savile]] when Starmer was [[Director of Public Prosecutions (England and Wales)|Director of Public Prosecutions]] in the [[Crown Prosecution Service]]. Starmer was DPP in the years immediately prior to Savile's death but there is no evidence he was involved in the decision to not have him prosecuted.<ref>{{Cite news |date=3 February 2022 |title=No evidence for Boris Johnson's claim about Keir Starmer and Jimmy Savile |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/60213975 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220208163011/https://www.bbc.com/news/60213975 |archive-date=8 February 2022 |access-date=8 February 2022 |work=BBC News}}</ref> A few days later, Johnson defended his comments but conceded that Starmer "had nothing to do personally with those decisions" by the CPS not to investigate Savile.<ref>{{cite web |date=3 February 2022 |title=Boris Johnson tries to 'clarify' Jimmy Savile 'slur' against Sir Keir Starmer after days of criticism |url=https://news.sky.com/video/boris-johnson-tries-to-clarify-jimmy-savile-slur-against-sir-keir-starmer-after-days-of-criticism-12532185 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220207074643/https://news.sky.com/video/boris-johnson-tries-to-clarify-jimmy-savile-slur-against-sir-keir-starmer-after-days-of-criticism-12532185 |archive-date=7 February 2022 |access-date=9 February 2022 |publisher=Sky News}}</ref>

====Vote of confidence====
{{Main|2022 vote of confidence in the Conservative Party leadership of Boris Johnson}}
In the week prior to and throughout the [[Platinum Jubilee of Elizabeth II]] in June 2022, it had been speculated that a vote of confidence in Johnson's leadership of the Conservative Party might soon occur.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Macaskill|first1=Andrew|url=https://www.reuters.com/world/uk/uk-pm-johnson-faces-new-threat-confidence-vote-over-lockdown-parties-2022-05-31/|title=UK's Boris Johnson faces new threat of confidence vote over lockdown parties|work=Reuters|date=31 May 2022|access-date=6 June 2022|archive-date=3 June 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220603014835/https://www.reuters.com/world/uk/uk-pm-johnson-faces-new-threat-confidence-vote-over-lockdown-parties-2022-05-31/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Horton |first1=Harry |title=Vote of no confidence in Boris Johnson could be announced 'as soon as Monday' as MP letters pile up |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2022-06-05/no-confidence-vote-in-pm-could-be-announced-on-monday-as-mp-letters-pile-up |work=The Guardian |date=5 June 2022 |access-date=6 June 2022 |archive-date=6 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220606000418/https://www.itv.com/news/2022-06-05/no-confidence-vote-in-pm-could-be-announced-on-monday-as-mp-letters-pile-up |url-status=live }}</ref> On 6 June 2022, the Conservative Party announced that Johnson would face a vote of confidence in his leadership of the party, after at least 54 Conservative MPs wrote no-confidence letters to Sir [[Graham Brady]], the chairman of the [[1922 Committee]]. Johnson won the vote, with 211 in favour and 148 against.<ref>{{cite news |date=6 June 2022 |title=Tory MPs to vote on Boris Johnson's leadership |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-61703422 |access-date=6 June 2022 |archive-date=6 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220606082250/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-61703422 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="MasonR-2022">{{cite news |last1=Mason |first1=Rowena |date=6 June 2022 |title=Boris Johnson wins no-confidence vote despite unexpectedly large rebellion |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/jun/06/boris-johnson-wins-no-confidence-vote-despite-unexpectedly-large-rebellion |access-date=6 June 2022 |work=[[The Guardian]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220606200653/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/jun/06/boris-johnson-wins-no-confidence-vote-despite-unexpectedly-large-rebellion |archive-date=6 June 2022 }}</ref> The number of rebel MPs was larger than had been expected.<ref name="MasonR-2022"/> The result was described by Keir Starmer as the "beginning of the end" for Johnson's premiership.<ref>{{Cite web |date=6 June 2022 |title=Confidence vote marks 'beginning of the end' for Boris Johnson, Keir Starmer says |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-confidence-vote-keir-starmer-b2094718.html |access-date=7 June 2022 |website=The Independent |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220607042711/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-confidence-vote-keir-starmer-b2094718.html |archive-date=7 June 2022 }}</ref>

====June 2022 by-elections====
Following heavy Conservative defeats in the 23 June 2022 by-elections in [[2022 Wakefield by-election|Wakefield]] and [[2022 Tiverton and Honiton by-election|Tiverton and Honiton]], former party leader Michael Howard called for Johnson to resign, saying: "[Mr Johnson's] biggest asset has always been his ability to win votes but I'm afraid yesterday's results make it clear that he no longer has that ability."<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-61922077|title=By-election defeats: Ex-leader Michael Howard calls for Boris Johnson to go|date=24 June 2022|work=BBC News|access-date=30 July 2022|archive-date=6 July 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220706044124/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-61922077|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/tv/news/michael-howard-boris-johnson-election-b2108851.html|title=Former Tory leader Michael Howard says Johnson should resign after by-election defeat|work=The Independent|date=24 June 2022 |access-date=30 July 2022|archive-date=27 June 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220627185832/https://www.independent.co.uk/tv/news/michael-howard-boris-johnson-election-b2108851.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

[[Oliver Dowden]], the Co-[[Chairman of the Conservative Party]], resigned saying: "somebody must take responsibility".<ref>{{cite news |date=24 June 2022 |title=Tory party chairman Oliver Dowden resigns after double by-election loss |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/oliver-dowden-resigns-conservative-chairman-b2108377.html |access-date=24 June 2022 |website=The Independent |last1=Forrest |first1=Adam |last2=Woodcock |first2=Andrew |archive-date=24 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220624044522/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/oliver-dowden-resigns-conservative-chairman-b2108377.html |url-status=live}}</ref> Johnson announced that he had no intention of changing or resigning; senior Conservatives accused him of increasingly "delusional" behaviour.<ref>{{cite news|title=Boris Johnson's aspiration to serve for a third term 'delusional' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/jun/25/boris-johnsons-aspiration-to-serve-for-a-third-term-delusional|date=25 June 2022|work=The Guardian |access-date=30 July 2022|archive-date=19 July 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220719172900/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/jun/25/boris-johnsons-aspiration-to-serve-for-a-third-term-delusional|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/jun/25/boris-johnsons-aspiration-to-serve-for-a-third-term-delusional |newspaper=[[The Observer]] |location=London |title=Boris Johnson's aspiration to serve for a third term 'delusional' |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220719172900/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/jun/25/boris-johnsons-aspiration-to-serve-for-a-third-term-delusional |archive-date=19 July 2022 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 26 June 2022 Johnson said: "At the moment I'm thinking actively about the third term and what could happen then, but I will review that when I get to it." He also claimed that he intended to stay as prime minister until the mid-2030s, although Number 10 later said that he had been joking.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-61939938 Boris Johnson 'actively thinking about' third term as PM] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220720122832/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-61939938 |date=20 July 2022}} [[BBC News]]. 26 June 2022.</ref>

==== Pincher scandal ====
{{main|Chris Pincher scandal}}
Government Deputy Chief Whip [[Chris Pincher]] resigned on 30 June 2022, saying he had "drunk far too much" the night before at the [[Carlton Club]] in [[St James's]], London, and having "embarrassed myself and other people".<ref>{{cite news |date=1 July 2022 |title=Chris Pincher suspended as Tory MP after groping allegation |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-62014765 |access-date=1 July 2022 |archive-date=1 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220701160833/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-62014765 |url-status=live}}</ref> It was later alleged that he sexually assaulted two men,<ref name="sky2/7/2022">{{cite news |date=2 July 2022 |title=Tory MP Chris Pincher suspended by party over 'drunken groping' claims |publisher=[[Sky News]] |url=https://news.sky.com/story/tory-mp-chris-pincher-suspended-by-party-over-drunken-groping-claims-12643558 |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=7 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220707135005/https://news.sky.com/story/tory-mp-chris-pincher-suspended-by-party-over-drunken-groping-claims-12643558 |url-status=live}}</ref> and he was suspended as an MP.<ref>{{cite news |date=1 July 2022 |title=Chris Pincher suspended as Tory MP after groping allegation |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-62014765 |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=8 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220708223142/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-62014765 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 3 July 2022 six new allegations against Pincher emerged, involving behaviour over a decade.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Snowdon |first1=Kathryn |last2=Seddon |first2=Paul |date=3 July 2022 |title=Chris Pincher: New claims emerge against former Tory MP |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-62025612 |access-date=3 July 2022 |work=BBC News |archive-date=7 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220707125811/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-62025612 |url-status=live }}</ref>

Johnson allegedly referred to Pincher as "handsy" and Cummings said Johnson joked about him being "Pincher by name, pincher by nature" in 2020, leading to calls for Johnson to explain how much he knew about Pincher's behaviour.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Blewett |first1=Sam |last2=Baynes |first2=Chris |date=2 July 2022 |title=Boris Johnson accused of turning blind eye to Chris Pincher allegations |work=[[The Independent]] |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/chris-pincher-grope-allegations-boris-johnson-b2114609.html |access-date=3 July 2022 |archive-date=3 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220703000621/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/chris-pincher-grope-allegations-boris-johnson-b2114609.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Ministers initially said that Johnson was unaware of any specific complaints against Pincher when he was appointed as deputy chief whip. The BBC then reported, however, that an official complaint and subsequent investigation into Pincher, while he was at the Foreign Office (July 2019 to February 2020), had confirmed his misconduct, and that Johnson had been made aware at that time.<ref>{{Cite news |date=5 July 2022 |title=Boris Johnson was made aware of formal Chris Pincher complaint |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-62040915 |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=28 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220728091611/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-62040915 |url-status=live }}</ref> Sir [[Simon McDonald, Baron McDonald of Salford|Simon McDonald]], former [[Permanent Under-Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs]], later said that the prime minister had been briefed "in person" about Pincher.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Davidson |first=Peter |date=5 July 2022 |title=Boris Johnson was told about Pincher inquiry as top official suggests No10 lied |url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/politics/boris-johnson-briefed-person-chris-27399080 |work=Daily Record |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=16 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220716075014/https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/politics/boris-johnson-briefed-person-chris-27399080 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Dimsdale |first=Connie |date=5 July 2022 |title=Simon McDonald letter in full: Peer claims Boris Johnson was briefed in person about Chris Pincher allegations |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/simon-mcdonald-letter-full-boris-johnson-briefed-chris-pincher-allegations-1723526 |work=i |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=25 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220725001112/https://inews.co.uk/news/simon-mcdonald-letter-full-boris-johnson-briefed-chris-pincher-allegations-1723526 |url-status=live }}</ref>

==== Mass resignations ====
{{main|July 2022 United Kingdom government crisis}}
On 5 July 2022, Sunak and Javid resigned within minutes of each other,<ref>{{Cite news |date=5 July 2022 |title=Chris Pincher: PM 'bitterly regrets' appointing MP after complaint |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-62054067 |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=21 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220721191931/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-62054067 |url-status=live }}</ref> followed over the next 24 hours by 11 other ministers, as well as Conservative MPs from [[parliamentary private secretary]] and other Government positions;<ref name="RESIG">{{cite news |date=6 July 2022 |title=Government resignations: Who has gone, who is staying? |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-62058278 |access-date=6 July 2022 |archive-date=5 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220705211035/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-62058278 |url-status=live }}</ref> other [[backbencher]]s also withdrew their support for Johnson. Many of the MPs stated that the Pincher affair had led them to change their minds on the suitability of Johnson to be prime minister.<ref name="RES">{{cite news |last1=Walker |first1=Peter |last2=Mason |first2=Rowena |date=6 July 2022 |title=Johnson hit by further resignations as Zahawi seeks to prop up PM |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/jul/06/boris-johnson-resignations-nadhim-zahawi-will-quince-laura-trott |access-date=6 July 2022 |archive-date=6 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220706085221/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/jul/06/boris-johnson-resignations-nadhim-zahawi-will-quince-laura-trott |url-status=live }}</ref> It was reported on 6 July that Johnson could face another confidence vote, with members of the 1922 Committee considering changing the rules as soon as that evening to allow this to happen.<ref name="VONC">{{cite news |last1=Elgot |first1=Jessica |date=6 July 2022 |title=Boris Johnson could face new confidence vote within days |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/jul/06/boris-johnson-could-face-new-confidence-vote-within-days-1922-committee |access-date=6 July 2022 |archive-date=6 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220706120644/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/jul/06/boris-johnson-could-face-new-confidence-vote-within-days-1922-committee |url-status=live }}</ref> By 6 July, there had been a total of 31 resignations.<ref>{{Cite news |title=The Tory MPs who have quit Boris Johnson's government – listed |last=Mason |first=Rowena |newspaper=The Guardian |date=6 July 2022 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/jul/06/the-tory-mps-who-have-quit-boris-johnsons-government-listed |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=28 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220728185842/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/jul/06/the-tory-mps-who-have-quit-boris-johnsons-government-listed |url-status=live }} 21 names as of 15:00, 6 July 2022</ref> As of May 2022, the government comprised 122 ministers.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Britchfield |first1=Colm |last2=Devine |first2=Dan |last3=Durrant |first3=Tim |title=Government ministers |url=https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/explainers/government-ministers |access-date=6 July 2022 |website=Institute for Government |date=21 May 2019 |archive-date=8 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191208104329/https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/explainers/government-ministers |url-status=live}}</ref>

==== Announcement of resignation ====
By the morning of 7 July, the newly installed [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]], [[Nadhim Zahawi]], publicly stated his belief that Johnson should resign. Within hours, the BBC and other media reported Johnson's intention to resign. Johnson announced his resignation at 12.30&nbsp;pm.<ref>{{cite news |last=Amos|first=Owen|date=7 July 2022|title=Boris Johnson resigns: Five things that led to the PM's downfall|work=[[BBC News]]|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-62070422|access-date=7 July 2022|archive-date=7 July 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220707212744/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-62070422|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Meredith|first=Sam|date=7 July 2022|title=UK Prime Minister Boris Johnson resigns|publisher=CNBC|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2022/07/07/boris-johnson-resigns-as-uk-prime-minister.html|access-date=7 July 2022|archive-date=7 July 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220707113826/https://www.cnbc.com/2022/07/07/boris-johnson-resigns-as-uk-prime-minister.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=7 July 2022 |title=Live: Boris Johnson expected to make statement on his leadership |work=ABC News |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2022-07-07/boris-johnson-government-cabinet-resignations-updates/101212040 |access-date=7 July 2022 |archive-date=7 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220707094625/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2022-07-07/boris-johnson-government-cabinet-resignations-updates/101212040 |url-status=live}}</ref>

{{Blockquote|text=I know that there will be many who are relieved, but perhaps quite a few who will be disappointed. And I want you to know how sad I am to give up the best job in the world - but them's the breaks.}}

Upon reports of his resignation, the [[pound sterling]] temporarily strengthened in value, and UK stocks rose.<ref>{{cite news |date=7 July 2022 |title=Pound Rallies as Johnson's Exit Plan Spells Relief for Traders |work=Bloomberg.com |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-07-07/pound-rallies-as-johnson-s-exit-plan-spells-relief-for-traders |access-date=7 July 2022 |archive-date=16 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220716053049/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-07-07/pound-rallies-as-johnson-s-exit-plan-spells-relief-for-traders |url-status=live}}</ref> He remained as prime minister until September, while the Conservative Party chose a new leader.<ref>{{cite news |date=7 July 2022 |title=Boris Johnson resigns: Johnson will stay on but only as caretaker PM, new cabinet agrees |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-politics-62072419/page/2 |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=15 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220715195951/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-politics-62072419/page/2 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 5 September 2022, it was announced that [[Liz Truss]] had won the [[July–September 2022 Conservative Party leadership election|Conservative leadership election]]. She became prime minister the next day.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/rishi-sunak-boris-johnson-labour-nhs-balmoral-b2160000.html | title=Truss wins Tory leadership race and faces daunting challenge as PM | website=[[The Independent]] | date=5 September 2022 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=6 September 2022 |title=Liz Truss confirmed as prime minister after meeting Queen at Balmoral – UK politics live |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2022/sep/06/liz-truss-pm-boris-johnson-queen-cabinet-reshuffle-rishi-sunak-tories- |access-date=6 September 2022 |website=The Guardian}}</ref> During his farewell speech outside 10 Downing Street on 6 September 2022, Johnson referred to the Roman statesman [[Cincinnatus]]. Some commentators noted that, while, as Johnson said, Cincinnatus returned to his plough, he was also later recalled to power.<ref>{{cite web|first=Jamie|last=Grierson|date=6 September 2022|title=Boris Johnson likens himself to Roman who returned as dictator|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/sep/06/boris-johnson-likens-himself-to-roman-cincinnatus-who-returned-as-dictator|website=[[The Guardian]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220906132030/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/sep/06/boris-johnson-likens-himself-to-roman-cincinnatus-who-returned-as-dictator|archive-date=6 September 2022|url-status=live}}</ref>

=== Environmental policies ===
In November 2020 Johnson announced a 10-point plan for a "green industrial revolution", to include ending the sale of petrol and [[Diesel engine|diesel]] cars and vans by 2030,{{efn|This was a reduction on the 2035 target set in February that year, which brought forward the previous deadline of 2040.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pickard |first1=Jim |last2=Campbell |first2=Peter |date=15 November 2020 |title=UK set to ban sale of new petrol and diesel cars from 2030 |url=https://www.ft.com/content/5e9af60b-774b-4a72-8d06-d34b5192ffb4 |url-status=live |work=Financial Times |archive-url=https://archive.today/20201114110316/https://www.ft.com/content/5e9af60b-774b-4a72-8d06-d34b5192ffb4 |archive-date=14 November 2020 |access-date=5 May 2021 |url-access=subscription}}</ref>}} quadrupling the amount of [[Wind power in the United Kingdom|offshore wind power]] capacity within a decade, funding emissions-cutting proposals, and spurning a proposed [[Green recovery|green post-COVID-19 recovery]].<ref>{{cite news|date=17 November 2020|title=The key areas of Boris Johnson's 'green industrial revolution'|work=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2020/nov/17/the-key-areas-of-boris-johnsons-green-industrial-revolution|access-date=25 November 2020|archive-date=24 November 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201124141019/https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2020/nov/17/the-key-areas-of-boris-johnsons-green-industrial-revolution|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2021 the Johnson government announced plans to cut [[Greenhouse gas emissions by the United Kingdom|carbon emissions]] by 78% by 2035.<ref>{{Cite news|date=22 April 2021|title=Boris Johnson: Climate change about jobs not 'bunny hugging'|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-56843367|access-date=31 May 2021|archive-date=1 June 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210601131601/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-56843367|url-status=live}}</ref>

Johnson announced that the UK would join the Global Methane Pledge to cut [[methane emissions]] by 30% by 2030 at the [[COP26]] summit, which the UK hosted.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Harvey |first1=Fiona |author-link=Fiona Harvey |date=17 September 2021 |title=US and EU pledge 30% cut in methane emissions to limit global heating |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2021/sep/17/us-and-eu-pledge-30-cut-in-methane-emissions-to-limit-global-heating |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211117080921/https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2021/sep/17/us-and-eu-pledge-30-cut-in-methane-emissions-to-limit-global-heating |archive-date=17 November 2021 |access-date=18 November 2021 |work=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Mason|first1=Jeff|last2=Alper|first2=Alexandra|date=18 September 2021|title=Biden asks world leaders to cut methane in climate fight|work=Reuters|url=https://www.reuters.com/business/environment/biden-convenes-world-leaders-discuss-climate-change-ahead-glasgow-summit-2021-09-17/|access-date=8 October 2021|archive-date=8 October 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211008134219/https://www.reuters.com/business/environment/biden-convenes-world-leaders-discuss-climate-change-ahead-glasgow-summit-2021-09-17/|url-status=live}}</ref> Before the summit, representatives of [[Greenpeace]] and [[Friends of the Earth]] criticised Johnson's comments on plans to introduce "enforceable limits" on carbon emissions for other countries, which they accused of being unsubstantive,<ref>{{cite web|date=19 January 2020|title=Boris Johnson accused of making impossible pledge for climate crisis summit|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-climate-change-summit-glasgow-fossil-fuel-paris-agreement-a9289116.html|access-date=19 January 2021|website=The Independent|archive-date=30 November 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201130224530/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-climate-change-summit-glasgow-fossil-fuel-paris-agreement-a9289116.html|url-status=live}}</ref> and his government faced criticism from environmental groups for cutting taxes on domestic air travel, given the [[Environmental effects of aviation in the United Kingdom|environmental impact of aviation]].<ref>{{Cite web|date=27 October 2021|title=Rishi Sunak cuts taxes on domestic flights days before Cop26 climate summit|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/climate-change/news/budget-flight-tax-cut-cop26-b1946258.html|access-date=18 November 2021|website=The Independent|archive-date=18 November 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211118154211/https://www.independent.co.uk/climate-change/news/budget-flight-tax-cut-cop26-b1946258.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

In April 2022, Johnson announced that eight more [[nuclear reactor]]s would be built on existing [[nuclear power plant]] sites and called for an expansion in wind energy.<ref>{{cite news |title=UK to build 8 nuclear reactors amid new energy strategy |url=https://apnews.com/article/russia-ukraine-boris-johnson-business-europe-london-375b3e41fbe17306381d070111f252a4 |access-date=7 April 2022 |work=[[Associated Press]] |date=7 April 2022 |location=London |archive-date=7 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220407132641/https://apnews.com/article/russia-ukraine-boris-johnson-business-europe-london-375b3e41fbe17306381d070111f252a4 |url-status=live}}</ref> Under these plans, up to 95% of the UK's electricity could come from [[low-carbon power]] sources by 2030.<ref>{{cite news |title=Energy strategy: UK plans eight new nuclear reactors to boost production |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-61010605 |access-date=7 April 2022 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=7 April 2022 |archive-date=6 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220406235641/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-61010605 |url-status=live}}</ref>

=== Foreign policy ===
{{further|List of international prime ministerial trips made by Boris Johnson}}
[[File:-G7Biarritz (48632272593).jpg|thumb|Johnson with US president Donald Trump at the [[45th G7 summit|G7 summit]] in [[Biarritz]], 26 August 2019]]
Johnson supported the [[European Union–Mercosur Free Trade Agreement]],<ref>{{cite news|date=24 August 2019|title=Britain joins Germany in criticizing Macron's Mercosur threat|work=Reuters|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-g7-summit-mercosur/britain-joins-germany-in-criticizing-macrons-mercosur-threat-idUSKCN1VE0ON|access-date=30 July 2022|archive-date=31 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220331170459/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-g7-summit-mercosur/britain-joins-germany-in-criticizing-macrons-mercosur-threat-idUSKCN1VE0ON|url-status=live}}</ref> which would form one of the world's largest free trade areas.<ref>{{cite news|date=24 August 2019|title=Amazon fires spark European rift at G7 over Mercosur trade deal|publisher=Deutsche Welle|url=https://www.dw.com/en/amazon-fires-spark-european-rift-at-g7-over-mercosur-trade-deal/a-50154578|access-date=30 July 2022|archive-date=28 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191028224103/https://www.dw.com/en/amazon-fires-spark-european-rift-at-g7-over-mercosur-trade-deal/a-50154578|url-status=live}}</ref> Johnson's government placed importance on the "[[Special Relationship]]" with the [[United Kingdom–United States relations|United States]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=McGee|first=Luke|title=UK's 'special relationship' with the US is more fragile than ever. Just when Boris Johnson is banking on it|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/10/17/politics/special-relationship-election-analysis-gbr-intl/index.html|date=17 October 2020|publisher=CNN|access-date=30 July 2022|archive-date=31 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220331170500/https://www.cnn.com/2020/10/17/politics/special-relationship-election-analysis-gbr-intl/index.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=7 November 2020|title=Biden presidency could bring difficulties for US-UK special relationship|url=https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/news/uk/biden-presidency-could-bring-difficulties-for-us-uk-special-relationship/|agency=Press Association|access-date=30 July 2022|archive-date=26 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210126191012/https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/news/uk/biden-presidency-could-bring-difficulties-for-us-uk-special-relationship/|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2022, his government introduced an [[Rwanda asylum plan|asylum deal]] whereby people entering the UK illegally would be sent to [[Rwanda]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=UK to send asylum seekers to Rwanda under controversial new deal |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2022/4/14/uk-to-sign-deal-to-send-male-channel-refugees-to-rwanda-reports |access-date=20 June 2022 |publisher=Al Jazeera |archive-date=4 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220704132024/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2022/4/14/uk-to-sign-deal-to-send-male-channel-refugees-to-rwanda-reports |url-status=live }}</ref>
