==== Hong Kong and China ====
Johnson said in July 2019 that his government would be very "pro-China" in an interview with the Hong Kong broadcaster [[Phoenix TV]]. He voiced support for Chinese president [[Xi Jinping]]'s infrastructure investment effort, the [[Belt and Road Initiative]], and promised to keep the United Kingdom "the most open economy in Europe" for [[Economy of China#Chinese investment abroad|Chinese investment]].<ref>{{cite news|date=24 July 2019|title='Pro-China' Boris Johnson 'enthusiastic' about belt and road plan|publisher=[[Yahoo! News]]|url=https://sg.news.yahoo.com/pro-china-boris-johnson-enthusiastic-065100165.html|access-date=30 July 2022|archive-date=6 April 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220406173456/https://sg.news.yahoo.com/pro-china-boris-johnson-enthusiastic-065100165.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

In June 2020 Johnson announced that if China were to continue pursuing the [[2020 Hong Kong national security law|Hong Kong national security law]], the UK would offer 350,000 [[Hongkongers|Hong Kong residents]] who are [[British National (Overseas) passport]] holders, and 2.6&nbsp;million other eligible individuals, the chance to move to the UK.<ref>{{cite news|date=1 July 2020|title=Hong Kong: UK makes citizenship offer to residents|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-53246899|access-date=30 July 2022|archive-date=1 July 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200701143437/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-53246899|url-status=live}}</ref> China accused the UK of interfering in its internal affairs.<ref>{{cite news|date=3 June 2020|title=China warns UK 'interfering' in Hong Kong affairs will 'backfire'|publisher=[[Al Jazeera English|Al Jazeera]]|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/6/3/china-warns-uk-interfering-in-hong-kong-affairs-will-backfire|access-date=30 July 2022|archive-date=8 June 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220608135240/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/6/3/china-warns-uk-interfering-in-hong-kong-affairs-will-backfire|url-status=live}}</ref>

Johnson declined to describe the Chinese government's [[Persecution of Uyghurs in China|treatment of the Uyghur people]] as "genocide", despite use of the term by the United States.<ref name="genocide"/> Johnson's government argued that genocide should be decided by the International Criminal Court.<ref>{{cite news |title=Johnson Wins U.K. Vote on Genocide Rulings After China Sanctions |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-03-22/johnson-faces-latest-u-k-tory-rebellion-on-uighur-human-rights |publisher=Bloomberg L.P. |date=22 March 2021}}</ref> Nevertheless, he called what is happening to the [[Uyghurs]] in Xinjiang as "utterly abhorrent".<ref name="genocide">{{cite news |title=Boris Johnson refuses to back Trump and Biden teams in calling Uighur situation 'genocide' |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-uighur-muslims-genocide-trump-biden-b1789997.html |work=The Independent |date=20 January 2021}}</ref>

The UK joined the [[AUKUS]] defence pact with the United States and Australia in September 2021. The pact was denounced by China<ref>{{Cite news|date=17 September 2021|title=Aukus: China denounces US-UK-Australia pact as irresponsible|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-58582573|access-date=17 February 2022|archive-date=16 September 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210916132300/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-58582573|url-status=live}}</ref> and caused a French backlash, as it usurped existing [[Attack-class submarine|plans for Australia to procure French submarines]].<ref>{{cite news|date=22 September 2021|title='Donnez-moi un break': Johnson deepens rift with France over defence deal|work=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2021/sep/22/aukus-row-boris-johnson-tells-france-donnez-moi-un-break|access-date=30 July 2022|archive-date=30 July 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220730052618/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2021/sep/22/aukus-row-boris-johnson-tells-france-donnez-moi-un-break|url-status=live}}</ref>

==== Afghanistan ====
On 8 July 2021 the day after saying he was "apprehensive" about the future of Afghanistan following what was then the [[Withdrawal of United States troops from Afghanistan (2020–2021)|impending withdrawal of US troops]], while announcing the near completion of British troop withdrawal from Afghanistan, Johnson expressed the view that there was "no military path to victory for the [[Taliban]]".<ref>{{Cite news|date=8 July 2021|title=Most of the remaining British troops have left Afghanistan, says Boris Johnson|work=Mint|agency=Agence France-Presse|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/world/most-of-the-remaining-british-troops-have-left-afghanistan-says-boris-johnson-11625747197686.html|access-date=19 August 2021|archive-date=30 July 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220730052616/https://www.livemint.com/news/world/most-of-the-remaining-british-troops-have-left-afghanistan-says-boris-johnson-11625747197686.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Taliban">{{cite news|date=15 August 2021|title=Boris Johnson urges international unity over Taliban as he recalls parliament|work=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2021/aug/15/boris-johnson-urged-to-recall-parliament-over-afghanistan-crisis|access-date=30 July 2022|archive-date=30 July 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220730052615/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2021/aug/15/boris-johnson-urged-to-recall-parliament-over-afghanistan-crisis|url-status=live}}</ref> Following the [[Fall of Kabul (2021)|fall of Kabul to the Taliban]], he blamed the United States for the crisis,<ref>{{cite news|date=16 August 2021|title=Afghanistan crisis: Johnson took holiday as Kabul was about to fall|work=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2021/aug/16/afghanistan-crisis-pm-boris-johnson-ended-summer-holiday|access-date=30 July 2022|archive-date=26 June 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220626203919/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2021/aug/16/afghanistan-crisis-pm-boris-johnson-ended-summer-holiday|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=16 August 2021|title=Blame on Biden? UK PM Johnson says US decision to pull out of Afghanistan 'accelerated' events|work=The Week|url=https://www.theweek.in/news/world/2021/08/16/trouble-for-biden-uk-pm-says-us-decision-to-pull-out-of-afghanista-accelerated-events.html|access-date=30 July 2022|archive-date=16 August 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210816074255/https://www.theweek.in/news/world/2021/08/16/trouble-for-biden-uk-pm-says-us-decision-to-pull-out-of-afghanista-accelerated-events.html|url-status=live}}</ref> saying that [[NATO]] alliance members "could not continue this US-led mission, a mission conceived and executed in support of America, without American logistics, without US air power and without American might".<ref>{{cite news|date=18 August 2021|title=British government details plan to settle 20,000 Afghan refugees in heated emergency debate|publisher=CBC News|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/britain-refugees-afghanistan-1.6144731|access-date=30 July 2022|archive-date=30 July 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220730052618/https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/britain-refugees-afghanistan-1.6144731|url-status=live}}</ref>

==== UK–EU trade negotiation ====
{{Main|Trade deal negotiation between the UK and EU|EU–UK Trade and Cooperation Agreement}}
Following the formal [[Brexit|withdrawal from the European Union]] in January 2020, Johnson's government entered [[Trade negotiation between the UK and the EU|trade negotiations with the EU]].<ref name="Mueller-2021">{{Cite news|last1=Mueller|first1=Benjamin|last2=Robins|first2=Peter|date=8 November 2021|title=What Is Brexit? And How Is It Going?|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/brexit-uk-eu-explained.html|access-date=4 February 2022|issn=0362-4331|archive-date=29 December 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201229062101/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/12/24/world/europe/brexit-uk-eu-explained.html|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Fish for finance|Fisheries was a major topic]] of the negotiations.<ref name="Mueller-2021" /><ref>{{Cite news|date=30 December 2020|title='Boris the betrayer' has swindled us over Brexit, England's fishermen say|work=Reuters|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-fish-idUSKBN29415G|access-date=4 February 2022|archive-date=4 February 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220204114610/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-fish-idUSKBN29415G|url-status=live}}</ref> On 16&nbsp;October 2020 Johnson said that the UK "must get ready" for no trade deal with the EU.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sparrow|first=Andrew|date=16 October 2020|title=Boris Johnson: UK must prepare for no-deal Brexit and 'Australia-style' trade – UK politics live|work=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/oct/16/uk-coronavirus-live-boris-johnson-local-restrictions-lockdown-tier-2-covid-brexit-latest-updates|access-date=16 October 2020|archive-date=16 October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201016084900/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/oct/16/uk-coronavirus-live-boris-johnson-local-restrictions-lockdown-tier-2-covid-brexit-latest-updates|url-status=live}}</ref> It was announced on 24&nbsp;December 2020<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Boffey|first1=Daniel|last2=O'Carroll|first2=Lisa|date=24 December 2020 |title=UK and EU agree Brexit trade deal|work=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/dec/24/uk-eu-agree-brexit-trade-deal-agreement|access-date=3 January 2021|archive-date=29 December 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201229024159/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/dec/24/uk-eu-agree-brexit-trade-deal-agreement|url-status=live}}</ref> that the [[EU–UK Trade and Cooperation Agreement]] had been reached; it came into force formally on 1 May. A [[2021 Jersey dispute|fisheries dispute between the UK and France]] occurred shortly afterwards. Introduction of new UK border checks were delayed until 2022 to minimise the disruption caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.<ref name="Mueller-2021" />

In May 2022, Johnson readied a draft that would unilaterally change parts of the [[Northern Ireland Protocol]], citing issues with medical supplies and cuts in VAT. One of the thornier points of contention involves safety regulations for food and plants, where the British government is opposed to a closer alignment with existing EU regulations. The EU rebuffed the idea of changing the text of the treaty to accommodate the British. A unilateral override by the UK would be tantamount to a breach of the agreement. As Johnson sought a more conciliatory tone, sources within the government began to stress that the draft is designed to be an "insurance policy" and would take years to become law.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Smyth |first1=Chris |last2=Waterfield |first2=Bruno |last3=Charter |first3=David |title=Boris Johnson defies warnings over Northern Ireland protocol |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/boris-johnson-defies-warnings-over-northern-ireland-protocol-mvtskzfvs |date=16 May 2022 |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=5 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220705185157/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/boris-johnson-defies-warnings-over-northern-ireland-protocol-mvtskzfvs |url-status=live }}</ref>

==== Russia and Ukraine ====
[[File:President of Ukraine Volodymyr Zelenskyy and Prime Minister of the United Kingdom Boris Johnson walked around the center of Kyiv. (51994084277).jpg|thumb|right|Johnson walks on a street of war-hit [[Kyiv]] along with [[President of Ukraine]] [[Volodymyr Zelenskyy]] on 10 April 2022]]
In November 2021 Johnson warned that the European Union faces "a choice" between "sticking up for Ukraine" and approving the [[Nord Stream 2]] natural gas pipeline from Russia to Europe.<ref>{{cite news |title=Boris Johnson warns EU to choose between Ukraine and Nord Stream 2 |url=https://www.ft.com/content/93c720de-bf39-4803-b1ec-1cd1798431e9 |work=Financial Times |date=15 November 2021 |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=22 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220722061812/https://www.ft.com/content/93c720de-bf39-4803-b1ec-1cd1798431e9 |url-status=live }}</ref>

During the [[prelude to the Russian invasion of Ukraine]], Johnson's government warned the Russian Government not to invade [[Donbas]].<ref>{{Cite news|date=1 February 2022|title=Boris Johnson visits Ukraine for talks as Russian invasion fears rise|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-60204847|access-date=1 February 2022|archive-date=31 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220131225343/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-60204847|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Sheridan|first=Danielle|date=31 January 2022|title=Boris Johnson puts Vladimir Putin on hold, allowing France to seize diplomatic initiative|work=The Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2022/01/31/boris-johnson-phone-call-vladimir-putin-ukraine-delayed-amid/|access-date=1 February 2022|issn=0307-1235|archive-date=31 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220131233456/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2022/01/31/boris-johnson-phone-call-vladimir-putin-ukraine-delayed-amid/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|date=30 January 2022|title=Ukraine crisis: What's at stake for the UK?|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-60159622|access-date=1 February 2022|archive-date=1 February 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220201004220/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-60159622|url-status=live}}</ref> Johnson and [[Vladimir Putin]] agreed in a phone call to work towards a "peaceful resolution".<ref>{{cite news |title=UK, Russian leaders discuss Ukraine crisis in phone call |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2022/2/2/uk-russian-leaders-discuss-ukraine-crisis-in-phone-call |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=2 February 2022 |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=6 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220606145348/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2022/2/2/uk-russian-leaders-discuss-ukraine-crisis-in-phone-call |url-status=live }}</ref> On 1 February 2022, Johnson arrived in [[Kyiv]] on a diplomatic visit.<ref>{{Cite web|date=1 February 2022|title=Johnson-Putin call rescheduled as PM's diplomacy drive falters|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/feb/01/boris-johnson-rebuffed-in-bid-to-play-key-role-in-ukraine-diplomacy|access-date=1 February 2022|website=The Guardian|archive-date=1 February 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220201110902/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/feb/01/boris-johnson-rebuffed-in-bid-to-play-key-role-in-ukraine-diplomacy|url-status=live}}</ref> He called the presence of the [[Russian Armed Forces]] near the [[Russia–Ukraine border]] "the biggest security crisis that Europe has faced for decades".<ref name="rferl">{{cite news |title=British PM Says Europe In Most Serious Security Crisis In Decades Over Ukraine |url=https://www.rferl.org/a/31695968.html |publisher=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty |date=10 February 2022 |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=30 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220730052619/https://www.rferl.org/a/russia-ukraine-truss-lavrov-exercises/31695968.html |url-status=live }}</ref> The Kremlin denied that it wanted to attack Ukraine.<ref name="rferl"/> On 20 February 2022, Johnson warned that Russia is planning the "biggest war in Europe since [[World War II|1945]]" as Putin intends to invade and encircle Kyiv.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ukraine: Russia plans biggest war in Europe since 1945 – Boris Johnson |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-60448162 |work=BBC News |date=20 February 2022 |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=23 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220223103748/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-60448162 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 21 February 2022, Johnson condemned [[Recognition of the Donetsk People's Republic and the Luhansk People's Republic by the Russian Federation|Russia's diplomatic recognition]] of two [[Self-declared states|self-proclaimed]] republics in Donbas.<ref>{{cite news |title=Britain prepares Russia sanctions, says Ukraine invasion could be imminent |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-ukraine-crisis-britian-johnson/putins-recognition-of-breakaway-ukraine-regions-is-clear-break-of-international-law-uks-johnson-idUSKBN2KQ1TS |work=Reuters |date=21 February 2021 |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=22 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220222011031/https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-ukraine-crisis-britian-johnson/putins-recognition-of-breakaway-ukraine-regions-is-clear-break-of-international-law-uks-johnson-idUSKBN2KQ1TS |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 24 February 2022, Johnson condemned the [[Russian invasion of Ukraine]], and ensured the UK joined in [[International sanctions during the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine|international sanctions]] on Russian banks and [[Russian oligarchs|oligarchs]].<ref>{{Cite news |date=24 February 2022 |title=Ukraine conflict: UK sanctions target Russian banks and oligarchs |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-60515626 |access-date=6 April 2022 |archive-date=6 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220406224114/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-60515626 |url-status=live }}</ref> He later announced the UK would phase out [[Russian oil]] by the end of 2022.<ref>{{Citation |title=Boris Johnson outlines plan to phase out Russian oil and gas by end of 2022 |date=9 March 2022 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/tv/news/boris-johnson-russian-oil-ukraine-b2031837.html |access-date=6 April 2022 |archive-date=6 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220406121243/https://www.independent.co.uk/tv/news/boris-johnson-russian-oil-ukraine-b2031837.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 9 April 2022, Johnson travelled to Kyiv and met the [[President of Ukraine]], [[Volodymyr Zelenskyy]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/apr/09/boris-johnson-meets-volodymyr-zelenskiy-in-unannounced-visit-to-kyiv|title=Boris Johnson meets Volodymyr Zelenskiy in unannounced visit to Kyiv|date=9 April 2022|website=The Guardian|access-date=30 July 2022|archive-date=4 May 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220504073305/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/apr/09/boris-johnson-meets-volodymyr-zelenskiy-in-unannounced-visit-to-kyiv|url-status=live}}</ref> On 16 April 2022, Russia's [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Russia)|Ministry for Foreign Affairs]] banned Johnson and a number of senior British politicians from visiting Russia, saying that Britain aimed to isolate Russia politically and supply "the Kyiv regime with lethal weapons and coordinating similar efforts on the part of NATO".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-61126391 |title=Ukraine war: Russia bans Boris Johnson from country over Ukraine war |work=BBC News |date=16 April 2022 |access-date=30 July 2022 |url-status=live |archive-date=18 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220418075731/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-61126391}}</ref>

Within Ukraine, Johnson is praised by many as a supporter of anti-Russian sanctions and [[List of military aid to Ukraine during the Russo-Ukrainian War|military aid for Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Spencer |first1=Richard |title=Ukrainians rename Odesa road as Boris Johnson Street |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/ukrainians-rename-odesa-road-as-boris-johnson-street-f0cmk0fw3 |access-date=2 May 2022 |work=The Times |date=24 April 2022 |archive-date=4 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220504121741/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/ukrainians-rename-odesa-road-as-boris-johnson-street-f0cmk0fw3 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 3 May, Johnson [[Web conferencing|virtually addressed]] the [[Ukrainian Parliament]], becoming the first world leader to speak in Ukraine since the invasion. He pledged an extra £300m in military aid to Ukraine, praised Ukraine's resistance to Russia as its "finest hour" and said that the West had been "too slow to grasp what was actually happening" prior to Russia's invasion.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Morris |first1=Sophie |title=Ukraine war: UK sends £300m more in military aid as PM set to praise country's 'finest hour' |url=https://news.sky.com/story/ukraine-war-boris-johnson-to-become-first-world-leader-to-address-countrys-parliament-since-conflict-began-12604138 |access-date=2 May 2022 |publisher=Sky News |date=2 May 2022 |archive-date=2 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220502213340/https://news.sky.com/story/ukraine-war-boris-johnson-to-become-first-world-leader-to-address-countrys-parliament-since-conflict-began-12604138 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Ukraine war: West too slow to grasp Russian threat to Ukraine, says PM |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-61297478 |access-date=3 May 2022 |work=BBC News |date=3 May 2022 |url-status=live |archive-date=3 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220503003529/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-61297478 }}</ref> In July 2022, Johnson warned that it would be a mistake to cease fire and [[Peace negotiations in the Russian invasion of Ukraine|freeze the conflict]].<ref>{{cite news |title='It could take years': NATO secretary-general warns of a possible lengthy war in Ukraine |url=https://www.euronews.com/2022/06/19/it-could-take-years-nato-secretary-general-warns-of-a-possible-lengthy-war-in-ukraine |work=Euronews |date=19 June 2022}}</ref> In August 2022, Johnson blamed Vladimir Putin for the emerging [[2021–present global energy crisis|global energy crisis]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Liz Truss under renewed pressure to outline cost of living support |url=https://www.ft.com/content/77c82ab5-5916-4dac-b4e9-12935e3eff5c |work=Financial Times |date=28 August 2022}}</ref>

== Post-premiership (2022–present) ==
{{overly detailed|section|date=May 2024}}
[[File:John Rose and Boris Johnson at the Republican Study Committee in 2023.jpg|thumb|upright|Johnson with U.S. Representative [[John Rose (Tennessee politician)|John Rose]] in 2023]]After stepping down, Johnson reverted to being a backbench MP.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/boris-johnson-to-continue-as-member-of-parliament-after-resigning-as-uk-pm-aide-says/939htl9xr |title=Boris Johnson to continue as member of parliament after resigning as UK prime minister |date=22 July 2022 |work=[[SBS (Australian TV channel)|SBS]] |access-date=30 September 2022 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://people.com/royals/boris-johnson-says-queen-elizabeth-was-bright-focused-last-meeting-prime-minister-two-days-before-death/ |title=Boris Johnson Says Queen Elizabeth Was 'Bright and Focused' in Last Meeting 2 Days Before Her Death |last=Juneau |first=Jan |date=12 September 2022 |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |access-date=30 September 2022 }}</ref> Following the [[death of Queen Elizabeth II]], Johnson took part in [[Charles III]]'s [[Proclamation of accession of Charles III|Accession Council]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/boris-johnson-statement-former-pm-pays-emotional-tribute-queen-1842612 |title=Boris Johnson statement: Former PM pays emotional tribute to the Queen after her death |last=Ferguson |first=Emma |date=8 September 2022 |work=[[i (newspaper)|i]] |access-date=30 September 2022 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2022/sep/19/all-six-living-former-prime-ministers-among-queens-funeral-congregation |title=All six living former prime ministers among Queen's funeral congregation |last=Mason |first=Rowena |date=19 September 2022 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=30 September 2022 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/all-six-uk-former-premiers-gather-as-charles-is-proclaimed-king/ |title=Boris, meet Tony: Every living ex-UK prime minister gathers as Charles is proclaimed king |last=Gallardo |first=Cristina |date=10 September 2022 |work=[[Politico]] |access-date=30 September 2022 }}</ref>

After [[Liz Truss]] announced her resignation as Conservative Party leader on 20 October 2022, Johnson received more than the 100 MPs' nominations required to stand in the [[October 2022 Conservative Party leadership election|leadership election]],<ref name="BBC2110">{{cite news |last1=Francis |first1=Same |title=Could Boris Johnson really make a comeback? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-63342114 |work=[[BBC News Online]] |access-date=21 October 2022 |date=21 October 2022 }}</ref> but soon announced that he would not stand.<ref>{{Cite news |date=4 November 2022 |title=Boris Johnson had backing to challenge Rishi Sunak, Sir Graham Brady confirms |work=[[BBC News Online]] |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-63503932 }}</ref><ref name="Enokido-Lineham-2022">{{Cite news |url=https://news.sky.com/story/boris-johnson-pulls-out-of-conservative-leadership-race-12728576 |title=Boris Johnson pulls out of Conservative leadership race |first=Olive |last=Enokido-Lineham |publisher=[[Sky News]] |date=23 October 2022 |access-date=23 October 2022 }}</ref><ref name="Mason-2022">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/oct/23/boris-johnson-says-he-will-not-stand-in-tory-leadership-contest|title=Boris Johnson says he will not stand in Tory leadership contest |first=Rowena |last=Mason |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=23 October 2022 |access-date=23 October 2022 }}</ref>

In May 2023, Johnson was referred to the police by the Cabinet Office regarding previously unknown potential breaches of COVID regulations between June 2020 and May 2021,<ref name=ChequersPoliceBBC>{{Cite news |date=23 May 2023 |title=Boris Johnson referred to police over potential Covid rule breaches |language=en-GB |work=[[BBC News Online]] |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-65690243 |access-date=25 May 2023}}</ref> to which Johnson's office issued a statement criticising the "unfounded suggestions" which "has all the hallmarks of yet another politically motivated stitch-up".<ref name=ChequersPoliceBBC />

On 9 June 2023, the publication of his [[2022 Prime Minister's Resignation Honours (Boris Johnson)|2022 Prime Minister's Resignation Honours]] led to a public feud with Sunak.<ref>{{Cite news |date=10 June 2023 |title=Chris Mason: The ghost of Boris Johnson haunts Rishi Sunak |language=en-GB |work=[[BBC News Online]] |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-65864011 |access-date=12 June 2023}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=12 June 2023 |title=Boris Johnson and Rishi Sunak trade barbs in row over honours list |work=[[BBC News Online]] |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-65876723 |access-date=12 June 2023}}</ref> Johnson supporter [[Nadine Dorries]] announced that she was resigning as an MP due to not being included as a peer on the honours list.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rogers |first=Alexandra |title=Nadine Dorries claims 'sinister forces' were behind House of Lords snub |work=[[Sky News]] |date=13 June 2023 |url=https://news.sky.com/story/nadine-dorries-claims-sinister-forces-were-behind-house-of-lords-snub-12901468 }}</ref> The same day, after receiving a confidential report from a committee of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] that was looking into whether he had lied to Parliament over lockdown-breaking parties, Johnson announced his resignation as MP.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Boris Johnson re-selected to run in Uxbridge at next general election after suggestions of safer seat |url=https://news.sky.com/story/boris-johnson-re-selected-to-run-in-uxbridge-at-next-general-election-after-suggestions-of-safer-seat-12835826 |access-date=10 June 2023 |work=[[Sky News]] }}</ref> His resignation statement said he is "not alone in thinking that there is a witch-hunt under way, to take revenge for Brexit and ultimately to reverse the 2016 referendum result".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2023/jun/09/it-is-sad-to-be-leaving-for-now-boris-johnsons-resignation-statement-in-full |title='It is sad to be leaving ... for now': Boris Johnson's resignation statement in full |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=9 June 2023 }}</ref>

On 15 June, the Commons Privileges Committee published their report, which concluded that Johnson lied to and deliberately misled the House of Commons over Partygate, misled the Committee themselves during the hearing, and acted in contempt of the Committee itself through a "campaign of abuse and intimidation".<ref>{{cite news |first1=Pippa|last1= Crerar|first2= Aubrey |last2=Allegretti|title=Johnson deliberately misled Parliament over Partygate, damning report finds |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2023/jun/15/johnson-deliberately-misled-parliament-over-partygate-damning-report-finds |access-date=15 June 2023 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=15 June 2023}}</ref> The report noted that had Johnson still been an MP, the Committee would have recommended he be suspended from Parliament for 90 days.<ref>{{cite news |title=Boris Johnson would be facing 90-day suspension if still an MP |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-politics-65876914 |access-date=15 June 2023 |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date=15 June 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Matter referred on 21 April 2022 (conduct of Rt Hon Boris Johnson): Final Report |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm5803/cmselect/cmprivi/564/summary.html |publisher=[[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] }}</ref> The contents of the report represented a recommendation to the House of Commons,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Baker |first=Tim |date=16 June 2023 |title=Rishi Sunak facing potentially acrimonious vote on Boris Johnson partygate report |url=https://news.sky.com/story/rishi-sunak-facing-potentially-acrimonious-vote-on-boris-johnson-partygate-report-12903366 |access-date=17 June 2023 |work=[[Sky News]] }}</ref> which accepted the report by 354 votes to seven.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Forrest |first1=Adam |last2=Dearden |first2=Lizzie |title=Humiliation for Boris Johnson as MPs back ban over Partygate lies |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-banned-parliament-partygate-b2360396.html |access-date=15 July 2023 |work=[[The Independent]] |date=20 June 2023 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Boris Johnson: MPs back Partygate report as just seven vote against |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-65953605 |access-date=15 July 2023 |work=BBC News |date=19 June 2023}}</ref>[[File:President of Ukraine and the former Prime Minister of the United Kingdom talked to students of Taras Shevchenko National University of Kyiv on the Day of Unity. (52717480094).jpg|thumb|Johnson with students and lecturers of [[Taras Shevchenko National University]] of Kyiv, Ukraine, 22 January 2023]]On 16 June, Johnson was unveiled as a new columnist for the ''[[Daily Mail]]''. The news website ''[[Politico Europe]]'' reported that Johnson would be paid a "very-high six-figure sum".<ref>{{cite news |last=McDonald |first=Andrew |date=16 June 2023 |title=Boris Johnson lands 'six-figure' Daily Mail column. Good luck getting him to file on time |work=[[Politico]] |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/boris-johnson-to-write-six-figure-column-for-the-daily-mail/ |accessdate=21 June 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Sarkar |first1=Alisha Rahaman |last2=Mathers |first2=Matt |last3=Gregory |first3=Andy |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-vote-result-house-of-commons-partygate-b2360572.html |title=Boris Johnson – latest: MPs back scathing Partygate report and sanctions in humiliation for ex-PM |work=The Independent |date=20 June 2023 |accessdate=21 June 2023 }}</ref> Johnson reportedly informed the [[Advisory Committee on Business Appointments]] half an hour before the columnist assignment was publicly announced. The committee ruled that Johnson committed a "clear breach" of the rules since he had not sought its advice on the matter within an appropriate timeframe.<ref>{{cite news |last=Brown |first=Faye |url=https://news.sky.com/story/boris-johnson-in-clear-breach-of-rules-after-daily-mail-job-announced-says-mp-watchdog-12903648 |title=Boris Johnson in 'clear breach' of rules after Daily Mail job announced, says MP watchdog |work=Sky News |publisher=Sky |date=16 June 2023 |accessdate=21 June 2023 }}</ref><ref name="Scott 2023 z305">{{cite web | last=Scott | first=Jennifer | title=Boris Johnson committed 'clear and unambiguous' rule breach by taking columnist job, says watchdog | website=Sky News | date=27 June 2023 | url=https://news.sky.com/story/boris-johnson-committed-clear-and-unambiguous-rule-breach-by-taking-columnist-job-says-watchdog-12910361 | access-date=27 June 2023}}</ref>

In October 2023, Johnson announced he would join the television channel [[GB News]] as a commentator and programme maker for the [[2024 United Kingdom general election|next general election]] and [[2024 United States presidential election|US presidential election]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=27 October 2023 |title=Former Prime Minister Boris Johnson joins GB News |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-67242822 |access-date=28 October 2023 |website=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Mason |first=Rowena |date=27 October 2023 |title=Boris Johnson to join GB News as presenter |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2023/oct/27/boris-johnson-join-gb-news-presenter |access-date=28 October 2023 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

Johnson condemned [[Hamas]]' attack [[7 October attacks|on Israel]], saying "there can be no moral equivalence between the terrorism of Hamas and the actions of the Israeli Defense Forces". He rejected calls for a ceasefire in the [[Gaza humanitarian crisis (2023–present)|Gaza Strip]] during the [[Israel–Hamas war]], and criticised [[Israel–Hamas war protests in the United Kingdom|pro-Palestinian protests in the UK]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ex-UK PM Johnson: Marchers for 'Free Palestine' give moral support to Hamas terrorists |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/ex-leader-of-uk-australia-johnson-and-morrison-arrive-in-israel-in-show-of-support/ |work=The Times of Israel |date=5 November 2023}}</ref> On 5 November 2023, Johnson visited Israel to express solidarity.<ref>{{cite news |title=Boris Johnson jets to Israel to 'express solidarity' after Hamas attacks |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/boris-johnson-israel-hamas-b2441887.html |work=The Independent |date=5 November 2023}}</ref>

In February 2024, Johnson had a private meeting with the president of Venezuela, [[Nicolás Maduro]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wells |first1=Ione |title=Boris Johnson flew to Venezuela for unofficial talks |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-68526317 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=10 March 2024}}</ref> In March 2024, ''The Times'' reported that Johnson is expected to campaign for the Conservatives in the next General Election.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Swinford |first1=Steven |title=Boris Johnson to make a general election comeback for the Tories |work=The Times |date=12 March 2024}}</ref>

On 2 May 2024 Johnson was turned away from his polling station for the [[2024 England and Wales police and crime commissioner elections|Thames Valley Police and Crime Commissioner]], after forgetting to bring [[Elections Act 2022|valid photographic identification]], a requirement of the [[Elections Act 2001|Elections Act]], which Johnson introduced while in office. When he arrived he had nothing to prove his identity except the sleeve of his copy of ''[[Prospect (magazine)|Prospect]]'' magazine, on which his name and address had been printed. He said that when he returned a few minutes later, with his [[Driving licence in the United Kingdom|driving licence]], he was then able to vote.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/article/2024/may/04/boris-johnson-pays-tribute-to-polling-staff-who-refused-to-let-him-vote-without-id|title=Boris Johnson 'pays tribute' to polling staff who refused to let him vote without ID |date=4 May 2024|work=The Guardian}}</ref> During the [[2024 United Kingdom general election|2024 general election]], Johnson campaigned for the Conservatives, who lost the election in a landslide to Labour.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Boris Johnson revs up the faithful with vintage performance - but the cameo's too late to save the Tories |url=https://news.sky.com/story/boris-johnson-revs-up-the-faithful-with-vintage-performance-but-the-cameos-too-late-to-save-the-tories-13162656 |access-date=3 July 2024 |website=Sky News |language=en}}</ref>

Johnson's memoirs ''[[Unleashed (book)|Unleashed]]'' were released in October 2024.<ref>{{Cite web |title=HarperCollins to unleash Boris Johnson's memoir in October |url=https://www.thebookseller.com/news/harpercollins-to-unleash-former-pm-boris-johnsons-memoir-in-october |access-date=20 June 2024 |website=The Bookseller |language=En}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Penna |first=Dominic |date=20 June 2024 |title=Boris Johnson announces release date for 'unrestrained' memoir |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2024/06/20/boris-johnson-memoir-unleashed-release-date-announced/ |access-date=20 June 2024 |work=The Telegraph |language=en-GB |issn=0307-1235}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Shaffi |first=Sarah |date=16 January 2023 |title=Boris Johnson to publish 'memoir like no other' of his time as PM |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2023/jan/16/boris-johnson-to-publish-memoir-like-no-other-of-his-time-as-pm |access-date=20 June 2024 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

==Political positions and ideology==
{{main|Political positions of Boris Johnson}}
[[File:Boris Johnson hartismere.jpg|thumb|Johnson at a demonstration against hospital closures with Liberal Democrat MP [[John Hemming (politician)|John Hemming]] (left) and Conservative MP [[Graham Stuart (politician)|Graham Stuart]] (centre) in March 2006]]
{{quote box|width=25em|align=right|quote=[I am] free-market, tolerant, broadly libertarian (though perhaps not ultra-libertarian), inclined to see the merit of traditions, anti-regulation, pro-immigrant, pro-standing on your own two feet, pro-alcohol, pro-hunting, pro-motorist and ready to defend to the death the right of [[Glenn Hoddle#Dismissal from England job|Glenn Hoddle to believe in reincarnation]].|author= —&thinsp;Boris Johnson, 2011{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=225}}}}

Ideologically, Johnson has been described as a "[[One-Nation Tory]]".<ref>{{cite news |last=Ferguson |first=Niall |author-link=Niall Ferguson |title=It's One Nation under Boris Johnson's populist groove |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/its-one-nation-under-boris-johnsons-populist-groove-s5vqb3vbk |url-status=live |website=[[The Times]] |date=15 December 2019 |access-date=4 January 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201028180329/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/its-one-nation-under-boris-johnsons-populist-groove-s5vqb3vbk |archive-date=28 October 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Parker |first=George |date=21 December 2014 |title=Boris Johnson aims to win back voters as 'One Nation Tory' |url=https://www.ft.com/content/74339ea2-88f8-11e4-ad5b-00144feabdc0 |url-status=live |work=Financial Times |location=London |archive-url=https://archive.today/20161214213726/https://www.ft.com/content/74339ea2-88f8-11e4-ad5b-00144feabdc0 |archive-date=14 December 2016 |access-date=5 May 2021 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> Political scientists have described Johnson's political positions as ambiguous and contradictory, encompassing [[Nativism (politics)|nativist]], authoritarian and [[free market]] tendencies on the one hand, and one-nation [[liberal conservatism]] on the other.<ref name="Hayton_2021" >{{cite journal |last=Hayton |first=Richard |title=Conservative Party Statecraft and the Johnson Government |journal=The Political Quarterly |volume=92 |issue=3 |pages=412–419 |date=July 2021 |s2cid=236571324 |doi=10.1111/1467-923X.13006|doi-access=free }}</ref> Some scholars have questioned Johnson's commitment to one-nation conservativism, instead characterising his ideology as flexible and populist.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Mornington |first=Alicia-Dorothy |title=Was Boris Johnson's One-Nation Post-Electoral Pledge Sincere? |journal=French Journal of British Studies |volume=25 |issue=3 |date=29 June 2020 |s2cid=225755384 |doi=10.4000/rfcb.5693|doi-access=free }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Williams |first=Ben |title=Boris Johnson – one nation Conservative or populist? |url=https://www.politicshome.com/thehouse/article/boris-johnson-one-nation-conservative-or-populist |work=Politics Home |date=11 February 2022 |access-date=9 August 2022}}</ref> Purnell stated that Johnson regularly changed his opinion on political issues, commenting on what she perceived to be "an ideological emptiness beneath the staunch Tory exterior".{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=2}}

During his tenure as mayor, Johnson gained a reputation as "a liberal, centre-ground politician", according to ''[[Business Insider]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Conservative moderates plan to take back control of Boris Johnson as prime minister |first1=Adam |last1=Payne |first2=Adam |last2=Bienkov |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/boris-johnson-conservative-leadership-race-moderate-mp-brexit-theresa-may-2019-5?r=US&IR=T |website=[[Business Insider]] |date=23 May 2019 |access-date=26 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406193257/https://www.businessinsider.com/boris-johnson-conservative-leadership-race-moderate-mp-brexit-theresa-may-2019-5?r=US&IR=T |url-status=live |archive-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> In 2012, the political scientist [[Tony Travers]] described Johnson as "a fairly classic—that is, small-state—mildly [[Euroscepticism in the United Kingdom|eurosceptic]] Conservative" who also embraced "modern social liberalism".<ref name="Channel4">{{cite news |title=Boris Johnson: Classic Tory or Political Maverick? |work=[[Channel 4 News]] |date=9 October 2012 |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/borish-johnson-classic-tory-or-political-maverick |access-date=26 May 2019 |url-status=live |archive-date=18 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150318042522/https://www.channel4.com/news/borish-johnson-classic-tory-or-political-maverick}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' stated that while mayor, Johnson blended economic and social liberalism,<ref>{{cite news |title=Mayor Boris, the liberal |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |last=Hill |first=Dave |date=4 December 2008 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/dec/04/boris-johnson-london-mayor-conservatives |access-date=11 December 2016 |url-status=live |archive-date=11 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181111063703/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/dec/04/boris-johnson-london-mayor-conservatives}}</ref> with ''[[The Economist]]'' saying that in doing so Johnson "transcends his Tory identity" and adopts a more libertarian perspective.<ref>{{cite news |title=Generation Boris |newspaper=[[The Economist]] |location=London |date=1 June 2013 |url=https://www.economist.com/news/britain/21578666-britains-youth-are-not-just-more-liberal-their-elders-they-are-also-more-liberal-any |url-access=subscription |access-date=5 May 2021 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150103002329/https://www.economist.com/news/britain/21578666-britains-youth-are-not-just-more-liberal-their-elders-they-are-also-more-liberal-any |archive-date=3 January 2015}}</ref> According to political scientist Richard Hayton, Johnson's premiership was about Brexit, which served as a "national cause". Johnson evoked the discourse of [[popular sovereignty]] and [[anti-establishment]] populism to portray Parliament as seeking to "sabotage" Brexit, and in doing so, presented himself "as the true representative of 'the people'".<ref name="Hayton_2021" /><ref name="Alexandre-Collier_2022" />

Scholars of [[comparative politics]] have drawn comparisons between Johnson and other populist leaders such as Donald Trump and [[Viktor Orban]].<ref name="Alexandre-Collier_2022" >{{cite journal |last1=Alexandre-Collier |first1=Agnès |title=David Cameron, Boris Johnson and the 'populist hypothesis' in the British Conservative Party |journal=Comparative European Politics |date=13 April 2022 |volume=20 |issue=5 |pages=527–543 |doi=10.1057/s41295-022-00294-5|s2cid=248154829 |doi-access=free }}</ref> Some commentators have likened Johnson's political style to [[Trumpism]],<ref name="Chadwick-2016">{{cite news |last=Chadwick |first=Vince |date=24 May 2016 |title=Donald Trump and Boris Johnson kiss and make Out |work=[[Politico]] |url=http://www.politico.eu/article/donald-trump-boris-johnson-kiss-mural-brexit-referendum-leave-remain/ |url-status=live |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206063613/https://www.politico.eu/article/donald-trump-boris-johnson-kiss-mural-brexit-referendum-leave-remain/ |archive-date=6 February 2021}}</ref><ref name="Greenslade-2016">{{cite news |last=Greenslade |first=Roy |author-link=Roy Greenslade |date=29 June 2016 |title=New York Post compares Boris Johnson to Donald Trump |work=The Guardian |location=London |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2016/jun/29/new-york-post-compares-boris-johnson-to-donald-trump |url-status=live |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206063615/https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2016/jun/29/new-york-post-compares-boris-johnson-to-donald-trump |archive-date=6 February 2021}}</ref><ref name="atlantic202110">{{Cite web |last=McTague |first=Tom |date=4 October 2021 |title=Is Boris Johnson a Liar? |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2021/10/boris-johnson/620269/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211019032011/https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2021/10/boris-johnson/620269/ |archive-date=19 October 2021 |access-date=18 October 2021 |website=The Atlantic}}</ref> although others have argued that Johnson's stance on matters such as social policy, immigration and free trade is liberal.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bourne |first=Ryan |date=23 July 2019 |title=Don't lump Boris Johnson together with Donald Trump |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2019/07/23/dont-lump-boris-johnson-together-with-donald-trump/ |url-status=live |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |archive-url=https://archive.today/20190723154017/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2019/07/23/dont-lump-boris-johnson-together-with-donald-trump/?noredirect=on |archive-date=23 July 2019 |access-date=5 May 2021 |url-access=limited}}</ref> Johnson biographer Gimson wrote that Johnson is economically and socially "a genuine liberal", although he retains a "Tory element" through his "love of existing institutions, and a recognition of the inevitability of hierarchy".{{sfn|Gimson|2012|p=342}} In 2019, reacting to reports in [[The Sun (United Kingdom)|''The Sun'']], that Johnson had told cabinet colleagues he was "basically a Brexity Hezza", former deputy leader of the Conservative Party [[Michael Heseltine]] wrote: "I fear that any traces of liberal conservatism that still exist within the prime minister have long since been captured by the rightwing, foreigner-bashing, inward-looking view of the world that has come to characterise his fellow Brexiters."<ref>{{cite news |last=Heseltine |first=Michael |author-link=Michael Heseltine |title=Boris Johnson has no right to call himself a one-nation Conservative |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/sep/12/boris-johnson-no-right-call-himself-one-nation-conservative |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=12 September 2019 |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220331171132/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/sep/12/boris-johnson-no-right-call-himself-one-nation-conservative |url-status=live |archive-date=31 March 2022}}</ref>

===Environment===
[[File:World Leaders' Summit Opening Ceremony (51647616433).jpg|thumb|Johnson spoke about climate action at the [[2021 United Nations Climate Change Conference|COP26 climate summit]] in Glasgow on 1 November 2021]]
Johnson expressed [[climate sceptic]]al views in several columns,<ref name="BBC News-2022">{{cite news|date=2 February 2022|title=Climate change: The science briefing that convinced Boris Johnson|work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-60203674|access-date=2 February 2022|archive-date=2 February 2022| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220202024539/https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-60203674|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="The Week UK-2021" /><ref name="Ward-2021" /> conflating the distinction between weather and climate and highlighting a factually incorrect claim by weather forecaster and conspiracy theorist [[Piers Corbyn]] that reduced solar activity could lead to a "mini-Ice Age".<ref name="newscientist"/><ref name="Ward-2021">{{cite news |last=Ward |first=Bob |title=Boris Johnson's climate change "scepticism" is an embarrassment to London's scientists |url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2013/01/boris-johnsons-climate-change-scepticism-embarrassment-londons-scientists |access-date=18 November 2021 |work=New Statesman |date=10 June 2021 |archive-date=5 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105110609/https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2013/01/boris-johnsons-climate-change-scepticism-embarrassment-londons-scientists |url-status=live}}</ref>

[[Bloomberg News]] suggested that Johnson's interest in climate change increased after becoming prime minister, and suggested this could have been influenced by his wife [[Carrie Symonds]] and father [[Stanley Johnson (writer)|Stanley Johnson]], who are both environmental campaigners.<ref name="bloomberg2">{{cite news |title=What Does Boris Johnson Really Think About Climate Change? |publisher=Bloomberg L.P. |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-05/what-does-boris-johnson-really-think-about-climate-change |date=5 February 2020 |access-date=1 January 2021 |archive-date=22 January 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210122072955/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-05/what-does-boris-johnson-really-think-about-climate-change |url-status=live}}</ref>

In 2019 and 2020 Johnson expressed support for the UK to have [[Carbon neutrality|"net-zero" greenhouse gas emissions]] by 2050<ref>{{cite news |last=Vaughan |first=Adam |date=11 June 2019 |title=UK commits to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to net zero by 2050 |journal=New Scientist |url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/2206302-uk-commits-to-reduce-greenhouse-gas-emissions-to-net-zero-by-2050/ |access-date=25 November 2020 |archive-date=26 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201126113827/https://www.newscientist.com/article/2206302-uk-commits-to-reduce-greenhouse-gas-emissions-to-net-zero-by-2050/ |url-status=live}}</ref> and spoke about increasing ambition for mitigating climate change through [[carbon capture and storage]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Gatten |first=Emma |date=24 September 2020 |title=Boris Johnson warns against 'napping' on climate change |work=The Daily Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/09/24/boris-johnson-warns-against-napping-climate-change/ |url-status=live |url-access=limited |access-date=5 May 2021 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20210120003756/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/09/24/boris-johnson-warns-against-napping-climate-change/ |archive-date=20 January 2021}}</ref> and a [[renewable energy transition]].<ref>{{cite news |date=2 November 2020 |title=Could Scotland ever be 'the Saudi Arabia of renewables'? |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-54441613 |access-date=25 November 2020 |archive-date=24 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201124205325/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-54441613 |url-status=live}}</ref> During the [[2021 United Nations Climate Change Conference]], Johnson called for greater efforts towards [[climate change mitigation]],<ref>{{cite news|date=1 November 2021|title=COP26: World at one minute to midnight over climate change – Boris Johnson|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-59114871|access-date=18 November 2021|archive-date=18 November 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211118065225/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-59114871|url-status=live}}</ref> and welcomed the prospect of [[coal phase-out]].<ref>{{cite news |date=14 November 2021 |title=COP26: Climate deal sounds the death knell for coal power – PM |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-59284505 |access-date=18 November 2021 |archive-date=17 November 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211117165044/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-59284505 |url-status=live }}</ref>

It was reported in 2022 that Johnson was convinced of the [[scientific consensus on climate change]] following a briefing by the chief scientist of the [[Met Office]] in January 2020, and subsequently made the issue a priority for his government.<ref name="BBC News-2022" />

According to [[TheyWorkForYou]] {{as of|lc=yes|2022}}, Johnson has "generally voted against" what it described as "key measures to prevent [[Climate change in the United Kingdom|climate change]]"{{clarify|reason=what does "generally voted against" mean? The website lists motions that were proposed by Labour, and look largely for political point-scoring, so of course he voted against.|date=June 2023}} while an MP,<ref>{{cite web | title=Boris Johnson MP, Uxbridge and South Ruislip | website=TheyWorkForYou | date=18 May 2022 | url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/10999/boris_johnson/uxbridge_and_south_ruislip/divisions?policy=1030 | access-date=20 May 2023}}</ref> and other sources confirm this.<ref name="newscientist">{{cite web| last=Aron| date=4 June 2019|first=Jacob|title=New prime minister Boris Johnson's climate change record|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/2205441-new-prime-minister-boris-johnsons-climate-change-record/|access-date=1 January 2021|website=[[New Scientist]]|archive-date=24 November 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201124182740/https://www.newscientist.com/article/2205441-new-prime-minister-boris-johnsons-climate-change-record/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="The Week UK-2021">{{cite web|title=What is Boris Johnson's record on climate change?|url=https://www.theweek.co.uk/105521/boris-johnson-s-record-on-climate-change|access-date=18 November 2021|website=The Week UK|date=4 February 2020 |archive-date=18 November 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211118152710/https://www.theweek.co.uk/105521/boris-johnson-s-record-on-climate-change|url-status=live}}</ref>{{update inline|date=November 2023}}

===Immigration and the European Union===
[[File:Johnson meets with Junker in Luxembourg.jpg|thumb|Johnson with EU Commission president [[Jean-Claude Juncker]], 16 September 2019]]
Purnell believed it was the influence of Johnson's maternal family that led to him developing "a genuine abhorrence of racial discrimination".{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=25}} In 2003, Johnson said, "I am not by any means an ultra-[[Euroscepticism in the United Kingdom|Eurosceptic]]. In some ways, I am a bit of a fan of the [[European Union]]. If we did not have one, we would invent something like it."<ref name="businessinsider"/> As mayor, Johnson was known as a supporter of [[Modern immigration to the United Kingdom|immigration]].<ref name="businessinsider">{{cite web |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/boris-johnson-brexit-speech-changed-his-mind-remain-2018-2 |title=All the times Boris Johnson has contradicted his own arguments for Brexit |first=Adam |last=Bienkov |website=Business Insider |access-date=26 May 2019 |date=14 February 2018 |archive-date=26 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190526224707/https://www.businessinsider.com/boris-johnson-brexit-speech-changed-his-mind-remain-2018-2 |url-status=live}}</ref> From 2009, he advocated a referendum on Britain's EU membership.<ref name="businessinsider"/><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Worthy |first1=Ben |last2=Bennister |first2=Mark |last3=Stafford |first3=Max W. |title=Rebels Leading London: the mayoralties of Ken Livingstone and Boris Johnson compared |url=http://create.canterbury.ac.uk/16760/1/16760_Rebels%20as%20Mayors%20WorthyBennisterStafford%28BP%29.pdf |url-status=live |journal=[[British Politics (journal)|British Politics]] |date=1 March 2019 |volume=14 |issue=1 |pages=23–43 |doi=10.1057/s41293-017-0069-1 |s2cid=158055383 |issn=1746-9198 |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=28 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190428224218/http://create.canterbury.ac.uk/16760/1/16760_Rebels%20as%20Mayors%20WorthyBennisterStafford%28BP%29.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-secret-pro-eu-article-revealed-expressing-doubts-brexit-a7363781.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018184759/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-secret-pro-eu-article-revealed-expressing-doubts-brexit-a7363781.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=18 October 2016 |title=A secret pro-EU article Boris Johnson wrote before the referendum has been revealed |date=15 October 2016 |website=The Independent |access-date=26 May 2019}}</ref>

In 2018, during Brexit negotiations, Johnson called for Britain to leave the [[European Single Market|Single Market]]<ref name="businessinsider"/> and advocated a more liberal approach to immigration than that of Prime Minister May.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ross |first=Tim |date=23 May 2018 |title=Boris Johnson reopens post-Brexit immigration debate |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-05-23/boris-johnson-calls-for-welcoming-approach-to-immigration |publisher=Bloomberg L.P. |access-date=5 May 2021 |url-access=subscription |archive-date=5 November 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211105000549/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-05-23/boris-johnson-calls-for-welcoming-approach-to-immigration |url-status=live }}</ref> He stated many people believed that [[United Kingdom membership of the European Union|Britain's EU membership]] had led to the suppression of British wages and said the EU was intent on creating a "superstate" that would seek to rob Britain of its sovereignty.<ref name="businessinsider"/> In 2019, Johnson said he would take Britain out of the EU on 31&nbsp;October whether there was a trade deal in place or not.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/may/26/brexit-top-tories-would-bring-down-any-pm-who-backs-no-deal |title=Brexit: top Tories would bring down any PM who backs no deal |last=Mason |first=Rowena |date=26 May 2019 |work=The Guardian |access-date=26 May 2019 |issn=0261-3077 |archive-date=26 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190526204831/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/may/26/brexit-top-tories-would-bring-down-any-pm-who-backs-no-deal |url-status=live }}</ref> Johnson also stated his opposition to a [[referendum on the Brexit withdrawal agreement]].<ref>{{cite tweet |user=borisjohnson |number=1143536757360738304 |date=25 June 2019 |title=If I become PM, we will leave the EU on 31 October, deal or no deal. Today I have asked @Jeremy_Hunt whether he will also commit to this date, no matter what. We must keep our promises to the British people and deliver Brexit – no ifs, no buts, and no second referendum.}}</ref>

On 19 August 2019, Johnson wrote a letter to the EU asking for the removal of the "backstop" accord. The president of the European Council, [[Donald Tusk]], rejected the proposal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kcbx.org/post/britains-boris-johnson-appeals-eu-drop-irish-backstop-demand#stream/0 |title=Britain's Boris Johnson Appeals To EU To Drop 'Irish Backstop' Demand |access-date=20 August 2019 |work=kcbx.org |date=20 August 2019 |archive-date=10 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210152333/https://www.kcbx.org/post/britains-boris-johnson-appeals-eu-drop-irish-backstop-demand#stream/0 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 26 August 2019, Johnson said that Britain would not pay £39&nbsp;billion for the withdrawal agreement were the UK to leave without a deal. The European Parliament Brexit coordinator [[Guy Verhofstadt]] said there would be no further negotiation unless the UK agreed to pay the entire sum.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.neweurope.eu/article/johnson-says-britain-will-not-pay-brussels-for-no-deal-brexit/ |title=Johnson says Britain will not pay Brussels for no-deal Brexit |access-date=27 August 2019 |work=New Europe |date=27 August 2019 |archive-date=28 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190828044714/https://www.neweurope.eu/article/johnson-says-britain-will-not-pay-brussels-for-no-deal-brexit/ |url-status=live}}</ref>{{Update inline|date=February 2022}}

===Unionism and devolution===
Johnson described himself as a "fervent and passionate [[Unionism in the United Kingdom|unionist]]".<ref>{{cite news |title=Boris Johnson declares unionist views on trip to Northern Ireland |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-50338539 |access-date=24 November 2020 |work=BBC News |date=7 November 2019 |archive-date=29 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201129025339/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-50338539 |url-status=live}}</ref> He proposed building an [[Irish Sea Bridge]], but he later scrapped this initiative.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-58574878.amp |title=Northern Ireland to Scotland bridge plans 'put to bed' |date=15 September 2021 |access-date=23 November 2021 |archive-date=20 November 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211120232421/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-58574878.amp |url-status=live}}</ref>

The devolved administrations have criticised the [[Internal Market Bill]] for its re-centralisation of control over commerce.<ref>{{cite web |title=Don't fall for Boris Johnson's big lie about the Internal Market Bill and its effect on devolution |first=Tommy |last=Sheppard |url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/opinion/columnists/uks-internal-market-bill-explicit-attack-scottish-devolution-tommy-sheppard-msp-2967633 |access-date=12 September 2020 |website=[[The Scotsman]] |date=10 September 2020 |archive-date=14 September 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200914081615/https://www.scotsman.com/news/opinion/columnists/uks-internal-market-bill-explicit-attack-scottish-devolution-tommy-sheppard-msp-2967633 |url-status=live}}</ref>

==Public image==
{{main|Public image of Boris Johnson}}
[[File:Boris Johnson pulling a bull in Aberdeen.jpg|alt=Boris Johnson pulling a cow.|thumb|Johnson visiting a cattle farm in [[Aberdeen]] in 2019]]Johnson has said that "humour is a utensil that you can use to sugar the pill and to get important points across".{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=3}} He is said to have a genuine desire to be liked.{{sfn|Gimson|2012|p=258}} Johnson has been described as having a light-hearted and charming persona;{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=103}}{{sfn|Crines|2013|p=1}}{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=31}}{{sfn|Gimson|2012|p=x}} many biographers and commentators suggest he has put significant effort into developing this version of himself.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=91}}{{sfn|Edwards|Isaby|2008|p=74}}{{sfnm|1a1=Edwards|1a2=Isaby|1y=2008|1p=74|2a1=Purnell|2y=2011|2p=1|3a1=Gimson|3y=2012|3p=301}}{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=3}} He has also been described as heavily focused on his own interests,{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=183}}{{sfn|Gimson|2012|p=108}}{{sfn|Gimson|2012|p=17}} with an often vitriolic or irresponsible way of conducting himself in private.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|pp=6–7}}{{sfn|Gimson|2012|p=301}}{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=37}}

Johnson has been described as a divisive, controversial figure in British politics.<ref>{{cite news |date=26 May 2019 |title=Who is Boris Johnson, the man poised to be the next British leader? |publisher=NBC News |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/who-boris-johnson-man-poised-be-next-british-leader-n1009841}}</ref><ref name="ABC3">{{cite news |last=Davies |first=Guy |date=23 July 2019 |title=Meet Boris Johnson: The UK's controversial new prime minister |website=[[ABC News (United States)|ABC News]] |url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/meet-boris-johnson-controversial-figure-uks-prime-minister/story?id=63861394 |access-date=8 May 2021}}</ref><ref name="FT">{{cite news |last=Blitz |first=James |date=23 July 2019 |title=Why is Boris Johnson such a divisive figure? |url=https://www.ft.com/content/bd03b736-ac7d-11e9-8030-530adfa879c2 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20190724054418/https://www.ft.com/content/bd03b736-ac7d-11e9-8030-530adfa879c2 |archive-date=24 July 2019 |access-date=5 May 2021 |work=[[Financial Times]]}}</ref> Supporters have praised him as witty and entertaining.{{sfn|Gimson|2012|p=20}} Johnson has been accused of lying or making misleading statements throughout his career,<ref>{{cite news |last=Grierson |first=Jamie |date=10 December 2021 |title=Lies, damned lies: the full list of accusations against Boris Johnson |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2021/dec/10/lies-accusations-boris-johnson-full-list-dishonesty-christmas-party |access-date=19 December 2021}}</ref> and has been compared to former US president [[Donald Trump]].<ref name="Chadwick-2016a">{{cite news |last=Chadwick |first=Vince |date=24 May 2016 |title=Donald Trump and Boris Johnson kiss and make Out |work=[[Politico]] |url=http://www.politico.eu/article/donald-trump-boris-johnson-kiss-mural-brexit-referendum-leave-remain/}}</ref><ref name="Greenslade-2016a">{{cite news |last=Greenslade |first=Roy |author-link=Roy Greenslade |date=29 June 2016 |title=New York Post compares Boris Johnson to Donald Trump |work=The Guardian |location=London |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2016/jun/29/new-york-post-compares-boris-johnson-to-donald-trump}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=23 March 2016 |title=London mayor Boris Johnson eyes Trump-style insurgency in EU battle |work=[[Newsweek]] |agency=Reuters |url=http://www.newsweek.com/boris-johnson-donald-trump-eu-brexit-439957}}</ref><ref name="atlantic2021102">{{Cite web |last=McTague |first=Tom |date=4 October 2021 |title=Is Boris Johnson a Liar? |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2021/10/boris-johnson/620269/ |access-date=18 October 2021 |website=The Atlantic}}</ref> He has been considered a figure with broad appeal outside of the usual Conservative support base.{{sfn|Edwards|Isaby|2008|p=47}} Johnson's premiership has been described by historians as the most controversial and scandal-affected since that of [[David Lloyd George]] about a century earlier.<ref name="Observer-historians">{{cite news |title=The most controversial PM since Lloyd George: historians on Boris Johnson |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/sep/04/the-most-controversial-pm-since-lloyd-george-historians-on-boris-johnson |access-date=4 September 2022 |work=[[The Observer]] |date=4 September 2022}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Since Johnson was born in New York City to British parents, he held [[British-American]] [[dual citizenship]]. In 2015, he agreed to pay [[capital gains tax]] to the [[Internal Revenue Service|US tax authorities]] on a property that he inherited in the UK.<ref name="telegraph-20141120">{{cite news |last=Watt |first=Holly |date=20 November 2014 |title=Boris Johnson could be hit with six-figure tax bill |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/london-mayor-election/mayor-of-london/11243742/Boris-Johnson-could-be-hit-with-six-figure-tax-bill.html |url-status=live |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |archive-url=https://archive.today/20141121131746/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/london-mayor-election/mayor-of-london/11243742/Boris-Johnson-could-be-hit-with-six-figure-tax-bill.html |archive-date=21 November 2014 |access-date=5 May 2021 |url-access=limited}}</ref><ref name="guardian-20141120">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/nov/20/boris-johnson-us-tax-bill |title=New York-born London mayor Boris Johnson refuses to pay US tax bill |last=Siddique |first=Haroon |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=20 November 2014 |access-date=21 November 2014 |archive-date=6 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206064813/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/nov/20/boris-johnson-us-tax-bill |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="bbc-20150122">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-30932891 |title=London Mayor Boris Johnson agrees to pay US tax bill |work=BBC News |date=22 January 2015 |access-date=15 February 2015 |archive-date=16 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150216123246/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-30932891 |url-status=live}}</ref> He renounced his US citizenship the following year.<ref>{{cite news |last=Shipman |first=Tim |date=15 February 2015|title=Crikey! Boris gives up White House to bid for No 10|work=[[The Times]]|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/crikey-boris-gives-up-white-house-to-bid-for-no-10-jhsxc5v2gnb|url-access=subscription|access-date=10 October 2021|issn=0140-0460|archive-date=10 October 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211010224434/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/crikey-boris-gives-up-white-house-to-bid-for-no-10-jhsxc5v2gnb|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="guardian-8–february">{{cite web |last=Wintour |first=Patrick |title=Boris Johnson among record number to renounce American citizenship in 2016 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/feb/08/boris-johnson-renounces-us-citizenship-record-2016-uk-foreign-secretary |work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=10 September 2018 |date=9 February 2017 |archive-date=22 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722082219/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/feb/08/boris-johnson-renounces-us-citizenship-record-2016-uk-foreign-secretary |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=9 February 2017 |title=Quarterly Publication of Individuals, Who Have Chosen To Expatriate, as Required by Section 6039G |url=https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2017/02/09/2017-02699/quarterly-publication-of-individuals-who-have-chosen-to-expatriate-as-required-by-section-6039g |access-date=3 July 2024 |website=Federal Register |language=en}}</ref> Johnson has knowledge of French, Italian, German, Spanish,{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=109}} [[Latin]] and [[Ancient Greek]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/reading-into-the-problem-of-illiteracy-where-street-is-often-king-1.625047 |title=Reading into the problem of illiteracy where 'Street' is often king |newspaper=The Irish Times |date=22 July 2010 |access-date=26 July 2019 |archive-date=29 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229032752/https://www.irishtimes.com/news/reading-into-the-problem-of-illiteracy-where-street-is-often-king-1.625047 |url-status=live}}</ref> frequently making [[Classics|classical]] allusions in his newspaper columns and his speeches.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=91}}

[[Sonia Purnell]] wrote in 2011 that Johnson was a "highly evasive figure" when it came to his personal life,{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=1}} who remained detached from others and who had few intimate friends.{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=15}} Among friends and family, Johnson is more commonly known as Al (short for his forename Alexander), rather than Boris.{{sfnm|1a1=Edwards|1a2=Isaby|1y=2008|1p=43|2a1=Purnell|2y=2011|2p=1|3a1=Gimson|3y=2012|3p=xiii}}

In 2007, Johnson said he had smoked [[cannabis]] before he went to university.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/1446705.boris_i_took_cocaine_and_cannabis/ |title=Boris: I took cocaine and cannabis |date=4 June 2007 |work=[[Oxford Mail]] |access-date=8 October 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181211033057/https://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/1446705.boris_i_took_cocaine_and_cannabis/ |archive-date=11 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> He has also said he had used [[cocaine]].{{sfn|Edwards|Isaby|2008|pp=144–145}} Johnson partakes in cycling, tennis and [[pilates]], and returned to road running in 2023.<ref>{{Cite web |title='Never interview here!' Boris Johnson's edict as he runs in the country |url=https://news.sky.com/video/never-interview-here-boris-johnsons-edict-as-he-runs-in-the-country-12897306 |access-date=28 October 2023 |website=Sky News |language=en}}</ref> He was considered [[obese]] in 2018 and [[overweight]] in 2020, and has spoken of making efforts to lose weight.<ref name="Mohdin-2020">{{Cite web |date=6 April 2020 |title=Hospital admission puts new focus on Boris Johnson's health |url=http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/apr/06/hospital-admission-puts-new-focus-on-boris-johnsons-health |access-date=12 April 2022 |website=The Guardian |archive-date=12 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220412223716/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/apr/06/hospital-admission-puts-new-focus-on-boris-johnsons-health |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Coronavirus: Boris Johnson says he was 'too fat' as he launches obesity crackdown |url=https://news.sky.com/story/pm-targets-checkout-sweets-and-buy-one-get-one-free-deals-in-national-obesity-plan-12037000 |access-date=12 April 2022 |publisher=Sky News |archive-date=12 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220412223713/https://news.sky.com/story/pm-targets-checkout-sweets-and-buy-one-get-one-free-deals-in-national-obesity-plan-12037000 |url-status=live }}</ref>

Johnson previously owned a £1.3&nbsp;million buy-to-let townhouse in [[Camberwell]], South London. According to [[HM Land Registry]] documents, he bought the four-bedroom property with his then-girlfriend [[Carrie Symonds]] in July 2019. The register of MPs' interests states that Johnson had a rental income of at least £10,000 a year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/boris-johnson-car-crash-townhouse-b2075095.html|title=Car crashes into garden of Boris Johnson's £1.3m south London townhouse|date=10 May 2022|website=The Independent|access-date=20 July 2022|archive-date=21 June 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220621192801/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/boris-johnson-car-crash-townhouse-b2075095.html|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2023, Johnson and Symonds bought [[Brightwell Manor]], a £3.8&nbsp;million moated mansion in [[Brightwell-cum-Sotwell]], Oxfordshire.<ref>{{Cite web |date=17 May 2023 |title=Boris and Carrie Johnson move into new £3.8m moated mansion in Oxfordshire – see inside |url=https://www.houseandgarden.co.uk/article/boris-johnson-house-mansion-oxfordshire |access-date=21 May 2023 |website=House & Garden }}</ref>

===Religion===
[[File:Boris Johnson speaks at Westminster Abbey on 2020 Commonwealth Day.jpg|thumb|Johnson speaking at [[Westminster Abbey]]'s [[Commonwealth Day]] Service, 2020]]
Johnson was baptised [[Catholic]] and later [[confirmed]] in the [[Church of England]],{{sfn|Purnell|2011|p=48}} but has said that his faith "comes and goes"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/apr/26/whowouldjesusvotefor |title=Who would Jesus vote for? |last=Sanderson |first=Terry |date=26 April 2008 |work=The Guardian |access-date=24 July 2019 |archive-date=23 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723204551/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/apr/26/whowouldjesusvotefor |url-status=live }}</ref> and that he is not a serious practising Christian.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/11378107/Boris-Johnson-I-am-not-a-serious-practicing-Christian.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/11378107/Boris-Johnson-I-am-not-a-serious-practicing-Christian.html |archive-date=10 January 2022 |url-status=live|title=Boris Johnson: I am not a serious practicing Christian |last=Swinford |first=Steven |date=29 January 2015 |work=The Telegraph |url-access=limited |access-date=5 May 2021}}{{cbignore}}</ref> In 2020 his son Wilfred was baptised Catholic.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pepinster |first=Catherine |date=26 September 2020 |title=As Boris Johnson's godmother, I'm so pleased he has returned to Catholicism |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/men/thinking-man/boris-johnsons-godmother-pleased-has-returned-catholicism/ |url-status=live |work=The Telegraph |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200926170455/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/men/thinking-man/boris-johnsons-godmother-pleased-has-returned-catholicism/ |archive-date=26 September 2020 |access-date=5 May 2021 |url-access=limited}}</ref> Johnson and Symonds married in a Catholic ceremony at [[Westminster Cathedral]] on 29&nbsp;May 2021.<ref name="BBC20210530">{{cite news|last1=Shearing|first1=Hazel|last2=Snowdon|first2=Kathryn|date=30 May 2021|title=Boris Johnson marries Carrie Symonds at Westminster Cathedral|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-57296472|work=BBC News|access-date=30 May 2021|archive-date=30 May 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210530205541/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-57296472|url-status=live}}</ref> Since he was baptised Catholic, but his previous weddings were not conferred by the Catholic Church, the Catholic Church considered them putatively invalid.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Southworth |first1=Phoebe |last2=Malnick |first2=Edward |last3=Stanley |first3=Tim |author3-link=Tim Stanley |title=Boris Johnson wedding: How did Prime Minister marry Carrie Symonds in a Catholic church? |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2021/05/29/boris-wedding-did-prime-minister-marry-carrie-symonds-catholic/ |url-status=live |url-access=subscription |work=The Telegraph |date=29 May 2021 |access-date=30 May 2021 |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2021/05/29/boris-wedding-did-prime-minister-marry-carrie-symonds-catholic/ |archive-date=10 January 2022 |issn=0307-1235}}{{cbignore}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Gledhill|first=Ruth|title=Boris weds Carrie at Westminster Cathedral|url=https://www.thetablet.co.uk/news/14185/boris-weds-carrie-at-westminster-cathedral|access-date=30 May 2021|website=[[The Tablet]]|archive-date=30 May 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210530090351/https://www.thetablet.co.uk/news/14185/boris-weds-carrie-at-westminster-cathedral|url-status=live}}</ref>

Johnson holds ancient Greek statesman [[Pericles]] as a personal hero.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/boris-johnson-could-prove-more-of-a-chancer-than-his-hero-pericles-p6x8bdl77 |title=Boris Johnson could prove more of a Chancer than his hero Pericles |last=Kidd |first=Patrick |website=The Times |date=23 July 2019 |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=31 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220331170819/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/boris-johnson-could-prove-more-of-a-chancer-than-his-hero-pericles-p6x8bdl77 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-leader-johnson-language/boris-johnsons-magniloquent-tongue-reaps-political-gold-linguists-say-idUSKCN1UI1LV |title=Boris Johnson's magniloquent tongue reaps political gold, linguists |date=23 July 2019 |work=Reuters |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=31 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220331170819/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-leader-johnson-language/boris-johnsons-magniloquent-tongue-reaps-political-gold-linguists-say-idUSKCN1UI1LV |url-status=live}}</ref> According to Johnson's biographer, Andrew Gimson, regarding ancient Greek and [[Roman polytheism]]: "it is clear that [Johnson] is inspired by the Romans, and even more by the Greeks, and repelled by the [[early Christians]]".<ref>{{cite news |date=27 July 2019 |url=https://www.economist.com/erasmus/2019/07/27/boris-johnsons-confusing-and-contradictory-religious-history |title=Boris Johnson's confusing and contradictory religious history |url-status=live |newspaper=[[The Economist]] |archive-url=https://archive.today/20190728201419/https://www.economist.com/erasmus/2019/07/27/boris-johnsons-confusing-and-contradictory-religious-history |archive-date=28 July 2019 |access-date=5 May 2021 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> Johnson views [[secular humanism]] positively and sees it as owing more to the [[classical world]] than to Christian thinking.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2019/08/what-i-learned-talking-to-boris-johnson-about-religion/ |title=What I learned talking to Boris Johnson about religion |first=Theo |last=Hobson |date=4 August 2019 |work=[[The Spectator]] |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=28 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191128111932/https://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2019/08/what-i-learned-talking-to-boris-johnson-about-religion/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In 20201 Johnson was asked if he held pre-Christian beliefs, which he denied, saying, "Christianity is a superb ethical system and I would count myself as a kind of very, very bad Christian... Christianity makes a lot of sense to me."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2021/07/boris-johnson-minister-of-chaos/619010/|title=Boris Johnson Knows Exactly What He's Doing|date=7 June 2021|first=Tom|last=McTague|website=The Atlantic|access-date=7 June 2021|archive-date=7 June 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210607045124/https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2021/07/boris-johnson-minister-of-chaos/619010/|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Relationships===
{{Sidebar | title = Children of Boris Johnson | heading1 = by [[Marina Wheeler]] | content1 = [[Lara Lettice Johnson-Wheeler]] (b. 1993)<br>Milo Arthur Johnson (b. 1995)<br>Cassia Peaches Johnson (b. 1997)<br>Theodore Apollo Johnson (b. 1999) | heading2 = by Helen Macintyre | content2 = Stephanie Macintyre (b. 2009) | heading3 = by [[Carrie Symonds]] | content3 = Wilfred Lawrie Nicholas Johnson (b. 2020)<br>Romy Iris Charlotte Johnson (b. 2021) <br> Frank Alfred Odysseus Johnson (b. 2023)| below =<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hellomagazine.com/healthandbeauty/mother-and-baby/20211213128898/boris-johnson-family-wives-and-children/|title=Boris Johnson's secret family: Prime Minister's 3 marriages and 7 children revealed|date=13 December 2021|website=HELLO!|access-date=30 July 2022|archive-date=8 July 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220708220448/https://www.hellomagazine.com/healthandbeauty/mother-and-baby/20211213128898/boris-johnson-family-wives-and-children/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://evoke.ie/2021/12/09/entertainment/boris-johnsons-children|title=What Do We Know About Boris Johnson's Seven Children?|date=9 December 2021|website=[[Evoke.ie]]|access-date=30 July 2022|archive-date=31 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220331170828/https://evoke.ie/2021/12/09/entertainment/boris-johnsons-children|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Boris and Carrie Johnson announce birth of son |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-66165003 |access-date=11 July 2023 |agency=BBC News}}</ref>}}

[[File:Boris Johnson and Carrie Symonds on 2020 Commonwealth Day.jpg|thumb|Johnson with his then-fiancée [[Carrie Symonds]] at the 2020 [[Commonwealth Day]] service]]

In 1987, Johnson married [[Allegra Mostyn-Owen]], daughter of the art historian [[William Mostyn-Owen]] and Italian writer [[Gaia Servadio]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Rachel |last=Helyer-Donaldson |url=http://www.theweek.co.uk/entertainment/17457/boris-johnson%E2%80%99s-first-wife-marries-again |title=Boris Johnson's first wife marries again |work=The Week |location=London |access-date=4 May 2017 |archive-date=17 May 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160517103328/http://www.theweek.co.uk/entertainment/17457/boris-johnson%E2%80%99s-first-wife-marries-again |url-status=live}}</ref> The couple's marriage ended in divorce or [[annulment]] in 1993{{efn|Sources differ on whether the marriage ended in divorce<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Sampson|first=Annabel|date=11 November 2019|title=Who is Boris Johnson's first wife, former Tatler cover girl Allegra Mostyn-Owen?|url=https://www.tatler.com/article/who-is-boris-johnsons-first-wife-allegra-mostyn-owen|magazine=Tatler|access-date=29 May 2021|archive-date=14 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210414111313/https://www.tatler.com/article/who-is-boris-johnsons-first-wife-allegra-mostyn-owen|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=McDonaugh|first=Melanie|date=29 May 2012|title='He's a better ex than he was a husband', says Boris Johnson's ex wife|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/he-s-a-better-ex-than-he-was-a-husband-says-boris-johnson-s-ex-wife-7800543.html|work=Evening Standard|access-date=29 May 2021|archive-date=27 May 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210527075103/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/he-s-a-better-ex-than-he-was-a-husband-says-boris-johnson-s-ex-wife-7800543.html|url-status=live}}</ref> or with an annulment.<ref name=guardian200218>{{cite news |last=Press Association |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/feb/18/boris-johnson-agrees-divorce-settlement-with-marina-wheeler |title=Boris Johnson agrees divorce settlement with Marina Wheeler |work=The Guardian |date=18 February 2020 |access-date=29 May 2021 |location=London |archive-date=29 May 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210529120739/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/feb/18/boris-johnson-agrees-divorce-settlement-with-marina-wheeler |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":1b">{{cite news |last1=Malnick |first1=Edward |last2=Stanley |first2=Tim |last3=Southworth |first3=Phoebe |title=Boris Johnson and Carrie Symonds married in secret wedding ceremony at Westminster Cathedral|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2021/05/29/boris-johnson-carrie-symonds-married-catholic-westminster-cathedral/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2021/05/29/boris-johnson-carrie-symonds-married-catholic-westminster-cathedral/ |archive-date=10 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=30 May 2021|access-date=30 May 2021}}{{cbignore}}</ref><!--See Talk:Boris Johnson/Archive 5#First marriage ended in annulment, not divorce.-->}} and 12 days later Johnson married [[Marina Wheeler]], a barrister, daughter of journalist <!-- Not knighted until 2006. -->[[Charles Wheeler (journalist)|Charles Wheeler]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Doward |first=Jamie |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2004/aug/29/comment.jamiedoward |title=No dumb blond |work=The Observer |date=29 August 2004 |access-date=7 July 2010 |location=London |archive-date=8 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108212634/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2004/aug/29/comment.jamiedoward |url-status=live}}</ref> Five weeks later, their first child was born.<ref name=marriagedateperIndy>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/marina-wheeler-profile-the-brains-behind-boris-johnson-a6871006.html |title=Marina Wheeler, profile: The brains behind Boris Johnson |date=13 February 2016 |first=Andy |last=McSmith |work=The Independent |location=London |access-date=7 September 2018 |archive-date=31 July 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200731231832/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/marina-wheeler-profile-the-brains-behind-boris-johnson-a6871006.html |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080413020741/http://www.backboris.com/news/april/Boris_celebrates_Vaisakhi_in_Southall.php |archive-date=13 April 2008 |url=http://www.backboris.com/news/april/Boris_celebrates_Vaisakhi_in_Southall.php |title=Boris celebrates Vaisakhi in Southall |publisher=BackBoris.com |date=6 April 2008 |access-date=3 May 2008}}</ref> They have four children: [[Lara Johnson-Wheeler|Lara Lettice]], Milo Arthur, Cassia Peaches and Theodore Apollo.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7376621.stm |title=The Boris Johnson story |work=BBC News |date=4 May 2008 |access-date=1 August 2021 |first=Brian |last=Wheeler |archive-date=6 May 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080506144031/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7376621.stm |url-status=live}}</ref>

Between 2000 and 2004, Johnson had an affair with ''Spectator'' columnist [[Petronella Wyatt]] when he was its editor, resulting in a terminated pregnancy and a [[miscarriage]].{{sfnm|1a1=Edwards|1a2=Isaby|1y=2008|1p=47|2a1=Purnell|2y=2011|2pp=257–263|3a1=Gimson|3y=2012|3pp=162–173, 209–218}} In April 2006, the ''[[News of the World]]'' alleged that Johnson was having an affair with ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]]'' journalist Anna Fazackerley. The pair did not comment; shortly afterward, Johnson employed Fazackerley.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1pp=296–300|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2pp=255–257}}<ref name="Barber-2008" />

In 2009, Johnson fathered a daughter with Helen Macintyre, an arts consultant.<ref name="Telegraph210513" /><ref name=Guardian130521>{{cite news |last=Halliday |first=Josh |title=Public has right to know Boris Johnson fathered child during affair, court rules |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/may/21/boris-johnson-fathered-child-affair |access-date=21 September 2021 |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=21 May 2013 |archive-date=6 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206063726/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/may/21/boris-johnson-fathered-child-affair |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Pitel |first=Laura |title='Boris lovechild' can be public knowledge, appeal court rules |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/law/article3771437.ece |access-date=7 May 2016 |work=The Times |date=22 May 2013 |location=London |url-access=subscription |archive-date=7 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170207080311/http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/law/article3771437.ece |url-status=live}}</ref> In September 2021 Johnson stated that he had six children, thereby denying the existence of further illegitimate children.<ref name=Guardian210921>{{cite web |last=Stewart |first=Helen |date=21 September 2021 |title=Boris Johnson admits he has six children |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2021/sep/21/boris-johnson-admits-he-has-six-children |website=The Guardian |access-date=22 September 2021 |archive-date=21 September 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210921222937/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2021/sep/21/boris-johnson-admits-he-has-six-children |url-status=live}}</ref>

In September 2018, Johnson and Wheeler issued a statement confirming that they had separated months earlier;<ref name="bbc-7–september">{{cite news |title=Boris Johnson and wife to divorce |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-45446254 |work=BBC News |access-date=10 September 2018 |date=7 September 2018 |archive-date=17 January 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210117165946/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-45446254 |url-status=live}}</ref> they divorced in 2020.<ref>{{cite news |date=8 May 2020 |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/uk/uk-pm-johnsons-divorce-with-indian-origin-wife-finalised/articleshow/75615513.cms |title=UK PM Johnson's divorce with Indian-origin wife finalised |work=The Times of India |access-date=9 October 2023}}</ref>

[[Jennifer Arcuri]] said that she had an affair with Johnson from 2012 to 2016.<ref>{{cite news |last=McKelvie |first=Geraldine |title=Jennifer Arcuri: Why I've decided to speak my truth about Boris Johnson |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/jennifer-arcuri-ive-decided-speak-23809260 |access-date=28 March 2021 |work=[[Sunday Mirror]] |date=28 March 2021 |archive-date=28 March 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210328110258/https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/jennifer-arcuri-ive-decided-speak-23809260 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Sommerlad |first=Joe |title=Jennifer Arcuri tells of 'four-year affair' with Boris Johnson and calls him 'cowardly' |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-jennifer-arcuri-affair-b1823529.html |access-date=28 March 2021 |work=The Independent |date=28 March 2021 |archive-date=28 March 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210328103829/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-jennifer-arcuri-affair-b1823529.html |url-status=live}}</ref>

In 2019, Johnson was living with [[Carrie Symonds]], the daughter of [[Matthew Symonds]], co-founder of ''[[The Independent]]'' newspaper.<ref name="ITV 22 June 2019">{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2019-06-22/carrie-symonds-who-is-boris-johnsons-partner/|title=Carrie Symonds: Who is Boris Johnson's partner?|website=itv.com|date=22 June 2019|access-date=24 June 2019|archive-date=29 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729012117/https://www.itv.com/news/2019-06-22/carrie-symonds-who-is-boris-johnsons-partner/|url-status=live}}</ref> Johnson and Symonds became engaged in late 2019<ref name="BBC51691434">{{cite news |title=PM Johnson and Symonds engaged and expecting baby |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51691434 |access-date=29 February 2020 |work=BBC News |date=29 February 2020 |archive-date=5 May 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200505075431/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51691434 |url-status=live }}</ref> and their son, Wilfred Lawrie Nicholas Johnson,<ref>{{cite news|last=Braddick|first=Imogen|title=Boris Johnson and Carrie Symonds name baby boy Wilfred Lawrie Nicholas Johnson after doctors who saved PM's life|date=2 May 2020|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/boris-johnson-carrie-symonds-baby-wilfred-a4430206.html|work=Evening Standard|location=London|access-date=2 May 2020|archive-date=2 August 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200802050835/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/boris-johnson-carrie-symonds-baby-wilfred-a4430206.html|url-status=live}}</ref> was born in April 2020.<ref name=Guardian200429>{{cite news|last=Proctor|first=Kate|title=Boris Johnson and Carrie Symonds announce birth of baby boy|date=29 April 2020|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/apr/29/boris-johnson-and-carrie-symonds-announce-birth-of-baby-boy|work=The Guardian|access-date=21 September 2021|archive-date=31 July 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210731153454/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/apr/29/boris-johnson-and-carrie-symonds-announce-birth-of-baby-boy|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-52469079|title=Boris Johnson and Carrie Symonds announce birth of son|work=BBC News|date=29 April 2020|access-date=29 April 2020|archive-date=1 May 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200501151755/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-52469079|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 29 May 2021 Johnson married Symonds at [[Westminster Cathedral]].<ref name="BBC20210530" /><ref>{{cite news|last=Beech|first=Samantha|date=30 May 2021|title=Boris Johnson marries Carrie Symonds in secret wedding|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2021/05/29/world/boris-johnson-marries-carrie-symonds-intl/index.html|publisher=CNN|access-date=1 June 2021|archive-date=31 May 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210531235846/https://edition.cnn.com/2021/05/29/world/boris-johnson-marries-carrie-symonds-intl/index.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Their daughter, Romy Iris Charlotte Johnson,<ref>{{cite news|title=Boris and Carrie Johnson announce name of new daughter|date=16 December 2021|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-59686354|work=BBC News|location=London|access-date=16 December 2021|archive-date=16 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211216132536/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-59686354|url-status=live}}</ref> was born in December 2021.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Boris Johnson's wife Carrie gives birth to second child|url=https://news.sky.com/story/boris-johnsons-wife-carrie-gives-birth-to-second-child-12490631|date=9 December 2021|access-date=11 December 2021|work=Sky News|archive-date=9 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211209221022/https://news.sky.com/story/boris-johnsons-wife-carrie-gives-birth-to-second-child-12490631|url-status=live}}</ref> Their third child, a son named Frank Alfred Odysseus Johnson, was born in July 2023.<ref>{{cite news |title=Boris and Carrie Johnson announce birth of son |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-66165003 |date=11 July 2023 |access-date=11 July 2023 |work=BBC News}}</ref>

===Family and ancestors===
[[File:Boris Johnson Leo Johnson.jpg|thumb|Johnson and his younger brother Leo in 2013]]
Johnson is the eldest of the four children of [[Stanley Johnson (writer)|Stanley Johnson]], a former [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[member of the European Parliament]], and the painter [[Charlotte Johnson Wahl]] (née Fawcett),<ref name="telegraph.co.uk" /> the daughter of Sir [[James Fawcett]], president of the [[European Commission of Human Rights]].<ref>Clapham, Andrew (1993). "Human Rights in the Private Sphere". [[OUP]]. p. 186.</ref> His younger siblings are [[Rachel Johnson]], a writer and journalist, Leo Johnson, a broadcaster,<ref>{{cite news |date=15 July 2018 |title=Has Leo Johnson, Boris' younger brother, found the key to happiness? |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/men/thinking-man/happiness-johnson-genes/ |work=The Telegraph |access-date=15 June 2023}}</ref> and [[Jo Johnson]], ex-minister of state and former Conservative MP for [[Orpington (UK Parliament constituency)|Orpington]], who resigned from his brother's government in September 2019<ref name="bbc2"/> and is now a member of the [[House of Lords]]. Johnson's stepmother, Jenny, the second wife of his father Stanley, is the stepdaughter of [[Teddy Sieff]], the former chairman of [[Marks & Spencer]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2008/may/14/5 |title=People |last=Bates |first=Stephen |work=The Guardian |date=14 May 2008 |location=London |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=6 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206063701/https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2008/may/14/5 |url-status=live }}</ref> Having been a member of the Conservatives between 2008 and 2011, Rachel Johnson joined the Liberal Democrats in 2017.<ref>{{cite news |last=Martinson |first=Jane |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2017/apr/27/rachel-johnson-joins-lib-dems-and-may-stand-in-general-election-member-tory-brexit |title=Rachel Johnson joins Lib Dems in protest against Tory backing for Brexit |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=27 April 2017 |access-date=27 April 2017 |archive-date=27 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427170559/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2017/apr/27/rachel-johnson-joins-lib-dems-and-may-stand-in-general-election-member-tory-brexit |url-status=live }}</ref> She stood as a candidate for [[Change UK]] in the [[2019 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2019 European Elections]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/apr/23/change-uk-independent-group-launches-european-election-campaign-brexit/ |title=Rachel Johnson and Gavin Esler to stand for Change UK |date=23 April 2019 |access-date=23 April 2019 |archive-date=23 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423113559/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/apr/23/change-uk-independent-group-launches-european-election-campaign-brexit |url-status=live }}/</ref> Johnson also has two half-siblings, [[Julia Johnson|Julia]] and Maximilian, through his father's later marriage to Jennifer Kidd.<ref>{{cite news |last=Walden |first=Celia |author-link=Celia Walden |date=11 April 2008 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/features/3636228/Stanley-Johnson-The-man-who-made-Boris.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/features/3636228/Stanley-Johnson-The-man-who-made-Boris.html |archive-date=10 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |title=Stanley Johnson: The man who made Boris |work=The Daily Telegraph |access-date=5 July 2016}}{{cbignore}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Killen |first=Mary |date=March 2015 |title=Boris Johnson's mother on her brilliant brood |url=http://www.tatler.com/article/boris-johnson-family-charlotte-johnson-wahl |work=[[Tatler]] |access-date=19 January 2018 |archive-date=19 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180119120328/http://www.tatler.com/article/boris-johnson-family-charlotte-johnson-wahl |url-status=live }}</ref>

Johnson's paternal grandfather, Wilfred Johnson, was an RAF pilot in [[Coastal Command]] during the Second World War.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bird |first=Steve |date=2 May 2020 |title=The story of Wilfred Johnson, the decorated WW2 pilot who has given his name to the Prime Minister's son |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/05/02/story-wilfred-johnson-decorated-ww2-pilot-has-given-name-prime/ |url-status=live |work=The Daily Telegraph |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200724203449/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/05/02/story-wilfred-johnson-decorated-ww2-pilot-has-given-name-prime/ |archive-date=24 July 2020 |access-date=5 May 2021 |url-access=limited}}</ref> Wilfred Johnson's father was the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] [[Ministry of the Interior (Ottoman Empire)|Interior Minister]] and journalist [[Ali Kemal]]. Ali Kemal's father was a [[Turkish people|Turk]] while his mother was a [[Circassians|Circassian]] reputedly of [[Circassian beauties|slave]] origin.{{sfnm|1a1=Edwards|1a2=Isaby|1y=2008|1p=44|2a1=Purnell|2y=2011|2pp=19–20|3a1=Gimson|3y=2012|3pp=5–7, 1957}}<ref>{{cite news |last=Acar |first=Özgen |date=20 June 2008 |title=Bir Baba Ocağı Ziyareti |trans-title=A Visit to Family Home |url=http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/bir-baba-ocagi-ziyareti-9229598 |language=tr |work=[[Hürriyet Daily News]] |location=Istanbul |access-date=19 July 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160510180507/http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/bir-baba-ocagi-ziyareti-9229598|archive-date=10 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Gökçe |first=Deniz |date=25 April 2016 |title=Obama ile Boris Johnson Kapıştı |trans-title=Obama versus Boris Johnson |url=http://www.aksam.com.tr/yazarlar/obama-ile-boris-johnson-kapisti/haber-510362 |language=tr |work=[[Akşam]] |location=Istanbul |access-date=19 July 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160501103823/http://www.aksam.com.tr/yazarlar/obama-ile-boris-johnson-kapisti/haber-510362 |archive-date=1 May 2016}}</ref> His other paternal ancestry includes English, German and French; one of his German ancestors was said to be the [[illegitimate]] daughter of [[Prince Paul of Württemberg]] and thus a descendant of [[George&nbsp;II of Great Britain]],{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1p=21|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=10}} which was later confirmed on an episode of ''[[Who Do You Think You Are? (British TV series)|Who Do You Think You Are?]]''<ref>{{Cite video |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1rJ2fHblikE |title=Boris Finds Out He's Related To King George II {{!}} Who Do You Think You Are |date=4 October 2018 |publisher=BBC |via=YouTube}}</ref>

Johnson's mother is the granddaughter of [[Elias Avery Lowe]], a [[palaeographer]] and a [[Russian Jewish]] immigrant to the US,<ref name="thejc1">{{cite journal|url=http://website.thejc.com/home.aspx?AId=55194&ATypeId=1&search=true2&srchstr=elias%20avery&srchtxt=0&srchhead=1&srchauthor=0&srchsandp=0&scsrch=0|title=Interview: Boris Johnson – my Jewish credentials|journal=[[The Jewish Chronicle]]|last=Peled|first=Daniella|year=2008|issue=April|access-date=19 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917061635/http://website.thejc.com/home.aspx?AId=55194&ATypeId=1&search=true2&srchstr=elias%20avery&srchtxt=0&srchhead=1&srchauthor=0&srchsandp=0&scsrch=0|archive-date=17 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Pennsylvania]]-born [[Helen Tracy Lowe-Porter]], a translator of [[Thomas Mann]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/boris-johnsons-sister-on-his-kibbutz-past-1.5421852 |title=Boris Johnson's Sister Reveals His Little-known Past as a Volunteer on an Israeli Kibbutz |date=8 August 2016 |work=[[Haaretz]] |access-date=30 June 2019 |archive-date=30 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190630001511/https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/boris-johnsons-sister-on-his-kibbutz-past-1.5421852 |url-status=live }}</ref> Referring to his varied ancestry, Johnson has described himself as a "one-man melting pot".<ref>{{cite news |author=Woodward, Will |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2007/jul/17/localgovernment.london |title=Phooey! One-man melting pot ready to take on King Newt |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=17 July 2007 |access-date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=15 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715151132/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2007/jul/17/localgovernment.london |url-status=live}}</ref> Johnson was given the middle name "[[Boris (given name)|Boris]]" after a [[White Russian]] émigré named Boris Litwin, who was a friend of his parents.{{sfnm|1a1=Purnell|1y=2011|1p=11|2a1=Gimson|2y=2012|2p=2}}

==Honours==
[[File:Freedom order.jpg|thumb|upright|Order of Liberty]]
* Honorary degree of [[Doctor of Laws]] (LLD) from [[Brunel University London]], 2007<ref>{{cite web|title=Honorary Graduates|url=https://www.brunel.ac.uk/about/people/Honorary-graduates|publisher=Brunel University London|access-date=6 October 2019|archive-date=20 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181120221308/https://www.brunel.ac.uk/about/people/Honorary-graduates|url-status=live}}</ref>
